WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.040
- The following is a conversation all
about the state-of-the-art in artificial

00:00:04.059 --> 00:00:07.790
intelligence, including some of the
exciting technical breakthroughs and

00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:11.580
developments in AI that happened
over the past year, and

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:15.480
some of the interesting things we
think might happen this upcoming

00:00:15.560 --> 00:00:19.440
year. At times, it does
get super technical,

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:23.420
but we do try to make sure that
it remains accessible to folks

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:27.240
outside the field without
ever dumbing it down. It

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:31.000
is a great honor and pleasure
to be able to do this kind of

00:00:31.060 --> 00:00:34.220
episode with two of my
favorite people in the AI

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:37.820
community, Sebastian Raschka and Nathan

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:41.900
Lambert. They are both
widely respected machine

00:00:41.940 --> 00:00:45.710
learning researchers and engineers
who also happen to be great

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:49.720
communicators, educators,
writers, and X posters.

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:53.120
Sebastian is the author of two books

00:00:53.860 --> 00:00:57.589
I highly recommend for beginners
and experts alike. First is

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:00.860
Build a Large Language Model from Scratch

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:05.400
and Build a Reasoning
Model from Scratch. I

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:09.340
truly believe in the
machine learning world, the

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:12.680
best way to learn and understand
something is to build it

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:16.990
yourself from scratch. Nathan is

00:01:17.020 --> 00:01:20.900
the post-training lead at
the Allen Institute for AI,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.860
author of the definitive book on
Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback.

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:30.040
Both of them have great X
accounts, great Substacks.

00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:34.020
Sebastian has courses on
YouTube, Nathan has a podcast.

00:01:34.060 --> 00:01:37.780
And everyone should absolutely
follow all of those.

00:01:37.840 --> 00:01:41.680
those. This is the Lex Fridman
podcast. To support it, please

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:45.580
check out our sponsors in the
description, where you can also find

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:49.400
links to contact me, ask
questions, get feedback, and so

00:01:49.540 --> 00:01:56.170
on. And now, dear friends, here's
Sebastian Raschka and Nathan Lambert.

00:01:57.220 --> 00:02:01.170
So I think one useful lens to
look at all this through is

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:05.160
the so-called DeepSeek
moment. This happened about

00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:09.139
a year ago in January 2025,
when the open-weight Chinese

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:13.000
company DeepSeek released
DeepSeek R1, that I

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:16.840
think it's fair to say surprised
everyone with near-state-of-the-art

00:02:16.940 --> 00:02:24.780
performance, with allegedly much less
compute for much cheaper. And from then

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:28.600
to today, the AI competition
has gotten insane,

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:32.420
both on the research and product
level. It's just been accelerating.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:36.360
discuss all of this today, and
maybe let's start with some spicy

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:37.920
questions if we can.

00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:42.820
Who's winning at the international
level? Would you say it's the set

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:46.590
of companies in China or the set
of companies in the United States?

00:02:46.700 --> 00:02:50.200
And Sebastian, Nathan,
it's good to see you guys.

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:53.360
guys. So Sebastian, who
do you think is winning?

00:02:53.420 --> 00:02:57.220
- Winning is a very broad term.

00:02:57.260 --> 00:03:01.240
I would say you mentioned the DeepSeek
moment, and I think DeepSeek is winning

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:05.200
the hearts of the people who work on
open-weight models because they share

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:09.140
these as open models. Winning,
I think, has multiple

00:03:09.180 --> 00:03:12.860
timescales to it. We have today,
we have next year, we have in 10

00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:16.740
years. One thing I know
for sure is that I don't

00:03:16.780 --> 00:03:20.420
think nowadays, in 2026,
that there will be any

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:24.370
company that has access to
technology that no other

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:28.420
company has access to. That
is mainly because researchers

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:32.010
are frequently changing jobs and labs.

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:36.080
They rotate. I don't think there
will be a clear winner in terms of

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:39.750
technology access. However,
I do think there will be,

00:03:39.860 --> 00:03:43.540
The differentiating factor will be
budget and hardware constraints.

00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:46.940
I don't think the ideas
will be proprietary,

00:03:46.980 --> 00:03:53.900
but rather the resources needed
to implement them. I don't see

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:58.980
currently a winner-take-all scenario.
I can't see that. At the moment.

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:00.700
- Nathan, what do you think?

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:04.670
- You see the labs put different energy
into what they're trying to do, and

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:08.640
I think to demarcate the point in time
when we're recording this, the hype

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:11.960
over Anthropic's Claude
Opus 4.5 model has been

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:15.860
absolutely insane, which is just...
I mean, I've used it and built stuff

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:20.040
in the last few weeks, and it's... it's almost
gotten to the point where it feels like a bit of

00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:21.880
a meme in terms of the hype. And it's

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:26.580
kind of funny because this is very organic,
and then if we go back a few months

00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:30.500
ago, we can see the release date and
the notes, as Gemini 3 from Google got

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:32.520
released, and it seemed like the

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:36.860
marketing and just, like, wow
factor of that release was super

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:40.810
high. But then at the end of November,
Claude Opus 4.5 was released and

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:44.720
the hype has been growing, but Gemini 3
was before this. And it kind of feels

00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:48.540
like people don't really talk about it as much, even
though when it came out, everybody was like, this

00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:52.540
is Gemini's moment to retake Google's

00:04:52.550 --> 00:04:56.480
structural advantages in AI. And Gemini 3
is a fantastic model, and I still use it.

00:04:56.500 --> 00:05:00.440
It's just kind of
differentiation is lower. And I

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:04.360
agree with Sebastian; what you're saying
with all these, the idea space is

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:08.600
very fluid, but culturally
Anthropic is known for betting very

00:05:08.660 --> 00:05:12.560
hard on code, which is the Claude Code thing,
is working out for them right now. So I

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:16.560
think that even if the ideas flow
pretty freely, so much of this is

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:20.580
bottlenecked by human effort and the
culture of organizations, where Anthropic

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:24.520
seems to at least be presenting
as the least chaotic. It's a

00:05:24.540 --> 00:05:28.330
bit of an advantage, if they can keep
doing that for a while. But on the other

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:32.020
side of things, there's a lot of
ominous technology from China where

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:35.940
there's way more labs than
DeepSeek. So DeepSeek kicked off

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:39.720
a movement within China, I
say kind of similar to how

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:43.740
ChatGPT kicked off a movement in the US
where everything had a chatbot. There's now

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:48.410
tons of tech companies in China that are
releasing very strong frontier open-weight

00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:52.340
models, to the point where I would say that
DeepSeek is kind of losing its crown as the

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:56.290
preeminent open model maker
in China, and the likes of

00:05:56.360 --> 00:06:00.200
Z.ai with their GLM
models, Minimax's models,

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:04.240
Kimi Moonshot, especially in the
last few months, has shown more

00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:08.060
brightly. The new DeepSeek models are
still very strong, but that's kind of

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:11.760
a... it could look back as a big
narrative point where in 2025

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:15.760
DeepSeek came and it provided this
platform for way more Chinese

00:06:15.780 --> 00:06:19.260
companies that are releasing these
fantastic models to kind of have this new

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:23.480
type of operation. So these models from these
Chinese companies are open-weights, and

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:27.520
depending on this trajectory of business
models that these American companies are

00:06:27.560 --> 00:06:31.512
doing, they could be at risk. But
currently, a lot of people are paying

00:06:31.532 --> 00:06:35.332
for AI software in the US, and
historically in China and other

00:06:35.352 --> 00:06:37.852
parts of the world, people
don't pay a lot for software.

00:06:37.992 --> 00:06:41.872
- So some of these models like DeepSeek
have the love of the people because

00:06:41.912 --> 00:06:45.732
they are open-weight. How long do
you think the Chinese companies keep

00:06:45.752 --> 00:06:47.712
releasing open-weight models?

00:06:47.752 --> 00:06:51.692
- I would say for a few years. I think
that, like in the US, there's not a

00:06:51.732 --> 00:06:55.692
clear business model for it. I have been
writing about open models for a while,

00:06:55.712 --> 00:06:59.112
and these Chinese companies have realized
it. So I get inbound from some of them.

00:06:59.132 --> 00:07:02.792
And they're smart and realize the same
constraints: a lot of top US tech

00:07:02.832 --> 00:07:06.772
companies and other IT companies
won't pay for an API subscription to

00:07:07.192 --> 00:07:10.801
Chinese companies for security
concerns. This has been a long-standing

00:07:10.912 --> 00:07:14.892
habit in tech, and the people at
these companies then see open

00:07:14.932 --> 00:07:18.752
weight models as an ability to influence
and take part of a huge growing

00:07:18.972 --> 00:07:22.512
AI expenditure market in the US. And
they're very realistic about this,

00:07:23.092 --> 00:07:26.752
and it's working for them. I think that
the government will see that that is

00:07:27.572 --> 00:07:31.212
building a lot of influence internationally
in terms of uptake of the technology,

00:07:31.272 --> 00:07:35.072
so there's going to be a lot of
incentives to keep it going. But building

00:07:35.132 --> 00:07:38.992
these models and doing the research is
very expensive, so at some point, I expect

00:07:39.672 --> 00:07:43.472
consolidation. But I don't expect that to
be a story of 2026, where there will be

00:07:44.392 --> 00:07:48.212
more open model builders throughout
2026 than there were in 2025. And a

00:07:48.272 --> 00:07:50.372
lot of the notable ones will be in China.

00:07:50.432 --> 00:07:51.312
- You were going to say something?

00:07:51.372 --> 00:07:57.632
- Yes. You mentioned DeepSeek losing its
crown. I do think to some extent, yes, but

00:07:58.552 --> 00:08:02.492
we also have to consider though, they are
still, I would say, slightly ahead. And

00:08:02.552 --> 00:08:06.272
the other ones—it's not that DeepSeek
got worse, it's just that the other ones

00:08:06.432 --> 00:08:10.192
are using the ideas from DeepSeek.
For example, you mentioned Kimi—same

00:08:10.232 --> 00:08:13.532
architecture, they're training it. And
then again, we have this leapfrogging

00:08:13.692 --> 00:08:17.372
where they might be at some point in time a
bit better because they have the more recent

00:08:17.412 --> 00:08:21.392
model. And I think this comes back
to the fact that there won't be

00:08:21.512 --> 00:08:25.472
a clear winner. It will just be
like that: one person releases

00:08:25.532 --> 00:08:29.512
something, the other one comes in, and the
most recent model is probably always the

00:08:29.552 --> 00:08:30.012
best model.

00:08:30.052 --> 00:08:33.672
- Yeah. We'll also see the Chinese companies
have different incentives. Like,

00:08:33.892 --> 00:08:37.672
DeepSeek is very secretive,
whereas some of these startups are

00:08:37.792 --> 00:08:41.552
like the MiniMaxs and Z.ais of the
world. Those two literally have filed

00:08:41.991 --> 00:08:45.592
IPO paperwork, and they're
trying to get Western

00:08:45.712 --> 00:08:49.512
mindshare and do a lot of outreach there. So I
don't know if these incentives will change the

00:08:49.552 --> 00:08:53.182
model development, because DeepSeek
famously is built by a hedge fund,

00:08:53.182 --> 00:08:57.112
Highflyer Capital, and we don't
know exactly what they use the

00:08:57.172 --> 00:08:58.892
models for or if they care about this.

00:08:59.252 --> 00:09:03.132
- They're secretive in terms of communication; they're
not secretive in terms of the technical reports that

00:09:03.152 --> 00:09:06.812
describe how their models work. They're
still open on that front. And we should also

00:09:06.872 --> 00:09:12.732
say, on the Claude Opus 4.5 hype,
there's the layer of something

00:09:13.952 --> 00:09:17.892
being the darling of the
X echo chamber, on the

00:09:18.072 --> 00:09:22.052
Twitter echo chamber, and the actual
amount of people that are using the

00:09:22.092 --> 00:09:25.532
model. I think it's probably
fair to say that ChatGPT and

00:09:25.592 --> 00:09:29.501
Gemini are focused on the
broad user base that just

00:09:29.552 --> 00:09:33.392
want to solve problems in their
daily lives, and that user base

00:09:33.432 --> 00:09:37.192
is gigantic. So the hype
about the coding may not be

00:09:37.232 --> 00:09:38.892
representative of the actual use.

00:09:38.992 --> 00:09:42.852
- I would say also a lot of
the usage patterns are,

00:09:43.052 --> 00:09:46.892
like you said, name recognition,
brand and stuff, but also

00:09:47.032 --> 00:09:50.852
muscle memory almost, where, you
know, ChatGPT has been around

00:09:50.952 --> 00:09:54.932
for a long time. People just got used to
using it, and it's almost like a flywheel:

00:09:54.972 --> 00:09:58.792
they recommend it to other users and that
stuff. One interesting point is also

00:09:58.852 --> 00:10:02.752
the customization of LLMs.
For example, ChatGPT has a

00:10:02.772 --> 00:10:06.752
memory feature, right? And so you
may have a subscription and you

00:10:06.952 --> 00:10:10.492
use it for personal stuff, but I don't know
if you want to use that same thing at work.

00:10:10.512 --> 00:10:14.412
Because it's a boundary between private and work.
If you're working at a company, they might not

00:10:14.452 --> 00:10:18.432
allow that or you may not want that. And
I think that's also an interesting point

00:10:18.492 --> 00:10:22.232
where you might have multiple
subscriptions. One is just clean code.

00:10:22.272 --> 00:10:26.152
It has nothing of your
personal images or hobby

00:10:26.192 --> 00:10:30.132
projects in there. It's just like the work thing.
And then the other one is your personal thing.

00:10:30.172 --> 00:10:33.792
So I think that's also something where there are
two different use cases, and it doesn't mean

00:10:34.152 --> 00:10:38.712
you only have to have one. I think
the future is also multiple ones.

00:10:38.772 --> 00:10:43.512
- What model do you think won 2025, and what
model do you think is going to win '26?

00:10:43.572 --> 00:10:47.332
- I think in the context of consumer chatbots,
it's a question of: are you willing to

00:10:47.412 --> 00:10:50.452
bet on Gemini over ChatGPT?

00:10:50.462 --> 00:10:54.432
Which I would say, in my gut,
feels like a bit of a risky bet

00:10:54.512 --> 00:10:58.432
because OpenAI has been the incumbent, and
there are so many benefits to that in tech.

00:10:58.492 --> 00:11:00.432
I think the

00:11:01.392 --> 00:11:05.322
momentum, if you look at 2025, was on
Gemini's side, but they were starting from

00:11:05.352 --> 00:11:12.362
such a low point. And RIP Bard and these
earlier attempts at getting started.

00:11:13.112 --> 00:11:16.972
Huge credit to them for powering through the
organizational chaos to make that happen.

00:11:17.032 --> 00:11:22.022
But also it's hard to bet against
OpenAI because they always come off as

00:11:22.892 --> 00:11:26.712
so chaotic, but they're very good
at landing things. And I think,

00:11:26.812 --> 00:11:30.771
personally, I have very mixed
reviews of GPT-5, but it must have

00:11:30.812 --> 00:11:34.572
saved them so much money with the
high-line feature being a router where

00:11:34.612 --> 00:11:38.392
most users are no longer charging
their GPU costs as much.

00:11:38.432 --> 00:11:42.232
So I think it's very hard to dissociate

00:11:42.692 --> 00:11:45.592
the things that I like out of models
versus the things that are going to

00:11:45.672 --> 00:11:50.282
actually be a general
public differentiator.

00:11:50.312 --> 00:11:52.852
- What do you think about
2026? Who's going to win?

00:11:52.892 --> 00:11:56.792
- I'll say something, even though it's risky. I think
Gemini will continue to make progress on ChatGPT.

00:11:56.832 --> 00:11:59.802
I think Google's scale,
when both of these are

00:11:59.872 --> 00:12:03.762
operating at such extreme
scales—and Google has the

00:12:03.792 --> 00:12:07.772
ability to separate research and product
a bit better, whereas you hear so much

00:12:07.812 --> 00:12:11.592
about OpenAI being chaotic operationally
and chasing the high-impact thing,

00:12:11.632 --> 00:12:15.222
which is a very startup culture. And then
on the software and enterprise side,

00:12:15.252 --> 00:12:19.052
I think Anthropic will have continued success,
as they've again and again been set up for that.

00:12:19.792 --> 00:12:23.612
And obviously Google Cloud
has a lot of offerings,

00:12:23.652 --> 00:12:27.172
but I think this kind of Gemini name
brand is important for them to build.

00:12:27.452 --> 00:12:31.312
Google Cloud will continue to do well, but

00:12:31.352 --> 00:12:34.902
that's a more complex
thing to explain in the

00:12:34.932 --> 00:12:38.792
ecosystem, because that's competing with
the likes of Azure and AWS rather than

00:12:38.872 --> 00:12:40.892
on the model provider side.

00:12:40.952 --> 00:12:45.292
- So in infrastructure, you think
TPU is giving an advantage?

00:12:45.640 --> 00:12:49.620
- Largely because the margin on
NVIDIA chips is insane, and

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:53.669
Google can develop everything from top to
bottom to fit their stack and not have

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:57.360
to pay this margin. And they've
had a head start in building data

00:12:57.400 --> 00:13:01.320
centers. So all of these things that have
both high lead times and very hard margins on

00:13:01.380 --> 00:13:05.000
high costs, Google has a just kind
of historical advantage there.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:09.600
And if there's going to be a new paradigm,
it's most likely to come from OpenAI where

00:13:09.620 --> 00:13:12.980
their research division
again and again has shown

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:17.599
this ability to land a new research
idea or a product. Like Deep

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:21.630
Research, Sora, o1
thinking models—all these

00:13:21.660 --> 00:13:24.929
definitional things have come from
OpenAI, and that's got to be one of their

00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:29.410
top traits as an organization. So
it's kind of hard to bet against

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:32.990
that, but I think a lot of this
year will be about scale and

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:37.000
optimizing what could be described
as low-hanging fruit in models.

00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:40.240
- And clearly there's a trade-off
between intelligence and

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:44.360
speed. This is what ChatGPT-5 was trying

00:13:44.420 --> 00:13:48.200
to solve behind the scenes.
It's like, do people actually

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:52.160
want intelligence, the broad
public, or do they want speed?

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:55.860
- I think it's a nice variety, or
the option to have a toggle there.

00:13:56.290 --> 00:14:00.160
I mean, for my personal usage,
most of the time when I look

00:14:00.220 --> 00:14:03.580
something up, I use ChatGPT to ask a quick
question, get the information I wanted

00:14:03.620 --> 00:14:07.080
fast. For most daily
tasks, I use the quick

00:14:07.160 --> 00:14:11.020
model. Nowadays, I think the auto mode is pretty
good where you don't have to specifically

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:14.760
say thinking or non-thinking.
Then again, I also

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:18.150
sometimes want the pro mode. Very often
what I do is, when I have something

00:14:18.200 --> 00:14:21.960
written, I put it into
ChatGPT and say, "Hey, do a

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:25.880
very thorough check. Are all my
references correct? Are all my thoughts

00:14:25.940 --> 00:14:29.600
correct? Did I make any formatting
mistakes and are the figure

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:33.420
numbers wrong?" Or something like
that. And I don't need that right

00:14:33.460 --> 00:14:37.440
away. I finish my stuff, maybe
have dinner, let it run, come back

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:41.380
and go through this. I think
this is where it's important to

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:45.320
have this option. I would go crazy if for
each query I would have to wait 30 minutes or

00:14:45.380 --> 00:14:46.340
10 minutes even.

00:14:46.380 --> 00:14:47.420
- That's me.

00:14:48.900 --> 00:14:52.740
I'm sitting over here losing my mind that you
use the router and the non-thinking model.

