00:29:26.212 --> 00:29:29.912
OpenAI's open model release, they were like,
"Don't forget about GPT-2," which I thought was

00:29:29.992 --> 00:29:33.772
really funny 'cause it's just such a
different time. But gpt-oss-120b is

00:29:33.851 --> 00:29:37.512
actually a very strong model and
does some things that other models

00:29:38.152 --> 00:29:44.492
don't do very well. Selfishly, I'll promote
a bunch of Western companies in the US

00:29:44.592 --> 00:29:48.432
and Europe that have these fully open models.
I work at the Allen Institute for AI,

00:29:48.492 --> 00:29:52.292
where we've been building OLMo, which
releases data and code. And now

00:29:52.492 --> 00:29:56.432
we have actual competition for people
that are trying to release everything

00:29:56.512 --> 00:29:59.532
so that others can train these models.
There's the Institute for Foundation

00:29:59.592 --> 00:30:03.172
Models/LM360, which has had their K2

00:30:03.212 --> 00:30:07.152
models of various types.
Apertus is a Swiss research

00:30:07.232 --> 00:30:11.152
consortium. Hugging Face has SmolLM, which

00:30:11.192 --> 00:30:14.912
is very popular. And NVIDIA's Nemotron
3 has started releasing data as

00:30:14.952 --> 00:30:18.872
well. And then Stanford's Martini
Community Project, which is kind

00:30:18.912 --> 00:30:22.692
of making it so there's a pipeline for people
to open a GitHub issue and implement a new

00:30:22.752 --> 00:30:26.732
idea and then have it run in a
stable language modeling stack.

00:30:26.792 --> 00:30:31.101
This space, that list
was way smaller in 2024—

00:30:31.152 --> 00:30:34.752
...so I think it was just AI2. So it's
a great thing for more people to get

00:30:34.772 --> 00:30:38.592
involved and to understand language
models, which doesn't really have a

00:30:38.632 --> 00:30:42.622
Chinese analog. While I'm talking, I'll

00:30:42.672 --> 00:30:46.492
say that the Chinese open
language models tend to be

00:30:46.532 --> 00:30:50.342
much bigger, and that gives them higher
peak performance as MoEs, where a lot of

00:30:50.392 --> 00:30:54.092
these things that we like a
lot, whether it was Gemma and

00:30:54.112 --> 00:30:58.052
Nemotron, have tended to be smaller
models from the US, which is starting

00:30:58.092 --> 00:31:01.872
to change from the US and Europe.
Mistral Large 3 came out, which was a

00:31:01.892 --> 00:31:05.132
giant MoE model, very similar
to DeepSeek architecture in

00:31:05.172 --> 00:31:12.932
December. And then a startup, RCAI, and
both Nemotron and NVIDIA have teased MoE

00:31:12.972 --> 00:31:16.002
models way bigger than
100 billion parameters-

00:31:16.002 --> 00:31:19.672
like this 400 billion parameter
range coming in this Q1

00:31:19.792 --> 00:31:23.764
2026 timeline. So I think this
kind of balance is set to change

00:31:23.774 --> 00:31:27.404
this year in terms of what people are
using the Chinese versus US open models

00:31:27.464 --> 00:31:32.364
for, which I'm personally going
to be very excited to watch.

00:31:32.404 --> 00:31:36.144
- First of all, huge props for
being able to name so many of

00:31:36.154 --> 00:31:38.744
these. Did you actually name LLaMA?

00:31:38.864 --> 00:31:39.623
- No.

00:31:39.644 --> 00:31:40.514
- I feel like ...

00:31:40.884 --> 00:31:41.254
- RIP.

00:31:41.264 --> 00:31:42.524
- This was not on purpose.

00:31:43.344 --> 00:31:45.264
- RIP LLaMA.

00:31:45.284 --> 00:31:48.754
All right. Can you mention some interesting
models that stand out? You mentioned

00:31:48.864 --> 00:31:51.584
Qwen 3 is obviously a standout.

00:31:51.644 --> 00:31:55.364
- So I would say the year's almost
bookended by both DeepSeek

00:31:55.464 --> 00:31:58.964
V3 and R1. And then on the other
hand, in December, DeepSeek-V3.2.

00:31:59.144 --> 00:32:02.884
Because what I like about those is
they always have an interesting

00:32:02.944 --> 00:32:03.814
architecture tweak

00:32:03.984 --> 00:32:07.784
that others don't have. But
otherwise, if you want to go with the

00:32:07.804 --> 00:32:11.504
familiar but really good
performance, Qwen 3 and, like

00:32:11.544 --> 00:32:15.204
Nathan said, also gpt-oss-120b.
And I think what's

00:32:15.264 --> 00:32:18.984
interesting about it is it's kind
of like the first public or open

00:32:19.064 --> 00:32:23.024
weight model that was really trained
with tool use in mind, which

00:32:23.164 --> 00:32:27.144
I do think is kind of a paradigm shift
where the ecosystem was not quite

00:32:27.284 --> 00:32:31.124
ready for it. By tool use, I mean
that the LLM is able to do a web

00:32:31.164 --> 00:32:33.294
search or to call a Python interpreter.

00:32:33.304 --> 00:32:36.464
And I do think it's a
standout because it's a huge

00:32:36.604 --> 00:32:40.504
unlock. Because one of the
most common complaints

00:32:40.564 --> 00:32:43.594
about LLMs are, for example,
hallucinations, right?

00:32:43.624 --> 00:32:47.104
And so, in my opinion, one of the best
ways to solve hallucinations is to

00:32:47.164 --> 00:32:51.064
not try to always remember
information or make things up.

00:32:51.104 --> 00:32:54.464
For math, why not use a
calculator app or Python?

00:32:54.524 --> 00:32:57.984
If I ask the LLM, "Who won
the soccer World Cup in

00:32:58.024 --> 00:33:01.384
1998?" instead of just trying
to memorize, it could go

00:33:02.044 --> 00:33:05.984
do a search. I think mostly
it's still a Google search.

00:33:06.024 --> 00:33:09.064
So ChatGPT and gpt-oss-120b,
they would do a tool call to

00:33:09.364 --> 00:33:12.604
Google, maybe find the FIFA
website. Find, okay, it was

00:33:12.724 --> 00:33:16.684
France. It would get you that information
reliably instead of just trying to

00:33:16.704 --> 00:33:20.424
memorize it. So I think it's
a huge unlock which right now

00:33:20.564 --> 00:33:23.924
is not fully utilized yet by
the open-source, open-weight

00:33:24.004 --> 00:33:27.744
ecosystem. A lot of people
don't use tool call modes

00:33:27.844 --> 00:33:31.704
because I think, first, it's a trust thing.
You don't want to run this on your computer

00:33:31.744 --> 00:33:35.344
where it has access to tools, could wipe your
hard drive or whatever. So you want to maybe

00:33:35.564 --> 00:33:39.364
containerize that. But
I do think that is like

00:33:39.604 --> 00:33:44.084
a really important step for the
upcoming years to have this ability.

00:33:44.124 --> 00:33:47.344
- So a few quick things.
First of all, thank you

00:33:47.424 --> 00:33:51.304
for defining what you mean by tool use. I
think that's a great thing to do in general

00:33:51.344 --> 00:33:54.864
for the concepts we're talking
about. Even things as sort of

00:33:54.924 --> 00:33:57.214
well-established as MoEs.

00:33:57.484 --> 00:34:01.474
You have to say that means mixture
of experts, and you kind of

00:34:01.564 --> 00:34:05.553
have to build up an intuition for people what
that means, how it's actually utilized, what

00:34:05.564 --> 00:34:09.324
are the different flavors. So what
does it mean that there's just such an

00:34:09.344 --> 00:34:13.324
explosion of open models?
What's your intuition?

00:34:13.464 --> 00:34:17.344
- If you're releasing an open model, you want people
to use it, is the first and foremost thing.

00:34:17.364 --> 00:34:21.324
And then after that comes things like
transparency and trust. I think when

00:34:21.364 --> 00:34:25.304
you look at China, the biggest reason
is that they want people around the

00:34:25.324 --> 00:34:29.314
world to use these models, and I think a
lot of people will not. If you look outside

00:34:29.344 --> 00:34:33.293
of the US, a lot of people will not pay for software, but they
might have computing resources where you can put a model on

00:34:33.324 --> 00:34:37.084
it and run it. I think there can also be
data that you don't want to send to the

00:34:37.124 --> 00:34:41.104
cloud. So the number one thing is
getting people to use models, use

00:34:41.184 --> 00:34:45.074
AI, or use your AI that might not be
able to do it without having access

00:34:45.084 --> 00:34:45.924
to the model.

00:34:46.043 --> 00:34:49.634
- I guess we should state explicitly, so we've
been talking about these Chinese models

00:34:50.344 --> 00:34:54.333
and open weight models.
Oftentimes, the way they're run is

00:34:54.384 --> 00:35:01.344
locally. So it's not like you're sending
your data to China or to whoever developed

00:35:01.704 --> 00:35:03.684
Silicon Valley, or whoever
developed the model.

00:35:04.384 --> 00:35:07.014
- A lot of American startups
make money by hosting-

00:35:07.084 --> 00:35:10.774
...these models from China and
selling them. It's called selling

00:35:10.844 --> 00:35:15.664
tokens, which means somebody will call
the model to do some piece of work.

00:35:15.704 --> 00:35:19.364
I think the other reason is for US
companies like OpenAI. They are so GPU

00:35:19.884 --> 00:35:23.814
deprived. They're at the limits of the
GPUs. Whenever they make a release,

00:35:23.824 --> 00:35:26.324
they're always talking about
like, "Our GPUs are hurting." And

00:35:27.164 --> 00:35:30.944
I think during one of these
gpt-oss-120b release sessions, Sam

00:35:31.004 --> 00:35:34.784
Altman said, "Oh, we're releasing this because
we can use your GPUs. We don't have to

00:35:34.864 --> 00:35:38.804
use our GPUs, and OpenAI can
still get distribution out

00:35:38.844 --> 00:35:43.724
of this," which is another very real thing,
because it doesn't cost them anything.

00:35:43.784 --> 00:35:47.604
- And for the user, I think also,
there are users who just use the

00:35:47.624 --> 00:35:51.584
model locally how they would use ChatGPT.
But also for companies I think it's a huge

00:35:51.624 --> 00:35:55.084
unlock to have these models because you can
customize them, you can train them, you

00:35:55.224 --> 00:35:58.684
can add post-training,
add more data. Like,

00:35:58.784 --> 00:36:02.284
specialize them into, let's say,
law, medical models, whatever you

00:36:02.324 --> 00:36:06.204
have. And the appeal, you mentioned
Llama, the appeal of the open-weight

00:36:06.324 --> 00:36:10.044
models from China is that the
open-weight models' licenses

00:36:10.104 --> 00:36:13.844
are even friendlier. I think they are
just unrestricted open source licenses

00:36:13.904 --> 00:36:17.584
where if we use something like Llama
or Gemma, there are some strings

00:36:17.624 --> 00:36:21.564
attached. I think it's like an upper limit in
terms of how many users you have. And then if

00:36:21.624 --> 00:36:24.744
you exceed, I don't know, so and so many
million users, you have to report your

00:36:24.804 --> 00:36:28.684
financial situation to, let's
say, Meta or something like that.

00:36:28.704 --> 00:36:32.684
And I think while it is a
free model, there are strings

00:36:32.704 --> 00:36:36.644
attached, and people do like things
where strings are not attached. So

00:36:36.724 --> 00:36:40.524
I think that's also one of the
reasons, besides performance, why the

00:36:40.564 --> 00:36:43.854
open-weight models from China are so
popular, because you can just use them.

00:36:43.884 --> 00:36:46.434
There's no catch in that sense.

00:36:46.464 --> 00:36:50.234
- The ecosystem has gotten better on that
front, but mostly downstream of these new

00:36:50.244 --> 00:36:53.894
providers providing such open licenses. That was
funny when you pulled up Perplexity and said,

00:36:53.894 --> 00:36:57.884
"Kimi K2 Thinking hosted in the US." Which is
just like an exact... I've never seen this, but

00:36:57.924 --> 00:37:01.334
it's an exact example of what we're talking
about where people are sensitive to this.

00:37:01.944 --> 00:37:05.844
But Kimi K2 Thinking and Kimi K2 is
a model that is very popular. People

00:37:05.864 --> 00:37:09.644
say that has very good creative writing
and also in doing some software

00:37:09.664 --> 00:37:13.364
things. So it's just these little quirks that
people pick up on with different models that they

00:37:13.404 --> 00:37:13.824
like.

00:37:14.531 --> 00:37:18.082
- What are some interesting ideas
that some of these models have

00:37:18.192 --> 00:37:21.932
explored that you can speak to, that
are particularly interesting to you?

00:37:21.971 --> 00:37:25.652
- Maybe we can go chronologically. I mean,
there was, of course, DeepSeek. DeepSeek

00:37:25.812 --> 00:37:29.732
R1 that came out in January of 2025,
if we just focus on 2025. However,

00:37:29.752 --> 00:37:33.572
this was based on DeepSeek-V3,
which came out the year before

00:37:33.632 --> 00:37:37.372
in December 2024. There are
multiple things on the architecture

00:37:37.432 --> 00:37:40.842
side. What is fascinating is...
I mean, that's what I do with my

00:37:41.031 --> 00:37:44.432
from-scratch coding projects. You can
still start with GPT-2, and you can

00:37:44.852 --> 00:37:48.172
add things to that model to make it
into this other model. So it's all

00:37:48.632 --> 00:37:52.162
still kind of like the same
lineage. It is a very close

00:37:52.232 --> 00:37:55.732
relationship between those. But
top of my head, DeepSeek—what was

00:37:55.812 --> 00:37:59.741
unique there is the Mixture of Experts.
Not that they were inventing Mixture of

00:37:59.812 --> 00:38:02.721
Experts—we can maybe talk a bit
more about what Mixture of Experts

00:38:02.812 --> 00:38:06.572
means—but just to list these
things first before we

00:38:06.612 --> 00:38:10.301
dive into detail. Mixture of Experts,
but then they also had Multi-head

00:38:10.392 --> 00:38:14.352
Latent Attention, which is a tweak
to the attention mechanism, where

00:38:14.912 --> 00:38:18.632
this was, I would say,
the main distinguishing

00:38:19.352 --> 00:38:22.692
factor between these
open-weight models. Different

00:38:23.252 --> 00:38:27.212
tweaks to make inference or KV
cache size... We can also define

00:38:27.252 --> 00:38:31.072
KV cache in a few moments,
but to kind of make it more

00:38:31.352 --> 00:38:35.152
economical to have long context, to
shrink the KV cache size. So what are

00:38:35.192 --> 00:38:38.932
tweaks that we can do? And most of them
focused on the attention mechanism. There

00:38:38.971 --> 00:38:42.952
is Multi-head Latent Attention
in DeepSeek. There is Group

00:38:43.011 --> 00:38:46.392
Query Attention, which is still very popular.
It's not invented by any of those models.

00:38:46.412 --> 00:38:49.582
It goes back a few years. But
that would be the other option.

00:38:50.132 --> 00:38:53.812
Sliding window attention—I think
OLMo 3 uses it, if I remember

00:38:53.832 --> 00:38:57.491
correctly. So there are these
different tweaks that make the models

00:38:57.551 --> 00:39:01.132
different. Otherwise, I put
them all together in an

00:39:01.192 --> 00:39:04.622
article once where I just
compared them. They are very,

00:39:04.732 --> 00:39:08.612
surprisingly similar. It's just different
numbers in terms of how many repetitions

00:39:08.672 --> 00:39:12.192
of the transformer block you
have in the center. And, like,

00:39:12.752 --> 00:39:16.352
just little knobs that people tune.
But what's so nice about it is

00:39:16.412 --> 00:39:20.232
it works no matter what. You can
tweak things. You can move the

00:39:20.272 --> 00:39:24.232
normalization layers around to get some
performance gains. And OLMo is always very

00:39:24.252 --> 00:39:28.072
good in ablation studies,
showing what it actually

00:39:28.092 --> 00:39:32.031
does to the model if you move something around.
Ablation studies: does it make it better or

00:39:32.072 --> 00:39:35.971
worse? But there are so many, let's say, ways you
can implement a transformer and make it still

00:39:36.031 --> 00:39:39.482
work. The big ideas that are
still prevalent is Mixture of

00:39:39.551 --> 00:39:43.412
Experts, multi-head latent attention,
sliding window attention, group

00:39:43.491 --> 00:39:47.392
query attention. And then at the
end of the year, we saw a focus

00:39:47.592 --> 00:39:51.531
on making the attention mechanism
scale linearly with inference token

00:39:51.632 --> 00:39:55.612
prediction. So there was
Qwen2-VL, for example,

00:39:55.622 --> 00:39:59.562
which added a gated delta
net. It's kind of inspired by

00:39:59.632 --> 00:40:03.502
State space models, where you have a fixed
state that you keep updating. But it

00:40:03.531 --> 00:40:04.912
makes essentially this attention

00:40:05.971 --> 00:40:08.612
cheaper, or it replaces attention
with a cheaper operation.

00:40:08.622 --> 00:40:12.572
- And it may be useful to step
back and talk about transformer

00:40:12.632 --> 00:40:13.672
architecture in general.

00:40:13.712 --> 00:40:17.652
- Yeah, so maybe we should start
with the GPT-2 architecture. The

00:40:17.672 --> 00:40:21.452
transformer that was derived from the
"Attention Is All You Need" paper.

00:40:21.971 --> 00:40:25.892
The "Attention Is All You Need" paper had
a transformer architecture that had two

00:40:25.991 --> 00:40:29.712
parts, an encoder and a
decoder. And GPT went

00:40:30.332 --> 00:40:34.192
just focusing in on the decoder
part. It is essentially still a

00:40:34.232 --> 00:40:37.372
neural network and it has
this attention mechanism

00:40:37.412 --> 00:40:41.232
inside. And you predict
one token at a time. You

00:40:41.292 --> 00:40:45.212
pass it through an embedding layer. There's
the transformer block. The transformer block

00:40:45.272 --> 00:40:49.092
has attention modules and a fully
connected layer. And there are some

00:40:49.152 --> 00:40:52.732
normalization layers in between. But it's essentially
neural network layers with this attention

00:40:52.772 --> 00:40:56.712
mechanism. So coming from
GPT-2 when we move on

00:40:56.732 --> 00:41:00.551
to gpt-oss-120b, there is, for
example, the Mixture of Experts

00:41:00.632 --> 00:41:04.092
layer. It's not invented by
gpt-oss-120b. It's a few years old.

00:41:04.192 --> 00:41:11.551
But it is essentially a tweak to make
the model larger without consuming more

00:41:11.632 --> 00:41:15.551
compute in each forward pass. So
there is this fully connected layer,

00:41:15.612 --> 00:41:18.712
and if listeners are
familiar with multi-layer

00:41:18.732 --> 00:41:22.602
perceptrons, you can think of a
mini multi-layer perceptron, a

00:41:22.632 --> 00:41:26.102
fully connected neural network layer
inside the transformer. And it's very

00:41:26.112 --> 00:41:29.952
expensive, because it's fully connected. If you
have a thousand inputs and a thousand outputs,

00:41:30.252 --> 00:41:34.102
that's like one million connections.
And it's a very expensive part in

00:41:34.132 --> 00:41:37.932
this transformer. And the idea
is to kind of expand that

00:41:37.991 --> 00:41:41.741
into multiple feedforward
networks. So instead of having

00:41:41.832 --> 00:41:45.712
one, let's say you have 256, but it
would make it way more expensive,

00:41:45.752 --> 00:41:49.511
because now you have 256, but you don't
use all of them at the same time. So you

00:41:49.612 --> 00:41:53.412
now have a router that says, "Okay,
based on this input token, it would be

00:41:53.511 --> 00:41:57.491
useful to use this fully
connected network." And in that

00:41:57.511 --> 00:42:01.232
context, it's called an expert. So a
Mixture of Experts means you have multiple

00:42:01.312 --> 00:42:05.212
experts. And depending on what
your input is, let's say it's more

00:42:05.272 --> 00:42:08.982
math-heavy, it would use different
experts, compared to, let's say,

00:42:09.491 --> 00:42:12.862
translating input text from English to
Spanish. It would maybe consult different

00:42:12.912 --> 00:42:16.822
experts. It's not quite clear, I mean,
not as clear-cut to say, "Okay, this

00:42:16.872 --> 00:42:20.072
is only an expert for math and
for Spanish." It's a bit more

00:42:20.112 --> 00:42:23.971
fuzzy. But the idea is
essentially that you pack more

00:42:24.032 --> 00:42:27.572
knowledge into the network, but not all
the knowledge is used all the time.

00:42:27.632 --> 00:42:31.272
That would be very wasteful.
So, during the token

00:42:31.332 --> 00:42:34.872
generation, you are more selective.
There's a router that selects which

00:42:34.912 --> 00:42:38.712
tokens should go to which expert.
It adds more complexity. It's

00:42:38.752 --> 00:42:42.622
harder to train. There's a lot that
can go wrong, like collapse and

00:42:42.672 --> 00:42:46.652
everything. So I think that's why OLMo
3 still uses dense... I mean, you

00:42:46.692 --> 00:42:50.332
have OLMo models with Mixture of
Experts, but dense models, where dense

00:42:50.392 --> 00:42:54.122
means... So also, it's
jargon. There's a distinction

00:42:54.152 --> 00:42:58.072
between dense and sparse. So Mixture
of Experts is considered sparse,

00:42:58.152 --> 00:43:01.632
because we have a lot of experts, but only
a few of them are active. So that's called

00:43:01.672 --> 00:43:05.292
sparse. And then dense would be the
opposite, where you only have one fully

00:43:05.352 --> 00:43:08.632
connected module, and
it's always utilized.

00:43:08.672 --> 00:43:11.221
- So maybe this is a good place
to also talk about KV cache.

00:43:11.232 --> 00:43:14.011
But actually, before that,
even zooming out, like

00:43:14.112 --> 00:43:22.180
fundamentally, how many new ideas have
been implemented from GPT-2 to today?

00:43:22.259 --> 00:43:25.500
Like, how different really
are these architectures?

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:28.940
- Take the Mixture of Experts.
The attention mechanism in

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:32.640
gpt-oss-120b, that would be the Group
Query Attention mechanism. So it's a

00:43:32.740 --> 00:43:36.160
slight tweak from Multi-Head Attention to
Group Query Attention. So that we have

00:43:36.220 --> 00:43:39.299
too... I think they replaced LayerNorm by

00:43:39.520 --> 00:43:43.500
RMSNorm, but it's just like a different
normalization there and not a big change.

00:43:43.520 --> 00:43:46.960
It's just like a tweak. The
nonlinear activation function—

00:43:47.240 --> 00:43:50.960
people familiar with deep neural
networks, I mean, it's the same as

00:43:51.259 --> 00:43:55.000
changing sigmoid with ReLU. It's not
changing the network fundamentally.

00:43:55.009 --> 00:43:58.900
It's just a little tweak.
And that's about it, I

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:02.819
would say. It's not really fundamentally
that different. It's still the same

00:44:02.859 --> 00:44:06.799
architecture. So you can go from

00:44:06.859 --> 00:44:09.940
one into the other by just
adding these changes basically.

00:44:09.960 --> 00:44:12.150
- It fundamentally is still
the same architecture.

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:16.100
- Yep. For example, you mentioned my book
earlier. That's a GPT-2 model in the

00:44:16.140 --> 00:44:19.630
book because it's simple
and it's very small, so 124

00:44:19.740 --> 00:44:23.620
million parameters approximately. But
in the bonus materials, I do have

00:44:24.200 --> 00:44:28.020
OLMo from scratch, Gemini 3 from
scratch, and other types of from-scratch

00:44:28.060 --> 00:44:31.690
models. And I always start it with my
GPT-2 model and just tweak the—well,

00:44:31.759 --> 00:44:35.700
add different components and you get
from one to the other. It's kind of like

00:44:35.779 --> 00:44:37.859
a lineage in a sense.

00:44:37.900 --> 00:44:41.819
- Can you build up an intuition for
people? Because when you zoom out,

00:44:41.880 --> 00:44:45.730
you look at it, there's so much
rapid advancement in the AI world.

00:44:46.700 --> 00:44:51.159
And at the same time, fundamentally
the architectures have not changed.

00:44:51.240 --> 00:44:58.080
So where is all the turbulence, the
turmoil of the advancement happening?

00:44:58.140 --> 00:45:00.960
Where are the gains to be had?

00:45:01.020 --> 00:45:04.920
- So there are different stages where
you develop the network or train the

00:45:04.960 --> 00:45:08.680
network. You have the pre-training.
Now back in the day, it was just

00:45:08.700 --> 00:45:12.250
pre-training with GPT-2. Now you
have pre-training, mid-training, and

00:45:12.359 --> 00:45:16.060
post-training. So I think
right now we are in the

00:45:16.100 --> 00:45:20.009
post-training focus stage.
Pre-training still gives you

00:45:20.700 --> 00:45:24.690
advantages if you scale it up with
better, higher quality data. But then

00:45:24.740 --> 00:45:28.500
we have capability unlocks that
were not there with GPT-2, for

00:45:28.540 --> 00:45:32.480
For example, ChatGPT is basically a GPT-3

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:36.420
model. And GPT-3 is the same as
GPT-2 in terms of architecture.

00:45:36.460 --> 00:45:40.319
What was new was adding
supervised fine-tuning and

00:45:40.339 --> 00:45:44.200
reinforcement learning with human feedback.
So it's more on the algorithmic side than the

00:45:44.240 --> 00:45:44.870
architecture.

00:45:44.900 --> 00:45:48.799
- I would say that the systems also change a
lot. If you listen to NVIDIA's announcements,

00:45:48.859 --> 00:45:52.560
they talk about things like, "You
now do FP8, you can now do FP4."

00:45:53.180 --> 00:45:57.150
What's happening is these labs are figuring
out how to utilize more compute to put

00:45:57.160 --> 00:46:00.920
it into one model, which lets
them train faster and put more

00:46:00.940 --> 00:46:04.889
data in. And then you can find better
configurations faster by doing

00:46:04.960 --> 00:46:08.880
this. So you can look at, essentially,
tokens per second per GPU

00:46:09.060 --> 00:46:12.750
as a metric that you look at when
you're doing large-scale training.

00:46:12.759 --> 00:46:16.640
You can go from 10k to 13k
by turning on FP8 training,

00:46:16.740 --> 00:46:20.120
which means you're using less
memory per parameter in the

00:46:20.160 --> 00:46:23.799
model. By saving less information,
you do less communication and train

00:46:23.859 --> 00:46:27.850
faster. So all of these
system things underpin way

00:46:27.980 --> 00:46:34.200
faster experimentation
on data and algorithms.

00:46:35.799 --> 00:46:39.700
It's a loop that keeps going where it's hard to
describe when you look at architectures and they're

00:46:39.740 --> 00:46:44.180
exactly the same, but the code base used
to train these models is vastly different-

00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:48.220
-and you could probably... the GPUs
are different but you probably

00:46:48.240 --> 00:46:54.410
train gpt-oss-20b way faster in wall-clock
time than GPT-2 was trained at the time.

00:46:54.440 --> 00:46:57.799
- Yeah. Like you said, they had, for
example, in Mixture of Experts this

00:46:57.980 --> 00:47:01.920
FP4 optimization where you
get more throughput. But I do

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:05.660
think, for speed this is true, but it

00:47:05.680 --> 00:47:09.319
doesn't give the model new capabilities.
It's just: how much can we

00:47:09.839 --> 00:47:13.720
make the computation coarser
without suffering in terms

00:47:13.819 --> 00:47:17.729
of model performance degradation?
But I do think- I mean,

00:47:17.779 --> 00:47:21.660
there are alternatives popping up to
the transformer. Text diffusion models,

00:47:21.680 --> 00:47:25.560
a completely different paradigm. And
there is also... I mean, although

00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:28.880
text diffusion models might use
transformer architectures, it's not an

00:47:28.920 --> 00:47:32.839
autoregressive transformer.
And also Mamba models.

00:47:32.940 --> 00:47:36.799
It's a state space model. But
they do have trade-offs, and

00:47:36.840 --> 00:47:40.540
nothing has yet replaced
the autoregressive

00:47:40.580 --> 00:47:44.460
transformer as the state-of-the-art model.
For state-of-the-art, you would still

00:47:44.480 --> 00:47:48.330
go with that, but there are now
alternatives for the cheaper

00:47:48.520 --> 00:47:51.910
end—alternatives that are kind of making

00:47:51.940 --> 00:47:55.529
compromises. It's not just one
architecture anymore. There are

00:47:56.380 --> 00:48:00.230
little ones coming up. But if we talk about
the state-of-the-art, it's pretty much still

00:48:00.259 --> 00:48:06.049
the transformer architecture, autoregressive,
derived from GPT-2 essentially.

00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:10.040
- I guess the big question here is, we talked
quite a bit about the architecture behind

00:48:10.080 --> 00:48:16.359
the pre-training. Are the scaling laws
holding strong across pre-training,

00:48:16.380 --> 00:48:20.779
post-training, inference, context
size, data, and synthetic data?

00:48:20.840 --> 00:48:23.490
- I'd like to start with the technical
definition of a scaling law-

00:48:23.490 --> 00:48:26.799
-which informs all of this. The scaling
law is the power law relationship

00:48:26.810 --> 00:48:30.540
between... You can think of the x-axis,
so kind of what you are scaling as a

00:48:30.580 --> 00:48:34.359
combination of compute and data,
which are kind of similar,

00:48:34.380 --> 00:48:37.960
and then the y-axis is like the held-out
prediction accuracy over next tokens.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:42.580
We talked about models being autoregressive.
It's like if you keep a set of

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:47.859
text that the model has not seen, how
accurate will it get when you train? And

00:48:47.899 --> 00:48:51.880
the idea of scaling laws came
when people figured out that that

00:48:51.920 --> 00:48:55.538
was a very predictable
relationship. And I think that

00:48:55.720 --> 00:48:59.630
that technical term is continuing,
and then the question is, what

00:48:59.660 --> 00:49:03.630
do users get out of it? Then there
are more types of scaling where,

00:49:03.720 --> 00:49:07.640
OpenAI's o1 was famous for introducing
inference time scaling. And I think

00:49:07.660 --> 00:49:11.540
less famously for also showing that you
can scale reinforcement learning training

00:49:11.580 --> 00:49:15.259
and get kind of this log x-axis and then a

00:49:15.299 --> 00:49:18.960
linear increase in performance on y-axis.
So there's kind of these three axes now

00:49:19.100 --> 00:49:23.060
where the traditional scaling laws are talked
about for pre-training, which is how big

00:49:23.100 --> 00:49:26.848
your model is and how big your dataset is,
and then scaling reinforcement learning,

00:49:26.888 --> 00:49:30.828
which is like how long can you do this trial
and error learning that we'll talk about.

00:49:30.848 --> 00:49:34.808
We'll define more of this, and then this
inference time compute, which is just letting the

00:49:34.848 --> 00:49:38.248
model generate more tokens on a specific
problem. So I'm kind of bullish,

00:49:39.048 --> 00:49:42.988
but they're all really still working, but
the low-hanging fruit has mostly been taken,

00:49:43.028 --> 00:49:46.548
especially in the last year on reinforcement
learning with verifiable rewards,

00:49:46.628 --> 00:49:50.218
which is this RLVR, and then
inference time scaling,

00:49:50.308 --> 00:49:53.978
which is just why these models feel
so different to use, where previously

00:49:53.988 --> 00:49:57.648
you would get that first token immediately.
And now they'll go off for seconds,

00:49:57.668 --> 00:50:01.288
minutes, or even hours,
generating these hidden thoughts

00:50:01.308 --> 00:50:05.088
before giving you the first word of
your answer. And that's all about this

00:50:05.128 --> 00:50:06.428
inference time scaling, which is

00:50:07.268 --> 00:50:11.008
such a wonderful kind of step function in
terms of how the models change abilities.

00:50:11.068 --> 00:50:14.838
They kind of enabled this tool use
stuff and enabled this much better

00:50:14.848 --> 00:50:17.977
software engineering that we
were talking about. And this,

00:50:18.008 --> 00:50:21.908
when we say enabled, is almost entirely
downstream of the fact that this

00:50:21.948 --> 00:50:25.728
reinforcement learning with verifiable
rewards training just kind of let the models

00:50:25.768 --> 00:50:29.728
pick up these skills very
easily. So let the models learn,

00:50:29.768 --> 00:50:33.658
so if you look at the reasoning
process when the models are generating

00:50:33.688 --> 00:50:37.678
a lot of tokens, what it'll often be doing is:
it tries a tool, it looks at what it gets back.

00:50:37.688 --> 00:50:41.568
It tries another API, it sees what it
gets back and if it solves the problem.

00:50:41.608 --> 00:50:44.948
So the models, when you're training
them, very quickly learn to do this.

00:50:45.008 --> 00:50:48.928
And then at the end of the day, that
gives this kind of general foundation

00:50:48.968 --> 00:50:52.628
where the model can use CLI
commands very nicely in your repo

00:50:52.688 --> 00:50:56.348
and handle Git for you and move
things around and organize things

00:50:56.388 --> 00:50:59.688
or search to find more information, which if
we were sitting in these chairs a year ago

00:51:00.428 --> 00:51:04.328
is something that we didn't really think
of the models doing. So this is just

00:51:04.348 --> 00:51:07.638
kind of something that has happened this
year and has totally transformed how

00:51:07.688 --> 00:51:11.028
has totally transformed how
we think of using AI which

00:51:11.188 --> 00:51:15.168
evolution and just unlocks so
much value. But it's like,

00:51:15.488 --> 00:51:19.468
just so- pr- unlocks so much
value. But it's- it's like,

00:51:19.528 --> 00:51:23.438
it's not clear what the next avenue will
be in terms of unlocking stuff like this.

00:51:23.488 --> 00:51:27.328
I think there's... we'll get to continual
learning later, but there's a lot of buzz

00:51:27.388 --> 00:51:31.298
around certain areas of AI, but no
one knows when the next step function

00:51:31.298 --> 00:51:31.908
will really come.

00:51:31.948 --> 00:51:34.907
- So you've actually said
quite a lot of things there,

00:51:35.828 --> 00:51:39.448
and said profound things
quickly. It would be nice to

00:51:39.488 --> 00:51:43.328
unpack them a little bit. You say you're
bullish basically on every version of

00:51:43.408 --> 00:51:48.088
scaling. So can we just even start
at the beginning? Pre-training,

00:51:49.508 --> 00:51:53.188
are we kind of implying that the
low- hanging fruit on pre-training

00:51:53.268 --> 00:51:57.248
scaling has been picked? Has pre-training

00:51:57.288 --> 00:52:01.168
hit a plateau, or is even pre-training
still something you're bullish on?

00:52:01.208 --> 00:52:04.848
- Pre-training has gotten extremely
expensive. I think to scale up

00:52:04.888 --> 00:52:08.648
pre-training, it's also implying
that you're gonna serve a very

00:52:08.708 --> 00:52:12.528
large model to the users.
So I think that it's been

00:52:12.588 --> 00:52:16.468
loosely established the likes of GPT-4
and similar models were around one

00:52:16.528 --> 00:52:20.197
trillion parameters at the biggest size.
There's a lot of rumors that they've

00:52:20.268 --> 00:52:24.248
actually gotten smaller as training has
gotten more efficient. You want to make

00:52:24.257 --> 00:52:28.218
the model smaller because then your costs
of serving go down proportionately.

00:52:28.248 --> 00:52:32.128
These models, the cost of training
them is really low relative to the

00:52:32.148 --> 00:52:36.138
cost of serving them to hundreds of millions of
users. I think DeepSeek had this famous number

00:52:36.208 --> 00:52:40.148
of about five million dollars for
pre-training at cloud market rates.

00:52:40.208 --> 00:52:44.188
In OLMo 3, section 2.4
in the paper, we just

00:52:44.208 --> 00:52:47.688
detailed how long we had the GPU clusters
sitting around for training which

00:52:47.728 --> 00:52:51.708
includes engineering
issues, multiple seeds,

00:52:51.728 --> 00:52:55.628
and it was like about two million dollars to rent
the cluster to deal with all the headaches of

00:52:55.708 --> 00:52:58.908
training a model. So
these models are pretty—

00:52:59.288 --> 00:53:02.938
like, a lot of people could get one to
10 million dollars to train a model,

00:53:02.988 --> 00:53:06.888
but the recurring costs of
serving millions of users is

00:53:06.928 --> 00:53:10.868
really billions of dollars of compute.
I think that you can look at a

00:53:10.888 --> 00:53:14.757
thousand GPU rental you can pay
100 grand a day for. And these

00:53:15.028 --> 00:53:18.888
companies could have millions of GPUs.
Like you can look at how much these things

00:53:18.928 --> 00:53:20.748
cost to sit around. So
that's kind of a big

00:53:21.648 --> 00:53:25.508
thing, and then it's like, if scaling
is actually giving you a better model,

00:53:25.568 --> 00:53:29.338
is it gonna be financially worth it?
And I think we'll slowly push it

00:53:29.428 --> 00:53:33.148
out as AI solves more compelling tasks,
so like the likes of Claude Opus 4.5,

00:53:33.268 --> 00:53:37.238
making Claude Code just
work for things. I—

00:53:37.238 --> 00:53:41.058
I launched this project called the
ATOM project, which is American Truly

00:53:41.108 --> 00:53:44.977
Open Models in July, and
that was like a true vibe

00:53:45.028 --> 00:53:48.988
coded website, and like,
I have a job to make

00:53:49.028 --> 00:53:52.488
plots and stuff. And then I came back to
refresh it in the last few weeks and it's like

00:53:52.888 --> 00:53:56.648
Claude Opus 4.5 versus whatever model at
the time was like, just crushed all the

00:53:56.688 --> 00:54:00.687
issues that it had from building in
June and July and like, it might be a

00:54:00.748 --> 00:54:04.668
bigger model. There's a lot of things that go
into this, but there's still progress coming.

00:54:04.688 --> 00:54:07.748
- So what you're speaking to is the
nuance of the y-axis of the scaling

00:54:07.788 --> 00:54:11.648
laws—the way it's experienced
versus on a benchmark, the

00:54:11.708 --> 00:54:15.688
actual intelligence might be
different. But still, your intuition

00:54:15.728 --> 00:54:19.128
about pre-training, if you
scale the size of compute,

00:54:20.048 --> 00:54:24.028
will the models get better? Not
whether it's financially viable but

00:54:24.108 --> 00:54:28.368
just from the law aspect of it, do you
think the models will get smarter?

00:54:28.448 --> 00:54:32.128
- Yeah. And I think that there's...
And this sometimes comes off as

00:54:32.168 --> 00:54:35.768
almost like disillusionment
from people, leadership at AI

00:54:35.848 --> 00:54:39.748
companies saying this, but they're like,
"It's held for 13 orders of magnitude

00:54:39.788 --> 00:54:43.668
of compute, why would it ever
end?" So I think fundamentally it

00:54:43.728 --> 00:54:47.458
is pretty unlikely to stop, it's just
eventually we're not even gonna be able to

00:54:47.488 --> 00:54:50.388
test the bigger scales because of all the
problems that come with more compute.

00:54:50.408 --> 00:54:54.368
I think that there's a
lot of talk on how 2026

00:54:54.428 --> 00:54:58.328
is a year when very large
Blackwell compute clusters,

00:54:58.448 --> 00:55:02.468
like gigawatt-scale facilities at
hyperscalers, are coming online.

00:55:03.788 --> 00:55:07.328
These were all contracts for
power and data centers that

00:55:07.348 --> 00:55:11.328
were signed and sought
out in 2022 and 2023.

00:55:11.388 --> 00:55:15.148
So before or right after ChatGPT.
It took this two-to-three-year

00:55:15.268 --> 00:55:19.208
lead time to build these bigger clusters to
train the models. While there's obviously

00:55:19.248 --> 00:55:23.168
immense interest in building even more data
centers than that. So that is the crux

00:55:23.188 --> 00:55:27.028
that people are saying: these new clusters
are coming. The labs are gonna have

00:55:27.048 --> 00:55:30.568
more compute for training.
They're going to utilize this,

00:55:30.608 --> 00:55:34.375
but it's not a given. I've seen so
much progress that I expect it,

00:55:34.415 --> 00:55:38.316
and I expect a little bit
bigger models, and I expect...

00:55:39.256 --> 00:55:43.096
I would say it's more like we'll see a
$2,000 subscription this year. We've seen

00:55:43.136 --> 00:55:46.676
$200 subscriptions. That could 10X again,
and these are the kind of things that

00:55:47.156 --> 00:55:50.596
could come, and they're all
downstream of this bigger model

00:55:50.656 --> 00:55:53.536
that offers just a little
bit more cutting edge.

00:55:53.576 --> 00:55:57.356
- So, you know, it's reported that xAI
is gonna hit that one-gigawatt scale

00:55:57.415 --> 00:56:00.786
early '26, and a

00:56:01.395 --> 00:56:05.915
full two gigawatts by year end. How
do you think they'll utilize that

00:56:06.875 --> 00:56:08.286
in the context of scaling laws?

00:56:09.156 --> 00:56:12.395
Is a lot of that inference?
Is a lot of that training?

00:56:12.776 --> 00:56:16.125
- It ends up being all of
the above. So I think

00:56:16.156 --> 00:56:20.016
that all of your decisions when
you're training a model come back to

00:56:20.036 --> 00:56:23.716
pre-training. So if you're going to
scale RL on a model, you still need to

00:56:23.736 --> 00:56:27.415
decide on your architecture that enables
this. We were talking about other

00:56:27.455 --> 00:56:31.216
architectures and using different types of
attention, or a mixture of experts models.

00:56:31.276 --> 00:56:35.176
The sparse nature of MoE models makes it

00:56:35.316 --> 00:56:39.276
much more efficient to do
generation, which becomes a big part

00:56:39.336 --> 00:56:43.276
of post-training, and you need to
have your architecture ready so

00:56:43.336 --> 00:56:47.036
that you can actually scale up this
compute. I still think most of the

00:56:47.096 --> 00:56:50.975
compute is going in at pre-training.
Because you can still make a model

00:56:51.056 --> 00:56:54.935
better, you still want to go and revisit
this. You still want the best base model

00:56:54.996 --> 00:56:58.975
you can. And in a few years that'll
saturate and the RL compute will just

00:56:59.036 --> 00:57:00.016
go longer.

00:57:00.056 --> 00:57:05.076
- Are there people who disagree with
you and say pre-training is dead?

00:57:06.036 --> 00:57:09.736
It's all about scaling inference,
scaling post-training,

00:57:09.836 --> 00:57:15.136
scaling context, continual learning,
scaling data, synthetic data?

00:57:15.176 --> 00:57:19.136
- People vibe that way and describe it in
that way, but I think it's not the practice

00:57:19.176 --> 00:57:19.466
that is happening.

00:57:19.496 --> 00:57:21.846
- It's just the general vibe of
people saying this thing is dead-

00:57:21.856 --> 00:57:24.816
- The excitement is elsewhere.
So the low-hanging fruit-

00:57:24.836 --> 00:57:28.786
...in RL is elsewhere. For example,
we released our model in November...

00:57:28.796 --> 00:57:31.946
Every company has deadlines. Our
deadline was November 20th, and

00:57:31.975 --> 00:57:35.955
for that, our run was five
days, which compared to 2024

00:57:36.256 --> 00:57:39.895
is a very long time to just be doing
post- training at a model of 30 billion

00:57:39.915 --> 00:57:43.676
parameters. It's not a big model. And
then in December, we had another release,

00:57:43.856 --> 00:57:47.576
where we let the RL run for
another three and a half weeks,

00:57:47.636 --> 00:57:51.596
and the model got notably better,
so we released it. And that's a

00:57:51.636 --> 00:57:55.505
to just allocate to something
that is going to be your peak-

00:57:55.656 --> 00:57:57.496
...for the year. So it's like-

00:57:57.536 --> 00:57:58.106
- The reasoning is-

00:57:58.106 --> 00:58:01.725
- There's these types of decisions when
training a model where they just...

00:58:01.756 --> 00:58:05.676
They can't leave it forever.
You have to keep pulling

00:58:05.736 --> 00:58:08.596
in the improvements from
researchers. So you redo

00:58:08.676 --> 00:58:12.536
pre-training, you'll do this
post-training for a month, but then you

00:58:12.596 --> 00:58:16.415
need to give it to your users. You
need to do safety testing. So it's

00:58:16.475 --> 00:58:20.375
just... I think there's a lot in
place that reinforces this cycle of

00:58:20.435 --> 00:58:24.196
updating the models. Things improve.
You get a new compute cluster

00:58:24.236 --> 00:58:28.156
that lets you do something more
stably or faster. It's like

00:58:28.216 --> 00:58:31.856
you hear a lot about Blackwell
having rollout issues, where at

00:58:31.895 --> 00:58:35.296
AI2, most of the models we're
pre-training are on 1,000 to 2,000

00:58:35.336 --> 00:58:39.316
GPUs. But when pre-training on
10,000 or 100,000 GPUs, you hit

00:58:39.336 --> 00:58:43.196
very different failures. GPUs break
in weird ways, and on a 100,000

00:58:43.236 --> 00:58:47.196
GPU run, you're pretty much
guaranteed to have one GPU

00:58:47.236 --> 00:58:50.935
that is down. Your training code must
handle that redundancy, which is a

00:58:50.955 --> 00:58:51.725
very different problem.

00:58:51.736 --> 00:58:55.665
Whereas what we're doing, like playing
with post-training on a cluster,

00:58:55.756 --> 00:58:59.596
or for people learning ML,
what they're battling to

00:58:59.636 --> 00:59:01.665
train these biggest models is just-

00:59:02.136 --> 00:59:05.716
...mass distributed scale,
and it's very different.

00:59:05.756 --> 00:59:11.455
But that's somewhat different
than- That's a systems problem-

00:59:11.496 --> 00:59:15.395
...in order to enable scaling
laws, especially at pre-training.

00:59:15.435 --> 00:59:19.196
You need all these GPUs at once.
When we shift to RL, it actually

00:59:19.556 --> 00:59:23.415
lends itself to heterogeneous compute
because you have many copies of the

00:59:23.455 --> 00:59:27.116
model. To do a primer for

00:59:27.236 --> 00:59:31.176
language model reinforcement learning,
what you're doing is having two sets of

00:59:31.216 --> 00:59:34.836
GPUs. One you can call the actor,
and one you call the learner.

00:59:34.895 --> 00:59:38.616
The learner is where your actual
reinforcement learning updates happen.

00:59:38.676 --> 00:59:42.246
These are traditionally
policy gradient algorithms.

00:59:42.336 --> 00:59:46.216
Proximal Policy Optimization,
PPO, and Group Relative Policy

00:59:46.225 --> 00:59:50.176
Optimization, GRPO, are
the two popular classes.

00:59:50.216 --> 00:59:53.685
And on the other side you have
actors which are generating

00:59:53.716 --> 00:59:57.546
completions, and these completions
are what you're going to grade.

00:59:57.596 --> 01:00:01.286
Reinforcement learning is all about
optimizing reward. In practice,

01:00:01.316 --> 01:00:05.116
you can have a lot of different actors
in different parts of the world

01:00:05.156 --> 01:00:08.645
doing different types of problems,
and then you send it back to

01:00:08.676 --> 01:00:12.596
this highly networked compute
cluster to do this actual learning

01:00:12.636 --> 01:00:16.336
where you take the gradients.
You need to have a

01:00:16.375 --> 01:00:20.276
tightly meshed network to do
different types of parallelism and

01:00:20.296 --> 01:00:24.136
spread out your model for efficient
training. Every different type of

01:00:24.256 --> 01:00:28.176
training and serving has these
considerations to scale.

01:00:28.216 --> 01:00:32.116
We talked about pre-training and RL,
and then inference time scaling-

01:00:32.156 --> 01:00:35.725
how do you serve a model that's thinking
for an hour to 100 million users?

01:00:35.756 --> 01:00:39.716
I don't know about that, but I know
that's a hard problem. In order

01:00:39.756 --> 01:00:43.596
to give people this intelligence, there's
all these systems problems, and we need

01:00:43.696 --> 01:00:46.026
more compute and you need more
stable compute to do it."

01:00:46.296 --> 01:00:50.196
- But you're bullish on all of these kinds
of scaling is what I'm hearing. On the

01:00:50.256 --> 01:00:54.415
inference, on the reasoning,
even on the pre-training?

01:00:54.435 --> 01:00:58.096
- Yeah, so that's a big can of worms
here, but there are basically two...

01:00:58.136 --> 01:01:01.836
The knobs are the training and the
inference scaling where you can

01:01:02.236 --> 01:01:05.915
get gains. In a world where
we had, let's say, infinite

01:01:05.956 --> 01:01:09.886
compute resources, you want to do all of them.
So you have training, you have inference

01:01:09.956 --> 01:01:13.625
scaling, and training is like a hierarchy:
it's pre-training, mid-training,

01:01:13.636 --> 01:01:17.596
post-training. Changing the model size,
more training data, training a bigger

01:01:17.676 --> 01:01:22.716
model gives you more knowledge in the
model. Then the model, let's say, has a

01:01:22.816 --> 01:01:26.446
better base model. Back in the day,
or still, we call it a foundation

01:01:26.496 --> 01:01:30.456
model, and it unlocks... But
you don't, let's say, have

01:01:30.496 --> 01:01:34.354
the model be able to solve
your most complex tasks

01:01:34.424 --> 01:01:38.084
during pre-training or after pre-training.
You still have these other unlock

01:01:38.104 --> 01:01:41.953
phases where you have mid-training
or, for example, post-training with

01:01:41.953 --> 01:01:45.844
RL that unlocks capabilities that the model
has in terms of knowledge in the pre-training.

01:01:45.884 --> 01:01:49.334
And I think, sure, if you

01:01:49.344 --> 01:01:53.044
do more pre-training, you get a
better base model that you can unlock

01:01:53.084 --> 01:01:57.044
later. But like Nathan said, it just becomes
too expensive. We don't have infinite compute,

01:01:57.104 --> 01:02:01.084
so you have to decide, do I want to spend
that compute more on making the model

01:02:01.124 --> 01:02:04.954
larger? It's like a trade-off. In
an ideal world, you want to do

01:02:05.024 --> 01:02:08.853
all of them. And I think in that sense,
scaling is still pretty much alive. You would

01:02:08.884 --> 01:02:12.794
still get a better model, but like we saw
with Claude Opus 4.5, it's just not worth it.

01:02:12.824 --> 01:02:16.544
Because you can unlock more

01:02:16.584 --> 01:02:20.524
performance with other techniques at
that current moment, especially if you

01:02:20.584 --> 01:02:24.424
look at inference scaling. That's one
of the biggest gains this year with o1,

01:02:24.924 --> 01:02:28.184
where it took a smaller model further than

01:02:29.044 --> 01:02:32.564
pre-training a larger model like
Claude Opus 4.5. So I wouldn't say

01:02:32.964 --> 01:02:36.484
pre-training scaling is dead, it's just that
there are other more attractive ways to scale

01:02:36.844 --> 01:02:40.824
right now. But at some point,
you will still want to make some

01:02:40.864 --> 01:02:43.684
progress on the pre-training.
The thing also to consider

01:02:44.484 --> 01:02:48.424
is where you want to spend your
money. If you spend it more

01:02:48.444 --> 01:02:52.204
on the pre-training, it's like a fixed cost.
You train the model, and then it has this

01:02:52.264 --> 01:02:56.104
capability forever. You can always use it.

01:02:56.124 --> 01:02:59.954
With inference scaling, you don't spend
money during training, you spend money

01:03:00.044 --> 01:03:03.944
later per query, and then it's also like
math. How long is my model gonna be

01:03:04.044 --> 01:03:07.484
on the market if I replace it in
half a year? Maybe it's not worth

01:03:07.644 --> 01:03:11.344
spending $5 million, $10 million,
$100 million on training

01:03:11.604 --> 01:03:15.324
it longer. Maybe I will just do more

01:03:15.364 --> 01:03:19.264
inference scaling and get performance there.
It maybe costs me $2 million in terms

01:03:19.324 --> 01:03:22.904
of user queries. It becomes a question
of how many users you have and doing the

01:03:22.964 --> 01:03:26.724
math, and I think that's also where
it's interesting where ChatGPT is in a

01:03:26.784 --> 01:03:30.474
position. I think they have a lot of users where
they need to go a bit cheaper, where they have that

01:03:30.544 --> 01:03:33.804
GPT-5 model that is a bit
smaller. Other companies that

01:03:33.944 --> 01:03:37.774
have... Let's say, if
your customers have other

01:03:37.884 --> 01:03:41.844
trade-offs. For example, there was
also the Math Olympiad or some

01:03:41.904 --> 01:03:43.593
of these math problems where

01:03:44.684 --> 01:03:48.364
ChatGPT or they had a proprietary
model, and I'm pretty sure it's just

01:03:48.424 --> 01:03:52.264
like a model that has been fine-tuned
a little bit more, but most of it

01:03:52.304 --> 01:03:56.244
was during inference scaling to achieve
peak performance in certain tasks.

01:03:56.264 --> 01:03:59.844
need that all the time. But
yeah, long story short, I do

01:03:59.884 --> 01:04:03.604
think all of these pre-training,
mid-training, post-training,

01:04:03.804 --> 01:04:07.313
inference scaling, they are all still
things you want to do. It's just

01:04:07.344 --> 01:04:11.184
finding—at the moment, in this year, it's
finding the right ratio that gives you the best

01:04:11.204 --> 01:04:12.954
bang for the buck, basically.

01:04:13.044 --> 01:04:16.894
- I think this might be a good place to
define pre-training, mid-training, and

01:04:16.964 --> 01:04:18.064
post-training.

01:04:18.104 --> 01:04:21.854
- So, pre-training is the classic training
one next token prediction at a time.

01:04:21.884 --> 01:04:25.824
You have a big corpus of data. And Nathan
probably also has very interesting

01:04:26.024 --> 01:04:29.864
insights there because of OLMo 3. A big
portion of the paper focuses on the

01:04:29.904 --> 01:04:33.604
right data mix. So, pre-training is
essentially just, you know, training

01:04:33.844 --> 01:04:37.344
cross entropy loss, training
on next token prediction on a

01:04:37.564 --> 01:04:41.464
vast corpus of internet data,
books, papers and so forth. It

01:04:41.504 --> 01:04:45.384
has changed a little bit over the years
in the sense people used to throw in

01:04:45.484 --> 01:04:48.904
everything they can. Now,
it's not just raw data. It's

01:04:48.984 --> 01:04:52.904
also synthetic data
where people, let's say,

01:04:52.964 --> 01:04:56.544
rephrase certain things. So synthetic
data doesn't necessarily mean

01:04:56.564 --> 01:05:00.404
purely AI-made data. It's also taking

01:05:00.444 --> 01:05:04.404
something from an article, a Wikipedia
article, and then rephrasing it as

01:05:04.464 --> 01:05:11.964
a Q&amp;A question or summarizing it, rewording
it, and making better data that way.

01:05:12.224 --> 01:05:16.124
Because I think of it also
like with humans. If someone,

01:05:16.184 --> 01:05:20.144
let's say, reads a book compared to a
messy—no offense, but like—Reddit post

01:05:20.164 --> 01:05:25.204
or something like that,
I do think you learn—

01:05:25.224 --> 01:05:28.114
- There's going to be a post
about this, Sebastian.

01:05:28.114 --> 01:05:31.014
- Some Reddit data is very coveted
and excellent for training.

01:05:31.014 --> 01:05:32.894
You just have to filter it.

01:05:33.184 --> 01:05:37.014
- And I think that's the idea.
I think it's like if someone

01:05:37.064 --> 01:05:42.724
took that and rephrased it in a, let's
say, more concise and structured way,

01:05:42.734 --> 01:05:45.984
I think it's higher quality data
that gets the LLM there faster.

01:05:46.944 --> 01:05:50.644
You get the same LLM out of it at the
end, but it trains faster because

01:05:50.704 --> 01:05:54.524
if the grammar and the punctuation are

01:05:54.564 --> 01:05:58.404
correct, it already learns the
correct way, versus getting

01:05:58.464 --> 01:06:02.404
information from a messy source and then
learning later how to correct that.

01:06:02.424 --> 01:06:09.844
So, I think that is how pre-training
evolved and why scaling still works.

01:06:09.904 --> 01:06:13.844
It's not just about the
amount of data, it's also

01:06:13.884 --> 01:06:17.834
the tricks to make that data
better for you, in a sense. And

01:06:17.864 --> 01:06:21.754
then mid-training is... I mean, it
used to be called pre-training.

01:06:21.784 --> 01:06:25.674
I think it's called mid-training because it was awkward
to have pre-training and post-training but nothing in the

01:06:25.724 --> 01:06:29.524
middle, right? It sounds a bit weird. You have pre-training
and post-training, but what's the actual training?

01:06:29.534 --> 01:06:33.404
So, the mid-training is usually
similar to pre-training,

01:06:33.444 --> 01:06:37.204
but it's a bit more
specialized. It's the same

01:06:37.264 --> 01:06:40.644
algorithm, but what you do is
you focus, for example, on

01:06:40.884 --> 01:06:44.744
long-context documents. The reason you

01:06:44.824 --> 01:06:48.444
don't do that during pre-training is
because you don't have that many long

01:06:48.484 --> 01:06:52.464
context documents. We have a specific
phase. And one problem of LLMs is

01:06:52.504 --> 01:06:55.744
still that it's a neural network.
It has the problem of catastrophic

01:06:55.824 --> 01:06:59.344
forgetting. So, you teach it something,
it forgets other things. And you

01:06:59.354 --> 01:07:03.264
wanna... I mean, it's not 100% forgetting,
but it's like "no free lunch."

01:07:03.304 --> 01:07:07.274
It's the same with humans. If you
ask me some math I learned 10 years

01:07:07.304 --> 01:07:09.204
ago, I would have to look at it again.

01:07:09.264 --> 01:07:13.244
- Nathan was actually saying that he's consuming
so much content that there's a catastrophic

01:07:13.344 --> 01:07:14.244
forgetting issue.

01:07:14.304 --> 01:07:17.584
- Yeah, I'm trying to learn so much about
AI, and it's like I was learning about

01:07:18.184 --> 01:07:22.054
pre-training parallelism. I'm like, "I lost
something and I don't know what it was."

01:07:22.084 --> 01:07:25.894
- I don't want to anthropomorphize
LLMs, but it's the same kind of thing

01:07:25.944 --> 01:07:29.799
in how humans learn. I mean,
quantity is not always better

01:07:29.859 --> 01:07:33.660
because you have to be selective.
And mid-training is being

01:07:33.720 --> 01:07:37.480
selective in terms of quality content
at the end. So the last thing the

01:07:37.560 --> 01:07:40.720
LLM has seen is the quality stuff.
And then post-training is all

01:07:40.759 --> 01:07:44.290
the fine-tuning, supervised fine-tuning,

01:07:44.680 --> 01:07:48.660
DPO, Reinforcement Learning
with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR),

01:07:49.540 --> 01:07:53.440
with human feedback, and so forth. So
the refinement stages. And it's also

01:07:53.460 --> 01:07:57.379
interesting, it's a cost thing. You spend
a lot of money on pre-training right now.

01:07:57.419 --> 01:08:01.200
RL a bit less. With RL, you don't really

01:08:01.259 --> 01:08:04.940
teach it knowledge. It's more like unlocking
the knowledge; it's more like a skill

01:08:05.180 --> 01:08:08.960
learning, like how to solve problems with
the knowledge that it has from pre-training.

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:12.779
There are actually three papers
this year, or last year, 2025,

01:08:12.859 --> 01:08:17.250
on RL for pre-training. But I don't
think anyone does that in production.

01:08:17.260 --> 01:08:18.519
- Toy examples for now.

01:08:18.529 --> 01:08:22.479
- Toy examples, right? But to generalize,
RL post-training is more like

01:08:22.540 --> 01:08:26.859
the skill unlock, where pre-training
is like soaking up the knowledge.

01:08:26.960 --> 01:08:30.819
- A few things that could be
helpful. A lot of people

01:08:31.479 --> 01:08:35.300
think of synthetic data as being bad
for training the models. You mentioned

01:08:35.359 --> 01:08:36.660
how DeepSeek got almost...

01:08:37.479 --> 01:08:41.399
OCR, which is Optical Character
Recognition. A lot of labs did it.

01:08:41.439 --> 01:08:44.910
Ai2 had one, Meta had multiple.

01:08:44.939 --> 01:08:48.779
And the reason each of these labs
has these is because there are vast

01:08:48.840 --> 01:08:52.760
amounts of PDFs and other digital documents
on the web that aren't in formats

01:08:52.800 --> 01:08:56.399
that are encoded with text easily.
So you use these Almost-OCR,

01:08:56.800 --> 01:09:00.599
DeepSeek OCR, or what we called our
Almost-OCR, to extract trillions of

01:09:00.639 --> 01:09:04.380
tokens of candidate data for pre-training.

01:09:04.399 --> 01:09:07.990
Pre-training dataset size is
measured in trillions of tokens.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:11.830
Smaller models from researchers can be
something like five to 10 trillion.

01:09:11.859 --> 01:09:15.620
researchers can be something
like five to 10 trillion. Um,

01:09:15.639 --> 01:09:19.399
Qwen is documented going up to 50 trillion,
and there are rumors that these closed

01:09:19.439 --> 01:09:23.200
labs can go to 100 trillion tokens.
Getting this potential data to put

01:09:23.279 --> 01:09:27.269
in—they have a very big funnel, and
the data you actually train on is

01:09:27.340 --> 01:09:31.279
a small percentage of this.
This character recognition data

01:09:31.300 --> 01:09:35.210
would be described as synthetic data for
pre-training in a lab. And then there's

01:09:35.279 --> 01:09:39.219
also the fact that ChatGPT now
gives wonderful answers, and you

01:09:39.269 --> 01:09:42.720
can train on those best answers, and that's
synthetic data. It's very different than

01:09:42.760 --> 01:09:46.660
early ChatGPT with lots
of hallucination data.

01:09:46.700 --> 01:09:48.750
when people became grounded
in synthetic data.

01:09:48.800 --> 01:09:52.620
- One interesting question is, if I recall
correctly, OLMo 3 was trained with less

01:09:52.680 --> 01:09:56.120
data than specifically some other
open-weight models, maybe even

01:09:56.300 --> 01:10:00.280
OLMo 2. But you still got better performance,
and that might be one example of how

01:10:00.340 --> 01:10:01.040
the data helped.

01:10:01.080 --> 01:10:02.590
- It's mostly down to data quality.

01:10:02.620 --> 01:10:06.540
I think if we had more compute, we would
train for longer. I think we'd ultimately see

01:10:06.599 --> 01:10:10.340
that as something we would want
to do. And especially with big

01:10:10.400 --> 01:10:14.330
models, you need more compute, because we
talked about having more parameters and

01:10:14.360 --> 01:10:18.160
we talked about knowledge. Essentially,
there's a ratio where big models can absorb

01:10:18.220 --> 01:10:22.160
more from data, and then you
get more benefit out of this.

01:10:22.180 --> 01:10:26.139
Any logarithmic graph in your mind
is like a small model will level off

01:10:26.200 --> 01:10:29.860
sooner if you're measuring tons
of tokens, and bigger models need

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:33.870
more. But mostly, we aren't training
that big of models right now at

01:10:33.920 --> 01:10:38.700
AI2, and getting the highest quality data
we can is the natural starting point.

01:10:38.740 --> 01:10:42.700
- Is there something to be said about the
topic of data quality? Is there some

01:10:42.740 --> 01:10:46.340
low-hanging fruit there still where
the quality could be improved?

01:10:46.400 --> 01:10:49.840
- It's like turning the crank.
Historically, in the open, there's been a

01:10:49.960 --> 01:10:53.599
canonical best pre-training
dataset that has

01:10:53.680 --> 01:10:57.200
moved around between who has the most
recent one or the best recent effort. Like

01:10:57.280 --> 01:11:00.740
AI2's Dolma was very early with the
first OLMo, and Hugging Face had

01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:04.780
FineWeb. And there's a DCLM project,
which has been kind of like a,

01:11:04.840 --> 01:11:08.740
which stands for Data Comp Language
Model. There's been Data Comp

01:11:08.800 --> 01:11:12.480
for other machine learning projects,
and they had a very strong

01:11:12.540 --> 01:11:16.500
dataset. And a lot of it is
the internet is becoming

01:11:16.620 --> 01:11:20.540
fairly closed off, so we have Common Crawl,
which is hundreds of trillions of tokens,

01:11:20.559 --> 01:11:23.960
and you filter it. It looks
like scientific work where

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:27.700
you're training classifiers and
making decisions based on how you

01:11:27.820 --> 01:11:31.720
prune down this dataset into the
highest quality stuff and the stuff

01:11:31.740 --> 01:11:35.700
that suits your tasks. Previously,
language models were tested a lot more

01:11:35.780 --> 01:11:39.740
on knowledge and conversational
things, but now they're expected

01:11:39.750 --> 01:11:43.519
to do math and code. To train a reasoning
model, you need to remix your whole

01:11:43.639 --> 01:11:47.460
dataset. And there's a lot of wonderful
scientific methods here where you can,

01:11:47.940 --> 01:11:51.700
you can take your gigantic dataset,
sample really tiny things from

01:11:51.780 --> 01:11:55.760
different sources, such as
GitHub, Stack Exchange, Reddit,

01:11:55.820 --> 01:11:59.800
Wikipedia. You can sample small things from
them, and train small models on each of these

01:11:59.860 --> 01:12:03.639
mixes and measure their performance on your
evaluations. You can just do basic linear

01:12:03.660 --> 01:12:07.610
regression, and it's like, "Here's your optimal
dataset." But if your evaluations change, your

01:12:07.620 --> 01:12:11.320
dataset changes a lot. So a lot
of OLMo 3 was new sources for

01:12:11.360 --> 01:12:15.040
reasoning to be better at math and
code, and then you do this mixing

01:12:15.059 --> 01:12:18.940
procedure and it gives you the answer.
I think that's happened at labs this

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:22.740
year; there's new hot things, whether
it's coding environments or web

01:12:22.780 --> 01:12:26.400
navigation, and you need to bring in new data,
change your whole pre-training so that your

01:12:26.420 --> 01:12:30.000
post-training can work better.
And that's like the constant

01:12:30.120 --> 01:12:35.300
evolution and the redetermining of
what they care about for their models.

01:12:35.340 --> 01:12:39.280
- Are there fun anecdotes of
what sources of data are

01:12:39.300 --> 01:12:42.840
particularly high quality that we
wouldn't expect? You mentioned Reddit

01:12:42.880 --> 01:12:45.059
sometimes can be a source.

01:12:45.080 --> 01:12:51.420
- Reddit was very useful. I
think PDFs is definitely one.

01:12:51.440 --> 01:12:52.540
- Oh, especially arXiv.

01:12:52.580 --> 01:12:57.080
- Yeah, so AI2 has run Semantic
Scholar for a long time, which is

01:12:58.000 --> 01:13:01.800
what you can say is a competitor to
Google Scholar with a lot more features.

01:13:01.820 --> 01:13:05.500
And to do this, AI2 has found
and scraped a lot of PDFs for

01:13:05.580 --> 01:13:09.450
openly accessible papers
that might not be behind the

01:13:09.450 --> 01:13:12.559
closed walled garden of a certain
publisher. So, truly open

01:13:12.720 --> 01:13:16.159
scientific PDFs. And if you sit
on all of these and you process

01:13:16.240 --> 01:13:18.740
it, you can get value out
of it. And I think that

01:13:18.800 --> 01:13:22.400
like, a lot of that style
of work has been done by

01:13:22.460 --> 01:13:25.690
the frontier labs did much
earlier. You just need to have

01:13:25.960 --> 01:13:29.840
a pretty skilled researcher that
understands how things change

01:13:29.920 --> 01:13:33.480
models; they bring it in, clean
it, and it's a lot of labor.

01:13:33.559 --> 01:13:37.400
When frontier labs scale
researchers, a lot more goes

01:13:37.440 --> 01:13:41.404
into data. If you join a
frontier lab and you want to

01:13:41.424 --> 01:13:44.724
have impact, the best way to do
it is just find new data that's

01:13:44.804 --> 01:13:48.364
better. And then, the fancy,
glamorous algorithmic things like

01:13:49.004 --> 01:13:52.884
figuring out how to make o1 is like the
sexiest thought of a scientist. It's

01:13:52.924 --> 01:13:56.803
like, "Oh, I figured out how to scale RL."
There's a group that did that, but most of the

01:13:56.844 --> 01:13:58.063
contribution is like—

01:13:58.124 --> 01:13:58.414
- On the dataset

01:13:58.443 --> 01:14:02.324
- ..."I'm gonna make the data better," or, "I'm gonna
make the infrastructure better so everyone on

01:14:02.364 --> 01:14:04.914
my team can run experiments 5% faster."

01:14:04.943 --> 01:14:08.784
- At the same time, I think it's also one of the
closest guarded secrets, what your training data is,

01:14:08.824 --> 01:14:12.624
for legal reasons. And so there's also, I
think, a lot of work that goes into hiding

01:14:12.683 --> 01:14:16.304
what your training data was
essentially. Like training the model

01:14:16.364 --> 01:14:19.384
to not give away the sources
because you have legal reasons.

01:14:19.443 --> 01:14:22.833
- The other thing, to be complete, is that
some people are trying to train on only

01:14:22.864 --> 01:14:26.693
licensed data, whereas Common Crawl
is a scrape of the whole internet.

01:14:26.724 --> 01:14:29.884
So if I host multiple websites,

01:14:29.983 --> 01:14:33.844
I'm happy to have them train language
models, but I'm not explicitly

01:14:33.904 --> 01:14:37.793
licensing what governs it. And
therefore, Common Crawl is

01:14:37.824 --> 01:14:41.483
largely unlicensed, which means that
your consent really hasn't been

01:14:41.504 --> 01:14:45.384
provided for how to use the data. There's another
idea where you can train language models only

01:14:45.443 --> 01:14:49.313
on data that has been licensed
explicitly, so that the kind of governing

01:14:49.404 --> 01:14:53.143
contract is provided, and I'm not sure
if Apertus is the copyright thing or the

01:14:53.183 --> 01:14:53.853
license thing.

01:14:53.964 --> 01:14:57.943
I know that the reason that they did it was for
an EU compliance thing, where they wanted to make

01:14:57.983 --> 01:15:05.164
sure that their model
fit one of those checks.

01:15:05.224 --> 01:15:10.273
- On that note, there's also the
distinction in licensing. Some people

01:15:11.084 --> 01:15:14.884
just purchase the license.
Let's say they buy an Amazon

01:15:15.124 --> 01:15:19.023
Kindle book, or a Manning book, and then
use that in training. That is a gray

01:15:19.103 --> 01:15:23.044
zone 'cause you paid for the content and you
might want to train on it. But then there

01:15:23.063 --> 01:15:26.884
are also restrictions where even that
shouldn't be allowed. And so that is

01:15:26.943 --> 01:15:30.853
where it gets a bit fuzzy.
And yeah, I think that is

01:15:30.904 --> 01:15:34.893
right now still a hot topic.
Big companies like OpenAI

01:15:34.964 --> 01:15:38.364
approached private companies
for their proprietary data and

01:15:38.784 --> 01:15:42.364
private companies, they become
more and more, let's say,

01:15:42.483 --> 01:15:46.304
protective of their data because they
know, "Okay, this is going to be my moat

01:15:46.464 --> 01:15:51.004
in a few years." And I do think that's
like the interesting question, where

01:15:52.584 --> 01:15:56.544
if LLMs become more commoditized, and I think
a lot of people learn about LLMs, there

01:15:56.563 --> 01:16:00.364
will be a lot more people able to train LLMs.
Of course, there are infrastructure challenges.

01:16:00.384 --> 01:16:03.664
But if you think of big
industries like pharmaceutical

01:16:03.724 --> 01:16:07.404
industries, law, finance industries,
I do think they, at some point, will

01:16:07.483 --> 01:16:11.304
hire people from other
frontier labs to build their

01:16:11.344 --> 01:16:15.273
in-house models on their proprietary
data, which will be then, again, another

01:16:15.324 --> 01:16:19.063
unlock with pre-training that is
currently not there. Because even if you

01:16:19.124 --> 01:16:23.063
wanted to, you can't get that data. You
can't get access to clinical trials

01:16:23.164 --> 01:16:27.004
most of the time and these types of things.
So, I do think scaling, in that sense,

01:16:27.044 --> 01:16:30.424
might be still pretty much
alive if you also look in

01:16:30.603 --> 01:16:34.454
domain-specific applications, because we are
still right now, in this year, just looking

01:16:34.523 --> 01:16:38.414
at general purpose LLMs on, on ChatGPT,
Anthropic and so forth. They are just

01:16:38.443 --> 01:16:42.404
general purpose, they're not even, I think,
scratching the surface of what an LLM

01:16:42.424 --> 01:16:46.904
can do if it is really specifically
trained and designed for a specific task.

01:16:47.004 --> 01:16:50.824
- I think on the data thing—this is one of the
things that happened in 2025, and we totally

01:16:50.864 --> 01:16:54.844
forget it—is Anthropic lost in
court and owed $1.5 billion to

01:16:54.924 --> 01:16:58.674
authors. Anthropic, I think,
bought thousands of books and

01:16:58.764 --> 01:17:02.733
scanned them and was cleared legally
for that because they bought

01:17:02.744 --> 01:17:06.414
the books, and that is kind of going through
the system. And then the other side, they also

01:17:06.464 --> 01:17:10.443
torrented some books, and I think this
torrenting was the path where the court

01:17:10.483 --> 01:17:14.384
said that they were then culpable to pay these
billions of dollars to authors, which is just

01:17:14.443 --> 01:17:18.344
such a mind-boggling lawsuit that
kind of just came and went. That is

01:17:18.404 --> 01:17:22.044
so much money- ... from the VC ecosystem.

01:17:22.103 --> 01:17:26.094
- These are court cases that will define the
future of human civilization, because it's clear

01:17:26.124 --> 01:17:29.884
that data drives a lot of this, and
there's this very complicated human

01:17:29.893 --> 01:17:34.603
tension of... I mean, you can
empathize. You're both authors.

01:17:34.624 --> 01:17:38.344
And there's some degree to which, I
mean, you put your heart and soul and

01:17:38.384 --> 01:17:43.384
your sweat and tears into
the writing that you do. It

01:17:43.523 --> 01:17:47.284
feels a little bit like theft
for somebody to train your data

01:17:47.324 --> 01:17:48.683
without giving you credit.

01:17:49.023 --> 01:17:53.014
- And there are, like Nathan said, also two
layers to it. Someone might buy the book and

01:17:53.044 --> 01:17:56.933
then train on it, which could be argued
fair or not fair, but then there

01:17:56.964 --> 01:18:00.744
are the straight-up
companies who use pirated

01:18:00.824 --> 01:18:04.764
books where it's not even compensating the
author. That is, I think, where people

01:18:04.804 --> 01:18:06.634
got a bit angry about it
specifically, I would say.

01:18:06.643 --> 01:18:11.054
- Yeah, but there has to be some kind of
compensation scheme. This is like moving towards-

01:18:11.124 --> 01:18:13.233
... towards something like
Spotify streaming did-

01:18:13.324 --> 01:18:15.614
... originally for music.
You know, what does that-

01:18:15.614 --> 01:18:19.344
... compensation look like? You have to define those
kinds of models. You have to think through all of that.

01:18:19.904 --> 01:18:23.714
One other thing I think people are generally
curious about, I'd love to get your

01:18:23.784 --> 01:18:28.464
thoughts, as LLMs are used more and
more. If you look at even arXiv, but

01:18:28.704 --> 01:18:32.204
GitHub, more and more of
the data is generated by

01:18:32.304 --> 01:18:38.904
LLMs. What do you do in that kind of
world? How big of a problem is that?

01:18:38.943 --> 01:18:42.884
- Largest problem's the infrastructure
and systems, but from an AI point

01:18:42.924 --> 01:18:45.063
of view, it's kind of inevitable.

01:18:45.103 --> 01:18:49.544
- So it's basically LLM-generated data that's
curated by humans essentially, right?

01:18:49.584 --> 01:18:53.044
- Yes, and I think that a lot of open source
contributors are legitimately burning

01:18:53.124 --> 01:18:56.933
out. If you have a popular open source
repo, somebody's like, "Oh, I want to do

01:18:56.933 --> 01:19:00.742
open source AI. It's good for
my career," and they just vibe-

01:19:00.804 --> 01:19:04.744
-code something and they throw it
in. You might get more of this-

01:19:04.964 --> 01:19:05.094
- I have a-

01:19:05.094 --> 01:19:05.464
- - than I do.

01:19:05.474 --> 01:19:09.304
- Yeah, so I have actually
a case study here.

01:19:09.324 --> 01:19:12.864
I have a repository called
MLxtend that I developed as a

01:19:12.943 --> 01:19:16.794
student around 10 years
ago, and it is a reasonably

01:19:16.904 --> 01:19:20.704
popular library still for certain
algorithms, I think especially like frequent

01:19:20.724 --> 01:19:24.643
data mining stuff. And
there were recently two or

01:19:24.683 --> 01:19:28.563
three people who submitted a lot of
PRs in a very short amount of time.

01:19:28.603 --> 01:19:32.374
I do think LLMs have been involved
in submitting these PRs. Me, as the

01:19:32.404 --> 01:19:36.313
maintainer, there are two things. First,
I'm a bit overwhelmed. I don't have time to

01:19:36.844 --> 01:19:39.943
read through it because, especially as an
older library, that is not a priority for me.

01:19:40.324 --> 01:19:44.224
At the same time, I kind of also
appreciate it because I think something

01:19:44.244 --> 01:19:48.044
people forget is it's not just using the
LLM. There's still a human layer that

01:19:48.084 --> 01:19:52.044
verifies something, and that
is in a sense also how data

01:19:52.103 --> 01:19:55.864
is labeled, right? One of
the most expensive things is

01:19:55.904 --> 01:19:59.483
getting labeled data for
RL from human feedback

01:19:59.504 --> 01:20:03.252
phases. And this is kind of like
that, where it goes through

01:20:03.272 --> 01:20:07.252
phases, and then you actually get higher
quality data out of it. And so I don't

01:20:07.312 --> 01:20:11.272
mind it in a sense. It can feel overwhelming,
but I do think there is also value

01:20:11.292 --> 01:20:11.752
in it.

01:20:11.812 --> 01:20:15.312
- It feels like there's a fundamental
difference between raw LLM-generated

01:20:15.412 --> 01:20:19.252
data and LLM-generated data
with a human in the loop

01:20:19.432 --> 01:20:23.262
that does some kind of verification, even
if that verification is a small percent

01:20:23.972 --> 01:20:25.892
of the lines of code.

01:20:25.912 --> 01:20:28.712
- I think this goes with anything where

01:20:29.732 --> 01:20:33.512
people think also sometimes, "Oh,
yeah. I can just use an LLM to learn

01:20:33.572 --> 01:20:37.492
about XYZ," which is true. You can,
but there might be a person who

01:20:37.532 --> 01:20:41.422
is an expert who might have used
an LLM to write specific code.

01:20:41.472 --> 01:20:45.372
There is kind of like this human work
that went into it to make it nice,

01:20:45.392 --> 01:20:49.332
throwing out the not-so-nice
parts to kind of pre-digest

01:20:49.372 --> 01:20:53.332
it for you, and that saves
you time. I think that's the

01:20:53.372 --> 01:20:57.352
value-add, where you have
someone filtering things or

01:20:57.392 --> 01:21:00.952
even using the LLMs correctly.
This is still labor that you

01:21:01.012 --> 01:21:04.742
get for free. For example, if
you read a Substack article,

01:21:04.772 --> 01:21:08.662
I could maybe ask an LLM to
give me opinions on that, but

01:21:08.792 --> 01:21:12.632
I wouldn't even know what to ask.
And I think there is still value in

01:21:12.652 --> 01:21:16.632
reading that article compared to me
going to the LLM because you are the

01:21:16.692 --> 01:21:20.232
expert. You select what knowledge
is actually spot on, should be

01:21:20.272 --> 01:21:23.922
included, and you give
me this very... this

01:21:23.972 --> 01:21:27.942
executive summary. And this is
a huge value-add because now I

01:21:27.972 --> 01:21:31.442
don't have to waste three to
five hours to go through this

01:21:31.452 --> 01:21:35.392
myself, maybe get some incorrect
information and so on. And so I think

01:21:35.412 --> 01:21:36.612
that's also where the future

01:21:37.772 --> 01:21:43.912
still is for writers even though there are
LLMs that... Can kind of save you time.

01:21:43.952 --> 01:21:47.482
- It's kinda fascinating to watch.
I'm sure you guys do this,

01:21:47.512 --> 01:21:51.202
but for me, I look at the
difference between a summary

01:21:52.652 --> 01:21:56.432
and the original content. Even
if it's a page-long summary of a

01:21:56.492 --> 01:22:00.212
page-long content, it's interesting to see

01:22:00.312 --> 01:22:04.232
how the LLM-based summary
takes the edge off. What

01:22:04.292 --> 01:22:07.252
is the signal it removes from the thing?

01:22:07.292 --> 01:22:09.692
- The voice is what I talk about a lot.

01:22:09.752 --> 01:22:13.441
- Voice? Well, voice... I would love
to hear what you mean by voice, but

01:22:13.471 --> 01:22:16.032
sometimes there's literally insights.

01:22:16.072 --> 01:22:19.981
By removing an insight, you're
changing the meaning of

01:22:20.032 --> 01:22:24.892
the thing. So I'm continuously
disappointed how bad LLMs are

01:22:25.752 --> 01:22:29.472
at really getting to the core
insights, which is what a

01:22:29.512 --> 01:22:37.132
great summary does. Yet even if I have
these extremely elaborate prompts where I'm

01:22:37.412 --> 01:22:41.312
really trying to dig for the
insights, it's still not

01:22:41.352 --> 01:22:45.082
quite there, which... I mean,
that's a whole deep philosophical

01:22:45.172 --> 01:22:49.132
question about what is human knowledge
and wisdom and what does it mean to be

01:22:49.152 --> 01:22:52.192
insightful and so on. But when you talk
about the voice, what do you mean?

01:22:52.252 --> 01:22:55.832
- When I write, I think a lot
of what I'm trying to do is

01:22:55.972 --> 01:22:59.752
take what you think as a
researcher, which is very raw. A

01:22:59.772 --> 01:23:03.532
researcher is trying to encapsulate
an idea at the frontier of their

01:23:03.572 --> 01:23:07.452
understanding and they're trying
to put what is a feeling into

01:23:07.512 --> 01:23:11.412
words. I try to do this
in my writing, which

01:23:11.472 --> 01:23:15.392
makes it come across as raw but
also high-information in a way that

01:23:15.432 --> 01:23:19.072
some people will get it and some won't.
And that's the nature of research.

01:23:19.092 --> 01:23:23.032
And language models don't do
this well. They're all trained

01:23:23.072 --> 01:23:26.882
with Reinforcement Learning from Human
Feedback, which takes feedback from many

01:23:26.892 --> 01:23:30.752
people and averages how the
model behaves from this.

01:23:30.772 --> 01:23:34.692
And I think it's going to
be hard for a model to

01:23:34.772 --> 01:23:38.732
be very incisive when there's
that sort of filter. This is a

01:23:40.112 --> 01:23:44.092
wonderful fundamental problem
for researchers in RLHF. This

01:23:44.132 --> 01:23:48.092
provides so much utility in making
the models better, but also

01:23:48.172 --> 01:23:52.032
the problem formulation is
kind of... there's this

01:23:52.052 --> 01:23:55.972
knot in it that you can't
get past. These language

01:23:56.032 --> 01:23:59.862
models don't have this prior in their
deep expression they're trying to get

01:23:59.912 --> 01:24:03.821
at. I don't think it's impossible.
There are stories of models that

01:24:03.832 --> 01:24:07.062
really shock people. Like, I
think of... I would love to have

01:24:07.072 --> 01:24:11.012
tried Bing Sydney. Did that
have more voice? Because

01:24:11.032 --> 01:24:14.821
it would so often go off the
rails, which is historically

01:24:14.912 --> 01:24:18.891
obviously a scary way—like telling a
reporter to leave his wife—is a crazy model

01:24:18.972 --> 01:24:22.951
to potentially put in general
adoption. But that's kind of like

01:24:23.011 --> 01:24:28.412
a trade-off; is this RLHF process
in some ways adding limitations?

01:24:28.472 --> 01:24:32.892
- That's a terrifying place to be as one
of these frontier labs and companies,

01:24:33.692 --> 01:24:35.832
because millions of people are using them.

01:24:35.892 --> 01:24:39.472
- There was a lot of backlash
last year with GPT-4o getting

01:24:39.532 --> 01:24:43.332
removed, and I've personally never used
the model, but I've talked to people at

01:24:43.372 --> 01:24:47.292
OpenAI where they get emails from

01:24:47.372 --> 01:24:51.212
users that might be detecting subtle
differences in the deployments

01:24:51.272 --> 01:24:55.172
in the middle of the night. And they email
them like, "My friend is different."

01:24:55.212 --> 01:24:59.112
And they find these employees' emails
and send them things because they are so

01:24:59.152 --> 01:25:00.532
attached to this

01:25:01.572 --> 01:25:05.132
set of model weights and configuration
that is deployed to the users.

01:25:05.192 --> 01:25:08.712
We see this with TikTok. You
open it... I don't use TikTok,

01:25:08.772 --> 01:25:12.302
but supposedly in five minutes the
algorithm gets you. It's locked in.

01:25:12.412 --> 01:25:16.332
And those are language models
doing recommendations. I think

01:25:16.432 --> 01:25:20.352
there are ways you can do this. Within
five minutes of chatting with it,

01:25:20.392 --> 01:25:22.602
the model just gets you.
And that is something that

01:25:23.712 --> 01:25:28.942
people aren't really ready for.
Like, don't give that to kids.

01:25:28.942 --> 01:25:30.172
At least until we know what's happening.

01:25:30.192 --> 01:25:34.032
- But there's also going to be this
mechanism... What's going to happen

01:25:34.072 --> 01:25:35.382
with these LLMs as they're
used more and more...

01:25:36.192 --> 01:25:39.812
Unfortunately, the nature of the human
condition is such that people commit suicide.

01:25:39.912 --> 01:25:43.412
And so what journalists will do
is they will report extensively

01:25:43.432 --> 01:25:47.172
on the people who commit suicide.
And they would very likely

01:25:47.232 --> 01:25:50.412
link it to the LLMs because they have
that data about the conversations.

01:25:50.472 --> 01:25:54.352
If you're really struggling in
your life, if you're depressed,

01:25:54.392 --> 01:25:58.332
if you're thinking about suicide, you're
going to probably talk to LLMs about it.

01:25:58.392 --> 01:26:02.352
And so what journalists will do is
say, "Well, the suicide was committed

01:26:02.412 --> 01:26:06.322
because of the LLM." And that's
going to lead to the companies,

01:26:06.352 --> 01:26:09.792
because of legal issues and so on,

01:26:10.472 --> 01:26:14.432
more and more taking the edge off
of the LLM. So it's going to be

01:26:14.512 --> 01:26:18.072
as generic as possible. It's so
difficult to operate in this space

01:26:18.112 --> 01:26:23.992
because you don't want an LLM to cause
harm to humans at that level, but also

01:26:24.072 --> 01:26:27.552
this is the nature of
the human experience,

01:26:27.592 --> 01:26:31.092
is to have a rich conversation,
a fulfilling conversation,

01:26:31.192 --> 01:26:35.011
one that challenges you from which
you grow. You need that edge.

01:26:35.072 --> 01:26:42.872
And that's something extremely difficult
for AI researchers on the RLHF front to

01:26:42.992 --> 01:26:47.012
actually have to solve, because you're
dealing with the human condition.

01:26:47.052 --> 01:26:50.122
- A lot of researchers at these
companies are so well-motivated,

01:26:50.392 --> 01:26:56.382
and definitely Anthropic and OpenAI
culturally want to do good for the world.

01:26:56.472 --> 01:27:00.372
And it's such a—I'm like, "Ooh,
I don't wanna work on this,"

01:27:00.382 --> 01:27:04.262
because on the one hand, a lot of
people see AI as a health ally,

01:27:04.352 --> 01:27:08.172
as somebody they can talk to about
their health confidentially,

01:27:08.212 --> 01:27:10.192
but then it bleeds all the way into this,

01:27:11.372 --> 01:27:15.251
like talking about mental
health, where it's

01:27:16.432 --> 01:27:19.792
heartbreaking that this will be the
thing where somebody goes over the edge,

01:27:19.812 --> 01:27:23.772
but other people might be saved.
And I'm like, "I don't..."

01:27:23.812 --> 01:27:27.762
As a researcher, it's like, I don't want to
train image generation models and release

01:27:27.772 --> 01:27:31.632
them openly because I don't want to
enable somebody to have a tool on their

01:27:31.692 --> 01:27:34.202
laptop that can harm other people.

01:27:34.212 --> 01:27:37.982
I don't have the infrastructure in
my company to do that safely. But

01:27:37.992 --> 01:27:41.972
there's a lot of areas like this
where it just needs people that will

01:27:42.132 --> 01:27:47.692
approach it with complexity and
conviction. It's just such a hard problem.

01:27:47.992 --> 01:27:51.812
- But also, we as a society, as users of these
technologies, need to make sure that we're

01:27:51.852 --> 01:27:55.712
having the complicated conversation
about it versus just fearmongering—

01:27:55.832 --> 01:27:59.712
that Big Tech is causing harm to
humans or stealing your data.

01:27:59.772 --> 01:28:03.112
It's more complicated than
that. And you're right.

01:28:03.152 --> 01:28:06.982
There's a very large number of people inside
these companies, many of whom I know,

01:28:07.072 --> 01:28:10.802
who deeply care about
helping people. They are

01:28:10.832 --> 01:28:14.612
considering the full human experience of
people from across the world, not just Silicon

01:28:14.632 --> 01:28:18.532
Valley. People across the United States
and the world, what their needs are.

01:28:18.551 --> 01:28:21.692
It's really difficult to
design this one system

01:28:22.632 --> 01:28:26.572
that is able to help all these different
kinds of people across different age groups,

01:28:26.632 --> 01:28:31.292
cultures, and mental states.

01:28:31.372 --> 01:28:35.312
- I wish that the timing of AI was
different relative to the relationship

01:28:35.362 --> 01:28:38.752
of Big Tech to the average person.
Big Tech's reputation was so low,

01:28:38.772 --> 01:28:42.712
and with how AI is so expensive, it's
inevitably going to be a Big Tech thing.

01:28:42.752 --> 01:28:46.432
It takes so many resources,
and people say the US is,

01:28:46.452 --> 01:28:50.412
"betting the economy on AI" with this
build-out. To have these be intertwined

01:28:50.472 --> 01:28:54.032
at the same time makes for such a
hard communication environment.

01:28:54.632 --> 01:28:58.312
It would be good for me to go talk to more
people in the world who hate Big Tech

01:28:58.612 --> 01:29:02.832
and see AI as a continuation of this.

01:29:02.872 --> 01:29:06.812
- And one of the things you recommend,
one of the antidotes that

01:29:06.852 --> 01:29:13.352
you talk about, is to find agency
in this system. As opposed to

01:29:13.372 --> 01:29:17.032
sitting back in a powerless
way and consuming the AI slop

01:29:17.332 --> 01:29:24.512
as it rapidly takes over the internet.
Find agency by using AI to build stuff,

01:29:24.652 --> 01:29:28.592
build apps, build... One, that
actually helps you build intuition,

01:29:28.612 --> 01:29:32.412
but two, it's empowering because
you can understand how it works,

01:29:32.572 --> 01:29:36.172
what the weaknesses are.
It gives your voice

01:29:36.272 --> 01:29:40.252
power to say, "This is a bad use of the
technology, and this is a good use."

01:29:40.272 --> 01:29:44.032
And you're more plugged
into the system then,

01:29:44.112 --> 01:29:48.532
so you can understand it better and
you can steer it better as a consumer.

01:29:48.592 --> 01:29:52.332
- I think that's a good point you brought up about
agency. Instead of ignoring it and saying,

01:29:52.341 --> 01:29:56.212
"Okay, I'm not going to use it,"
I think it's probably long-term

01:29:56.272 --> 01:29:59.832
healthier to say, "Okay, it's
out there. I can't put it back."

01:30:00.112 --> 01:30:04.072
when they came out. How do
I make best use of it, and

01:30:04.121 --> 01:30:07.992
how does it help me to up-level myself?
The one thing I worry about here, though,

01:30:08.072 --> 01:30:12.012
is, if you just fully use it for something
you love to do, the thing you love to do

01:30:12.032 --> 01:30:16.012
is no longer there. And that could
potentially, I feel, lead to burnout.

01:30:16.072 --> 01:30:19.852
For example, if I use an LLM
to do all my coding for me,

01:30:19.912 --> 01:30:23.772
now there's no coding. I'm just managing
something that is coding for me.

01:30:23.812 --> 01:30:27.471
Two years later, let's say, if I
just do that eight hours a day,

01:30:27.552 --> 01:30:35.512
having something code for me,
do I feel fulfilled still?

01:30:36.612 --> 01:30:40.572
Is this hurting me in terms of being excited
about my job, excited about what I'm doing?

01:30:40.812 --> 01:30:43.152
Am I still proud to build something?

01:30:43.212 --> 01:30:47.202
- On that topic of enjoyment, it's quite
interesting. We should just throw this in there,

01:30:47.252 --> 01:30:50.622
that there's this recent survey of about

01:30:50.852 --> 01:30:55.572
791 professional developers, meaning
10-plus years of experience.

01:30:55.612 --> 01:31:01.072
- That's a long time. As a junior developer?

01:31:01.272 --> 01:31:05.132
- Yeah, in this day and age.
So, there's also many fronts

01:31:05.192 --> 01:31:09.082
that are surprising. They break it down

01:31:09.112 --> 01:31:12.412
by junior and senior developers.
But, I mean, it just shows

01:31:12.432 --> 01:31:21.352
that both junior and senior developers
use AI-generated code in code they ship.

01:31:22.032 --> 01:31:25.952
So this is not just for fun or
intermediate learning things.

01:31:26.052 --> 01:31:30.012
This is code they ship.
25%—like, most of them

01:31:30.092 --> 01:31:33.712
use around 50% or more.
And what's interesting is,

01:31:33.732 --> 01:31:37.432
for the category of over 50%
of your code that you ship

01:31:37.652 --> 01:31:41.532
is AI-generated, senior
developers are much more likely

01:31:41.612 --> 01:31:46.332
to do so. But you don't want AI
to take away the thing you love.

01:31:46.412 --> 01:31:49.632
I think this speaks to my experience,
these results I'm about to say.

01:31:49.692 --> 01:31:53.672
Together, about 80% of people
find it either somewhat

01:31:53.732 --> 01:31:59.102
more enjoyable or significantly more
enjoyable to use AI as part of the work.

01:31:59.732 --> 01:32:02.792
- I think it depends on the task. From
my personal usage, for example,

01:32:03.732 --> 01:32:07.472
I have a website where I
sometimes tweak things.

01:32:07.552 --> 01:32:11.522
I personally don't enjoy
this. So in that sense,

01:32:11.572 --> 01:32:15.562
if the AI can help me to implement
something on my website, I'm all for it.

01:32:15.612 --> 01:32:19.592
It's great. But then, at the same
time, when I solve a complex problem—

01:32:19.612 --> 01:32:23.472
well, if there's a bug,
and I hunt this bug,

01:32:23.552 --> 01:32:27.472
and I find it, it's the best feeling
in the world. You feel great.

01:32:27.512 --> 01:32:31.392
But now, if you don't
even think about the bug,

01:32:31.452 --> 01:32:34.952
you just go directly to the LLM, well, you
never have this kind of feeling, right?

01:32:35.032 --> 01:32:38.962
But then there could be
the middle ground where,

01:32:38.992 --> 01:32:42.912
well, you try yourself, you
can't find it, you use the LLM,

01:32:42.952 --> 01:32:46.792
and then you don't get frustrated because it helps
you and you move on to something that you enjoy.

01:32:46.832 --> 01:32:50.532
And so, looking at these statistics,
I think what is not factored in

01:32:50.612 --> 01:32:54.492
is that it's averaging over
all the different scenarios.

01:32:54.552 --> 01:32:58.261
We don't know if it's for the core task

01:32:58.412 --> 01:33:02.252
or if it's for something mundane that
people would not have enjoyed otherwise.

01:33:02.352 --> 01:33:06.312
So, in a sense, AI is really great for doing
mundane things that take a lot of work.

01:33:06.352 --> 01:33:10.292
For example, my wife the
other day—she has a podcast

01:33:10.352 --> 01:33:17.802
for book discussions, a book club, and
she was transferring the show notes from

01:33:17.852 --> 01:33:21.502
Spotify to YouTube, and then
the links somehow broke.

01:33:21.692 --> 01:33:25.492
And she had in some episodes, because
it is so many books, like 100 links,

01:33:25.572 --> 01:33:29.352
and it would have been really painful to
go in there and fix each link manually.

01:33:29.412 --> 01:33:33.272
So I suggested, "Hey, let's try ChatGPT."
We copied the text into ChatGPT,

01:33:33.312 --> 01:33:37.252
and it fixed them. Instead of two hours

01:33:37.292 --> 01:33:41.252
going from link to link fixing
that, it made that type of

01:33:41.312 --> 01:33:45.272
work much more seamless.
I think everyone has a

01:33:45.332 --> 01:33:49.072
use case where AI is useful
for something that would be

01:33:49.212 --> 01:33:50.762
really boring, really mundane.

01:33:51.152 --> 01:33:58.302
- For me personally, since we're talking about
coding, and you mentioned debugging...

01:33:58.312 --> 01:34:02.152
the source of enjoyment for me, more
on the Cursor side than Claude Code,

01:34:02.252 --> 01:34:09.532
is that I have a friend, I have
a pair programmer. It's less

01:34:09.852 --> 01:34:15.192
lonely. You made debugging
sound like this great joy.

01:34:15.232 --> 01:34:18.792
No, I would say debugging
is like a drink of

01:34:18.852 --> 01:34:21.772
water after you've been
going through a desert

01:34:21.792 --> 01:34:25.642
for days. You skip the whole desert part

01:34:25.772 --> 01:34:29.532
where you're suffering.
Sometimes it's nice to have

01:34:29.892 --> 01:34:33.752
a friend who can't really find the bug,
but can give you some intuition about

01:34:33.792 --> 01:34:37.672
the code, and together you're

01:34:37.752 --> 01:34:41.632
going through the desert and finding
that drink of water. At least

01:34:41.672 --> 01:34:45.342
for me, maybe it speaks to the loneliness
of the programming experience.

01:34:45.412 --> 01:34:48.452
That is a source of joy.

01:34:48.612 --> 01:34:52.552
- It's maybe also related to delayed
gratification. I'm a person who,

01:34:52.592 --> 01:34:56.392
even as a kid, I liked
the idea of Christmas

01:34:56.532 --> 01:34:59.932
presents—having them, getting
them—better than actually

01:35:00.452 --> 01:35:04.112
receiving the presents. I would
look forward to the day I get the

01:35:04.132 --> 01:35:07.952
presents, but then it's over and I'm
disappointed. And maybe it's the same

01:35:07.992 --> 01:35:11.492
with food. I think food tastes
better when you're really

01:35:11.532 --> 01:35:18.832
hungry. You're right, with debugging,
it is not always great. It's often

01:35:18.872 --> 01:35:22.862
frustrating, but then if
you can solve it, then it's

01:35:22.892 --> 01:35:26.492
great. But there's a sweet Goldilocks
zone; if it's too hard, then

01:35:26.532 --> 01:35:30.312
it's just wasting your time. But I think

01:35:30.372 --> 01:35:34.352
another challenge is how
will people learn? We

01:35:34.392 --> 01:35:37.972
looked at the chart and
saw that more senior

01:35:37.992 --> 01:35:41.982
developers are shipping more
AI-generated code than the junior ones.

01:35:42.032 --> 01:35:45.872
It's very interesting, because intuitively
you would think it's the junior developers

01:35:45.912 --> 01:35:49.672
because they don't know
how to do the thing yet,

01:35:49.732 --> 01:35:53.412
and so they use AI to do that
thing. It could mean the AI is

01:35:53.452 --> 01:35:57.152
not good enough yet to solve that
task, but it could also mean

01:35:57.232 --> 01:35:59.772
experts are more effective
at using it. They know

01:36:00.752 --> 01:36:05.312
how to use it better, review the code,
and then they trust the code more.

01:36:06.352 --> 01:36:09.912
One issue for society in the future
will be: how do you become an

01:36:09.972 --> 01:36:17.312
expert if you never try to do the thing
yourself? One way I always learned

01:36:17.392 --> 01:36:21.292
is by trying things myself. If you
look at math textbooks and the

01:36:21.312 --> 01:36:25.212
solutions, you learn something,
but you learn actually

01:36:25.252 --> 01:36:29.192
better if you try first. Then you
appreciate the solution differently

01:36:29.232 --> 01:36:32.952
because you know how to put it
into your mental framework. If

01:36:33.372 --> 01:36:37.032
LLMs are here all the time, would
you actually go to the length

01:36:37.252 --> 01:36:42.892
of struggling? Would you be willing to
struggle? Struggle is not nice, right? But

01:36:42.952 --> 01:36:46.832
if you use the LLM to do everything, at
some point you will never really take

01:36:46.872 --> 01:36:47.882
the next step, and then

01:36:48.932 --> 01:36:52.272
you will maybe not get that unlock that
you would get as an expert using an

01:36:52.372 --> 01:36:56.152
LLM. So, I think there's
like a Goldilocks sweet

01:36:56.252 --> 01:36:59.872
spot where maybe the trick
here is you make dedicated

01:36:59.912 --> 01:37:03.572
offline time where you study two hours
a day, and the rest of the day use

01:37:03.652 --> 01:37:07.522
LLMs. But I think it's important
also for people to still invest in

01:37:07.532 --> 01:37:10.892
themselves, in my opinion,
to not just LLM everything.

01:37:10.952 --> 01:37:16.522
- Yeah, as a civilization, we each individually
have to find that Goldilocks zone.

01:37:16.632 --> 01:37:20.332
And in the programming context as
developers. Now, we've had this fascinating

01:37:20.412 --> 01:37:24.252
conversation that started with
pre-training and mid-training.

01:37:24.272 --> 01:37:27.652
Let's get to post-training.
A lot of fun stuff in

01:37:27.692 --> 01:37:31.732
post-training. So, what are some of the
interesting ideas in post-training?

01:37:31.792 --> 01:37:35.052
- The biggest one from 2025 is learning this

01:37:35.492 --> 01:37:39.452
reinforcement learning with verifiable
rewards. You can scale up the training

01:37:39.472 --> 01:37:42.912
there, which means doing a lot of
this kind of iterative generate-grade

01:37:43.232 --> 01:37:47.052
loop, and that lets the
models learn both interesting

01:37:47.112 --> 01:37:51.052
behaviors on the tool use and software
side. This could be searching, running

01:37:51.132 --> 01:37:54.952
commands on their own and seeing the
outputs, and then also that training

01:37:55.012 --> 01:37:58.852
enables this inference time
scaling very nicely. And it just

01:37:58.872 --> 01:38:02.782
turned out that this paradigm was
very nicely linked, where this

01:38:02.792 --> 01:38:06.732
kind of RL training enables inference time
scaling. But inference time scaling could have

01:38:06.752 --> 01:38:10.692
been found in different ways. So, it was kind of
this perfect storm where the models change a lot,

01:38:10.992 --> 01:38:16.452
and the way that they're trained is a major
factor in doing so. And this has changed

01:38:17.212 --> 01:38:20.080
how people approach
post-training dramatically.

01:38:20.120 --> 01:38:25.759
- Can you describe RLVR, popularized by
DeepSeek R1? Can you describe how it works?

01:38:25.820 --> 01:38:29.400
- Yeah. Fun fact: I was on the
team that came up with the term

01:38:29.500 --> 01:38:33.480
RLVR, which is from our Tulu
3 work before DeepSeek. We

01:38:33.519 --> 01:38:37.299
don't take a lot of credit for being
the people to popularize the scaling

01:38:37.360 --> 01:38:41.299
RL, but as fun as what
academics get, as an

01:38:41.320 --> 01:38:43.920
aside, is the ability
to name and influence

01:38:43.929 --> 01:38:47.870
the discourse, because the closed
labs can only say so much. That

01:38:47.900 --> 01:38:51.619
one of the things you can do as an academic is
you might not have the compute to train the

01:38:51.719 --> 01:38:55.339
model, but you can frame things
in a way that ends up being

01:38:55.400 --> 01:38:59.320
described as a community coming
together around this RLVR term, which

01:38:59.339 --> 01:39:03.160
is very fun. And then DeepSeek are the
people that did the training breakthrough,

01:39:03.200 --> 01:39:06.780
which is, they scaled the
reinforcement learning. You

01:39:07.080 --> 01:39:11.059
have the model generate answers and
then grade the completion if it

01:39:11.099 --> 01:39:14.540
was right, and then that accuracy is your

01:39:14.599 --> 01:39:18.179
reward for reinforcement learning.
So reinforcement learning is

01:39:18.240 --> 01:39:22.139
classically an agent that acts in an
environment, and the environment gives

01:39:22.179 --> 01:39:25.639
it a state and a reward back,
and you try to maximize this

01:39:25.700 --> 01:39:29.460
reward. In the case of language
models, the reward is normally

01:39:29.580 --> 01:39:32.780
accuracy on a set of verifiable
tasks, whether it's math

01:39:32.839 --> 01:39:37.200
problems or coding tasks. And it
starts to get blurry with things like

01:39:38.080 --> 01:39:41.920
factual domains. That is also,
in some ways, verifiable,

01:39:41.980 --> 01:39:45.759
or constraints on your instruction,
like respond only with

01:39:45.820 --> 01:39:49.730
words that start with A." All of
these things are verifiable in

01:39:49.780 --> 01:39:53.740
some way, and the core
idea of this is you find a

01:39:53.839 --> 01:39:57.339
lot more of these problems that are
verifiable and you let the model try it

01:39:57.880 --> 01:40:00.900
many times while taking
these RL steps, these

01:40:01.219 --> 01:40:05.130
RL gradient updates. The
infrastructure evolved from

01:40:05.160 --> 01:40:09.070
reinforcement learning from human
feedback, where in that era the score

01:40:09.099 --> 01:40:12.740
they were trying to optimize was
a learned reward model of human

01:40:12.780 --> 01:40:16.690
preferences. So you kind of changed
the problem domains and that

01:40:16.719 --> 01:40:20.309
let the optimization go on to
much bigger scales, which kind of

01:40:20.320 --> 01:40:24.559
kickstarted a major change in what the
models can do and how people use them.

01:40:24.620 --> 01:40:28.519
- What kind of domains is RLVR amenable to?

01:40:28.580 --> 01:40:31.330
- Math and code are the famous
ones, and then there's a lot of

01:40:32.299 --> 01:40:36.240
work on what is called the rubrics,
which is related to a word people might

01:40:36.320 --> 01:40:40.240
have heard: LLM-as-a-judge.
For each problem,

01:40:40.280 --> 01:40:44.080
I'll have a set of problems in my
dataset. I will then have an LLM

01:40:44.160 --> 01:40:48.040
and ask it, "What would a good
answer to this problem look

01:40:48.139 --> 01:40:52.009
like?" And then you could try the
problem over and over again and

01:40:52.009 --> 01:40:55.940
assign a score based on this rubric.
That's not necessarily verifiable like

01:40:55.980 --> 01:40:59.650
math and code domains, but
this rubrics idea and other

01:40:59.679 --> 01:41:03.380
scientific problems that might be
a little bit more vague is where

01:41:03.460 --> 01:41:07.259
the attention is, where they're trying
to push this set of methods into

01:41:07.339 --> 01:41:11.120
these kind of more open-ended domains
so the models can learn a lot more.

01:41:11.179 --> 01:41:14.000
- I think that's called reinforcement
learning with AI feedback, right?

01:41:14.059 --> 01:41:17.799
- That's the older term for it coined
in Anthropic's Constitutional

01:41:17.860 --> 01:41:21.379
AI paper. It's like a lot of
these things come in cycles.

01:41:21.460 --> 01:41:25.360
- Also, just one step back
for RLVR. I think the

01:41:25.440 --> 01:41:29.280
interesting thing here is that
you ask the LLM a, let's say,

01:41:29.339 --> 01:41:33.250
math question, and then you know the
correct answer, and you let the LLM,

01:41:33.280 --> 01:41:37.240
as you said, figure it out. How
it does it—you don't constrain it

01:41:37.299 --> 01:41:41.240
much. There are some constraints like
"use the same language, don't switch

01:41:41.250 --> 01:41:44.980
between Spanish and English." But let's
say you're pretty much hands-off.

01:41:45.040 --> 01:41:48.950
You only give the question and
the answer, and then the LLM has

01:41:48.980 --> 01:41:52.719
the task to arrive at the
right answer, but the

01:41:52.740 --> 01:41:56.670
beautiful thing here is what
happens in practice: the LLM will

01:41:56.679 --> 01:41:59.880
do a step-by-step description,
like as a student or as

01:41:59.960 --> 01:42:03.950
a mathematician would derive the
solution. It will use those steps,

01:42:03.980 --> 01:42:07.639
and that helps the model to
improve its own accuracy.

01:42:07.759 --> 01:42:11.360
And then, like you said,
the inference scaling.

01:42:11.480 --> 01:42:15.259
Inference scaling loosely
means spending more compute

01:42:15.299 --> 01:42:19.799
during inference, and here
the inference scaling is

01:42:20.820 --> 01:42:24.679
that the model would use more tokens.
In the DeepSeek R1 paper, they

01:42:24.719 --> 01:42:28.679
showed the longer they train the
model, the longer the responses are.

01:42:28.700 --> 01:42:32.320
They grow over time. They use more
tokens, so it becomes more expensive.

01:42:32.339 --> 01:42:36.240
It becomes expensive for simple tasks,
but these explanations help accuracy.

01:42:36.280 --> 01:42:40.139
There are also papers showing
what the model explains

01:42:40.179 --> 01:42:44.160
does not necessarily have to be
correct or maybe it's unrelated to the

01:42:44.179 --> 01:42:47.879
answer, but for some reason, it
still helps the model that it

01:42:47.920 --> 01:42:51.580
is explaining. And I think it's
also—again, I don't want to

01:42:51.599 --> 01:42:55.360
anthropomorphize these LLMs, but it's
kind of like how we humans operate.

01:42:55.400 --> 01:42:59.040
If there's a complex math
problem in a math class,

01:42:59.080 --> 01:43:02.840
class, you usually have a note paper and
you do it step by step. You cross out

01:43:02.879 --> 01:43:06.799
things. And the model also self-corrects,
and that was, I think, the

01:43:06.860 --> 01:43:10.660
aha moment in the DeepSeek R1 paper. They called
it the aha moment because the model itself

01:43:10.679 --> 01:43:14.610
recognized it made a mistake and then said,
"Ah, I did something wrong, let me try again."

01:43:14.639 --> 01:43:18.519
And I think that's just
so cool that this falls

01:43:18.580 --> 01:43:22.490
out of just giving it the correct answer
and having it figure out how to do

01:43:22.519 --> 01:43:26.349
it, that it kind of does in a
sense what a human would do.

01:43:26.379 --> 01:43:30.340
Although LLMs don't think like humans, it's
kind of like an interesting coincidence

01:43:30.400 --> 01:43:34.360
and it... And the other nice
side effect is it's great for

01:43:34.420 --> 01:43:38.259
us humans often to see these steps.
It builds trust, but also we

01:43:38.320 --> 01:43:40.139
us humans to see these steps. It builds trust,
but also we learn and can double check things.

01:43:40.150 --> 01:43:41.230
- There's a lot in here. I think

01:43:41.230 --> 01:43:44.879
some of the debate... There's been a lot of
debate this year on if the language models

01:43:44.940 --> 01:43:48.860
like these... I think the aha moments
are kind of fake because in pre-training

01:43:49.080 --> 01:43:51.590
you essentially have
seen the whole internet.

01:43:51.620 --> 01:43:55.519
so you have definitely seen people
explaining their work, even verbally, like

01:43:55.620 --> 01:43:59.580
a transcript of a math lecture. "You try
this, oh, I messed this up." And what RLVR

01:43:59.660 --> 01:44:02.769
is very good at doing is amplifying

01:44:02.769 --> 01:44:06.620
these behaviors because they're very useful
in enabling the model to think longer and to

01:44:06.660 --> 01:44:10.468
check its work. And I agree that
it is very beautiful that this

01:44:10.528 --> 01:44:14.448
training kind of... The model learns to amplify
this in a way that is so useful for the

01:44:14.708 --> 01:44:16.938
final answers being better.

01:44:16.968 --> 01:44:20.808
- I can give you also a hands-on example. I
was training the Qwen 3 base model with

01:44:20.928 --> 01:44:28.407
RLVR on MATH-500. The base model had an
accuracy of about 15%. Just 50 steps,

01:44:28.628 --> 01:44:32.048
like in a few minutes with
RLVR, the model went from

01:44:32.108 --> 01:44:35.888
15% to 50% accuracy. And the
model... You can't tell me

01:44:35.948 --> 01:44:38.628
it's learning anything
fundamentally about math in

01:44:38.648 --> 01:44:42.628
- The Qwen example is weird because there've been
two papers this year, one of which I was on, about

01:44:42.668 --> 01:44:44.168
data contamination in Qwen

01:44:44.388 --> 01:44:48.338
and specifically that they train on a
lot of this special mid-training phase

01:44:48.367 --> 01:44:50.798
that we should take a minute
on, because it's weird

01:44:50.798 --> 01:44:53.458
because they train on problems
that are almost identical to MATH.

01:44:53.468 --> 01:44:57.308
- Exactly. And so you can
see that basically the RL,

01:44:57.448 --> 01:45:01.028
it's not teaching the model any new knowledge
about math. You can't do that in 50 steps.

01:45:01.068 --> 01:45:03.867
So the knowledge is already there, in the
pre-training, you're just unlocking it.

01:45:03.928 --> 01:45:07.827
- I still disagree with the premise because
there's a lot of weird complexities that you

01:45:07.888 --> 01:45:09.548
can't prove because

01:45:10.388 --> 01:45:14.168
one of the things that points to weirdness is
that if you take the Qwen 3 so-called base

01:45:14.268 --> 01:45:18.068
model and you... You
could Google like "math

01:45:18.168 --> 01:45:22.068
dataset, Hugging Face", and you could take
a problem and what you do if you put it

01:45:22.108 --> 01:45:26.028
into Qwen 3 base... All these math problems
have words, so it'd be like "Alice

01:45:26.068 --> 01:45:30.028
has five apples and takes one... and gives
three to whoever," and there are these

01:45:30.068 --> 01:45:33.948
word problems. With these Qwen-based
models, why people are suspicious of them

01:45:34.088 --> 01:45:36.548
is if you change the
numbers but keep the words-

01:45:36.907 --> 01:45:40.768
Qwen will produce, without
tools, will produce a

01:45:40.808 --> 01:45:43.198
very high accuracy decimal representation

01:45:43.768 --> 01:45:47.348
of the answer, which means there's
some... At some time, it was shown

01:45:47.388 --> 01:45:51.308
problems that were almost identical
to the test set, and it was using

01:45:51.388 --> 01:45:55.327
tools to get a very high precision answer,
but a language model without tools

01:45:55.348 --> 01:45:59.258
will never actually have this.
So it's kind of been this

01:45:59.268 --> 01:46:03.148
big debate in the research community:
how much of these reinforcement learning

01:46:03.188 --> 01:46:06.918
papers that are training on Qwen
and measuring specifically on this

01:46:06.928 --> 01:46:10.848
math benchmark, where there's been multiple
papers talking about contamination, is like,

01:46:10.888 --> 01:46:14.808
how much can you believe them? And I think
this is what caused the reputation of RLVR

01:46:14.848 --> 01:46:18.687
being about formatting, because you
can get these gains so quickly,

01:46:18.728 --> 01:46:22.628
therefore it must already be in the model. But
there's a lot of complexity here that we...

01:46:22.848 --> 01:46:26.916
It's not really like controlled
experimentation, so we don't really know.

01:46:26.928 --> 01:46:30.818
- But if it weren't true, I would say
distillation wouldn't work, right?

01:46:30.867 --> 01:46:34.798
I mean, distillation can work to
some extent, but the thing is that

01:46:34.848 --> 01:46:38.628
is, I think, the biggest problem, and I research this
contamination because we don't know what's in the

01:46:38.648 --> 01:46:42.628
data. Unless you have a new dataset,
it is really impossible. And the

01:46:42.668 --> 01:46:46.617
same, you mentioned the math dataset,
where you have a question and

01:46:46.648 --> 01:46:50.548
then answer and an explanation is given,
but then also even something simpler

01:46:50.608 --> 01:46:54.588
like MMLU, which is a multiple-choice
benchmark. If you just

01:46:54.648 --> 01:46:57.708
change the format slightly,
like, I don't know, if you

01:46:58.528 --> 01:47:02.458
use a dot instead of a parenthesis
or something like that, the

01:47:02.528 --> 01:47:04.848
model accuracy will vastly differ.

01:47:04.907 --> 01:47:09.268
- I think that that could be like a model
issue rather than a general issue.

01:47:09.288 --> 01:47:13.128
- It's not even malicious by the developers of the LLM,
like, "Hey, we want to cheat at that benchmark."

01:47:13.208 --> 01:47:17.148
It has seen something at some point. I
think the only fair way to evaluate an LLM

01:47:17.208 --> 01:47:22.228
is to have a new benchmark that is after
the cutoff date when the LLM was deployed.

01:47:22.288 --> 01:47:26.248
- Can we lay out what would
be the recipe of all

01:47:26.288 --> 01:47:30.197
the things that go into post-training?
And you mentioned RLVR was

01:47:30.208 --> 01:47:32.568
a really exciting, effective thing.

01:47:32.608 --> 01:47:36.518
Maybe we should elaborate. RLHF
still has a really important

01:47:36.548 --> 01:47:40.308
component to play. What kind of other
ideas are there on post-training?

01:47:40.388 --> 01:47:42.488
- I think you can kind of take
this in order. I think you could

01:47:43.407 --> 01:47:46.928
view it as what made o1, which
is this first reasoning model,

01:47:46.968 --> 01:47:50.488
possible, or what will the
latest model be? And they

01:47:50.588 --> 01:47:54.528
actually... You're going to have
similar interventions at these,

01:47:54.568 --> 01:47:58.268
where you start with mid-training,
and the thing that is

01:47:58.508 --> 01:48:02.068
rumored to enable o1 and similar
models is really careful data

01:48:02.128 --> 01:48:06.008
curation, where you're providing
a broad set of what is

01:48:06.048 --> 01:48:09.728
called reasoning traces, which
is just the model generating

01:48:09.768 --> 01:48:13.428
words in a forward process
that is reflecting, like

01:48:13.708 --> 01:48:17.608
breaking down a problem into intermediate steps
and trying to solve them. So at mid-training,

01:48:17.628 --> 01:48:18.188
you need to have

01:48:19.168 --> 01:48:22.888
data that is similar to this to make it
so that when you move into post-training,

01:48:23.088 --> 01:48:27.007
primarily with these verifiable
rewards, it can learn.

01:48:27.028 --> 01:48:30.668
And then what is happening
today is you're figuring

01:48:30.768 --> 01:48:34.468
out which problems to
give the model and how

01:48:34.548 --> 01:48:38.108
out which problems to give the model and how long
you can train it for and how much inference you can

01:48:38.148 --> 01:48:42.028
enable the model to use when solving
these verifiable problems. So as

01:48:42.048 --> 01:48:44.428
models get better, certain problems

01:48:45.407 --> 01:48:49.108
models get better, certain problems are no longer...
The model will solve them 100% of the time, and

01:48:49.128 --> 01:48:52.728
therefore there's very little signal
in this. If we look at the GRPO

01:48:52.768 --> 01:48:56.288
equation, this one is famous for
this because essentially the

01:48:56.348 --> 01:49:00.248
reward given to the agent
is based on how good

01:49:00.308 --> 01:49:04.088
a given action—an action is a
completion—is relative to the other

01:49:04.168 --> 01:49:08.068
answers to that same problem. So if all the problems
get the same answer, there's no signal in these

01:49:08.108 --> 01:49:12.048
types of algorithms. So what they're doing
is they're finding harder problems, which is

01:49:12.088 --> 01:49:15.988
why you hear about things like
scientific domains, where it's so

01:49:16.028 --> 01:49:19.818
hard to get anything right. If you
have a lab or something, it just

01:49:19.848 --> 01:49:23.588
generates so many tokens or much
harder software problems. So the

01:49:23.628 --> 01:49:27.548
frontier models are all pushing into these
harder domains when they can train on more

01:49:27.588 --> 01:49:31.488
problems and the model will learn
more skills at once. The RLHF

01:49:31.508 --> 01:49:35.248
link to this is that RLHF has been
and still is kind of like the

01:49:35.308 --> 01:49:38.168
finishing touch on the models, where
it makes the models more useful

01:49:38.988 --> 01:49:42.867
by improving the organization or style
or tone. There are different things that

01:49:42.907 --> 01:49:46.768
resonate with different audiences, like some
people like a really quirky model and RLHF could

01:49:46.808 --> 01:49:50.648
be good at enabling that
personality, and some people hate

01:49:50.708 --> 01:49:54.628
this markdown bulleted list
thing that the models do,

01:49:54.688 --> 01:49:58.568
but it's actually really good for quickly
parsing information. In RLHF, this

01:49:58.608 --> 01:50:02.588
human feedback stage is
really great for putting

01:50:02.598 --> 01:50:06.367
this into the model at the end of
the day. It's what made ChatGPT

01:50:06.468 --> 01:50:09.897
so magical for people. And that
use has actually remained fairly

01:50:09.948 --> 01:50:13.922
stable. This formatting can also help

01:50:13.922 --> 01:50:17.472
the models get better at math
problems, for example. So it's

01:50:17.532 --> 01:50:21.472
like the border between style
and formatting, and like

01:50:21.512 --> 01:50:24.432
the method that you use
to answer a problem is

01:50:24.452 --> 01:50:28.312
actually all very closely
linked in terms of when

01:50:28.352 --> 01:50:32.032
you're training these models, which is
why RLHF can still make a model better at

01:50:32.092 --> 01:50:35.912
math, but these verifiable domains
are a much more direct process to

01:50:35.972 --> 01:50:39.432
doing this because it makes
more sense with the problem

01:50:39.492 --> 01:50:43.292
formulation, which is why it ends up all
forming together. But to summarize, it's like

01:50:43.352 --> 01:50:47.072
mid-training is give the model
the skills it needs to then

01:50:47.092 --> 01:50:51.072
learn. RL with verifiable
rewards is letting the model try

01:50:51.152 --> 01:50:54.872
a lot of times, so put a lot of compute
into trial-and-error learning across hard

01:50:54.932 --> 01:50:58.832
problems. And then RLHF would be like
finishing the model, making it easy to

01:50:58.952 --> 01:51:02.012
use and kind of just
rounding the model out.

01:51:02.072 --> 01:51:05.952
- Can you comment on the amount
of compute required for RLVR?

01:51:06.012 --> 01:51:09.712
- It's only gone up and up.
I think Ilya Sutskever was

01:51:09.772 --> 01:51:12.502
famous for saying they use a similar
amount of compute for pre-training and

01:51:12.572 --> 01:51:16.412
post-training. Back to the scaling
discussion, they involve very

01:51:16.512 --> 01:51:20.212
different hardware for scaling. Pre-training
is very compute-bound, which is like this

01:51:20.332 --> 01:51:24.322
FLOPs discussion, which is just how many matrix
multiplications can you get through at once.

01:51:24.372 --> 01:51:27.982
And because with RL you're generating
these answers, you're trying the

01:51:28.052 --> 01:51:31.932
model in real-world environments, it ends
up being much more memory-bound because

01:51:31.972 --> 01:51:35.482
you're generating long sequences
and the attention mechanisms have

01:51:35.512 --> 01:51:39.402
this behavior where you get a
quadratic increase in memory

01:51:40.132 --> 01:51:43.922
as you're getting to longer sequences.
So the compute becomes very different.

01:51:43.972 --> 01:51:47.832
In pre-training we would talk about a
model—if we go back to like the Biden

01:51:47.852 --> 01:51:51.472
administration executive order, it's
like 10 to the 25th FLOPs to train a

01:51:51.512 --> 01:51:55.172
model. If you're using FLOPs in
post-training, it's a lot weirder because the

01:51:55.212 --> 01:51:58.972
reality is just like: how many hours
are you allocating? How many GPUs

01:51:59.032 --> 01:52:02.772
for? And I think in terms
of time, the RL compute is

01:52:02.812 --> 01:52:06.702
getting much closer because you just
can't put it all into one system.

01:52:06.732 --> 01:52:10.682
Pre-training is so computationally dense where
all the GPUs are talking to each other and

01:52:10.712 --> 01:52:14.512
it's extremely efficient, whereas RL has all
these moving parts and can take a long time

01:52:15.292 --> 01:52:18.372
to generate a sequence of
100,000 tokens. If you think

01:52:18.452 --> 01:52:22.391
about GPT-5.2 Pro taking an hour,
it's like, what if your training run

01:52:22.451 --> 01:52:25.492
has a sample for an hour and you have to
make sure that's handled efficiently?

01:52:25.532 --> 01:52:29.112
So I think in GPU hours
or just wall-clock hours,

01:52:29.192 --> 01:52:32.801
the RL runs are probably approaching the
same number of days as pre-training,

01:52:32.912 --> 01:52:36.812
but they probably aren't using
as many GPUs at the same time.

01:52:36.852 --> 01:52:40.772
There are rules of thumb where in
labs you don't want your pre-training

01:52:40.812 --> 01:52:44.772
runs to last more than a month because
they fail catastrophically. And if you

01:52:44.792 --> 01:52:48.332
are planning a huge cluster to be
held for two months and then it

01:52:48.392 --> 01:52:52.212
fails on day 50, the opportunity
costs are just so big.

01:52:52.332 --> 01:52:56.292
So people don't want to put
all their eggs in one basket.

01:52:56.392 --> 01:53:00.372
GPT-4 was the ultimate YOLO
run, and nobody ever wanted to

01:53:00.392 --> 01:53:04.272
do it before, where it took three months
to train and everybody was shocked that it

01:53:04.292 --> 01:53:07.432
worked. I think people are a little
bit more cautious and incremental now.

01:53:07.472 --> 01:53:11.372
- So RLVR is more, let's say, unlimited in

01:53:11.472 --> 01:53:15.342
how much you can train or still get benefit,
where RLHF, because it's a preference

01:53:15.432 --> 01:53:19.162
tuning, you reach a certain point where it
doesn't really make sense to spend more

01:53:19.252 --> 01:53:22.902
RL budget on that. So just a step
back with preference tuning:

01:53:22.972 --> 01:53:26.792
there are multiple people that
can give multiple, let's say,

01:53:26.832 --> 01:53:30.752
explanations for the same thing and they can both
be correct, but at some point you learn a certain

01:53:30.872 --> 01:53:34.612
style and it doesn't make
sense to iterate on it. My

01:53:34.652 --> 01:53:38.492
favorite example is: if relatives
ask me what laptop they should buy,

01:53:38.932 --> 01:53:42.652
I give them an explanation or
ask, "What is your use case?"

01:53:42.712 --> 01:53:46.142
They, for example,
prioritize battery life and

01:53:46.252 --> 01:53:50.112
storage. Other people like us, for
example, we would prioritize RAM and

01:53:50.212 --> 01:53:54.172
compute. Both answers are
correct, but different people

01:53:54.292 --> 01:53:58.152
require different answers. With preference
tuning, you're trying to average somehow.

01:53:58.232 --> 01:54:02.072
You are asking the data labelers
to give you, not the right,

01:54:02.132 --> 01:54:05.952
but the preferred answer and then you
train on that. But at some point you learn

01:54:05.972 --> 01:54:09.892
that average preferred answer.
And there's no reason to keep

01:54:10.272 --> 01:54:14.192
training longer on it because it's
just a style, whereas with RLVR,

01:54:14.272 --> 01:54:18.252
you let the model solve more and more

01:54:18.492 --> 01:54:22.292
complex, difficult problems. So I
think it makes more sense to allocate

01:54:22.532 --> 01:54:30.512
more budget long-term to RLVR. Also,
right now we are in an RLVR 1.0

01:54:30.771 --> 01:54:34.372
blend where it's still that simple
thing where we have a question and

01:54:34.452 --> 01:54:38.392
answer, but we don't do anything
with the stuff in between.

01:54:38.412 --> 01:54:42.152
There were multiple research
papers, also by Google for example,

01:54:42.272 --> 01:54:46.072
on process reward models that
also give scores for the

01:54:46.112 --> 01:54:49.992
explanation—how correct is the
explanation. And I think that will be the

01:54:50.052 --> 01:54:53.982
next thing, let's say
RLVR 2.0 for this year,

01:54:53.992 --> 01:54:57.732
focusing in between question and
answer, like how to leverage that

01:54:57.772 --> 01:55:01.532
information, the explanation,
to help it get better

01:55:01.592 --> 01:55:05.282
accuracy. So that's one angle.
And there was a DeepSeek

01:55:05.372 --> 01:55:08.872
Math-V2 paper where they also had

01:55:08.932 --> 01:55:12.762
interesting inference scaling
there where, first, they had

01:55:12.852 --> 01:55:16.812
developed models that grade
themselves, a separate model.

01:55:16.832 --> 01:55:20.612
And I think that will be one aspect. And
the other, like Nathan mentioned, it will

01:55:20.652 --> 01:55:23.852
be for RLVR branching into other domains.

01:55:23.892 --> 01:55:26.712
- The place where people are
excited are value functions,

01:55:26.792 --> 01:55:30.622
which is pretty similar. So process
reward models are kind of like...

01:55:30.732 --> 01:55:32.372
Process reward models assign

01:55:33.452 --> 01:55:36.912
how good something is at each
intermediate step in a reasoning

01:55:36.992 --> 01:55:40.752
process, where value functions apply
value to every token the language

01:55:40.812 --> 01:55:46.292
model generates. Both of these have
been largely unproven in the language

01:55:46.332 --> 01:55:50.192
modeling and reasoning model era.
People are more optimistic about

01:55:50.232 --> 01:55:53.932
value functions for whatever
reason now. I think process reward

01:55:53.992 --> 01:55:57.932
models were tried a lot more
in this pre-o1, pre-reasoning

01:55:57.992 --> 01:56:01.892
model era, and a lot of people had a lot of
headaches with them. So I think a lot of it is human

01:56:01.952 --> 01:56:02.762
nature...

01:56:03.692 --> 01:56:07.432
Value models have a very deep history in
reinforcement learning. They're one of the

01:56:07.472 --> 01:56:11.422
first things core to deep
reinforcement learning existing, is

01:56:11.452 --> 01:56:15.432
training value models. So
right now people are excited

01:56:15.492 --> 01:56:19.312
about trying value models, but there's
very little proof. And there are negative

01:56:19.352 --> 01:56:22.012
examples in trying to scale
up process reward models.

01:56:22.072 --> 01:56:25.791
These things don't always hold
in the future. We came to this

01:56:25.831 --> 01:56:29.572
discussion by talking about scaling.
The simple way to summarize what you're

01:56:29.592 --> 01:56:33.492
saying is you don't want to do too much
RLHF, where the signal doesn't scale.

01:56:33.512 --> 01:56:37.331
People have worked on RLHF for language
models for years, especially with intense

01:56:37.392 --> 01:56:41.331
interest after ChatGPT.
And the first release

01:56:41.452 --> 01:56:45.352
of a reasoning model trained with
RLVR, OpenAI's o1, had a scaling

01:56:45.372 --> 01:56:49.092
plot where if you increase training
compute logarithmically, you get a linear

01:56:49.132 --> 01:56:53.001
increase in evaluations. This has been
reproduced multiple times. DeepSeek

01:56:53.112 --> 01:56:57.111
had a plot like this. But there's no
scaling law for RLHF where if you

01:56:57.151 --> 01:57:01.062
log-increase the compute, you get
performance. In fact, the seminal scaling

01:57:01.152 --> 01:57:04.751
paper for RLHF is scaling laws for
reward model over-optimization.

01:57:05.152 --> 01:57:08.772
So that's a big line to
draw with RLVR and the

01:57:08.831 --> 01:57:12.492
methods we have now. In the future,
they will follow this scaling

01:57:13.232 --> 01:57:17.052
paradigm: where you can let
the best runs run for an

01:57:17.132 --> 01:57:20.441
extra 10x and you get performance,
but you can't do this with

01:57:20.552 --> 01:57:24.472
RLHF. And that is just going to be
field-defining in how people approach

01:57:24.482 --> 01:57:28.472
them. While I'm a shill for
people to academically do RLHF,

01:57:28.512 --> 01:57:32.501
to do the best RLHF you might not

01:57:32.532 --> 01:57:36.352
need the extra 10 or 100x of
compute, but to do the best

01:57:37.472 --> 01:57:41.092
RLVR you do. I think
there's a seminal paper

01:57:41.132 --> 01:57:45.012
from a Meta internship. It's
called something like "The Art of

01:57:45.022 --> 01:57:48.872
Scaling Reinforcement Learning with
Language Models." What they describe as a

01:57:48.912 --> 01:57:52.172
framework is Scale-RL. Their
incremental experiment

01:57:52.972 --> 01:57:56.791
was like 10,000 V100 hours,
which is like thousands or

01:57:56.831 --> 01:58:00.632
tens of thousands of dollars per
experiment. They do a lot of them, and

01:58:00.692 --> 01:58:04.192
This cost is not accessible to the average

01:58:04.291 --> 01:58:07.052
academic, which is a
hard equilibrium where

01:58:07.892 --> 01:58:11.152
it's trying to figure out how
to learn from each community.

01:58:11.192 --> 01:58:14.952
- I was wondering if we could take
a bit of a tangent and talk

01:58:15.012 --> 01:58:18.932
about education and learning.
If you're someone listening

01:58:18.972 --> 01:58:22.652
to this who's a smart person
interested in programming

01:58:22.692 --> 01:58:27.422
and AI, I presume building something
from scratch is a good beginning.

01:58:28.232 --> 01:58:31.522
So can you take me through what
you would recommend people do?

01:58:32.052 --> 01:58:35.952
- I would personally start, like you
said, implementing a simple model from

01:58:35.992 --> 01:58:39.732
scratch that you can run on
your computer. The goal is not,

01:58:39.751 --> 01:58:43.012
when you build a model from scratch,
to have something for every day use.

01:58:43.032 --> 01:58:46.912
It's not going to be your
personal assistant replacing

01:58:46.972 --> 01:58:50.852
an existing open-weight model or
ChatGPT. It's to see what exactly

01:58:50.892 --> 01:58:54.852
goes into the LLM, what comes out,
and how the pre-training works

01:58:54.892 --> 01:58:58.672
on your own computer, preferably.

01:58:59.152 --> 01:59:02.812
Then you learn about pre-training,
supervised fine-tuning, and the

01:59:02.852 --> 01:59:06.782
attention mechanism. You get a solid
understanding of how things work, but

01:59:06.831 --> 01:59:10.652
at some point you reach a limit, because
small models can only do so much.

01:59:11.232 --> 01:59:15.032
The problem with learning about
LLMs at scale is that it's

01:59:15.092 --> 01:59:18.942
exponentially more complex
to make a larger model,

01:59:18.992 --> 01:59:22.782
because the model isn't just
larger—you have to shard your

01:59:22.791 --> 01:59:26.772
parameters across multiple GPUs. Even
for the KV cache, there are multiple

01:59:26.831 --> 01:59:30.802
ways to implement it. One is just to
understand how it works, just to grow the

01:59:30.892 --> 01:59:34.852
cache. You grow it step-by-step
by, let's say, concatenating

01:59:34.992 --> 01:59:38.681
lists, but then that
wouldn't be optimal on

01:59:38.712 --> 01:59:42.501
GPUs. You would pre-allocate
a tensor and then fill it in.

01:59:42.572 --> 01:59:46.452
But that adds another 20 or 30
lines of code. And for each thing,

01:59:46.532 --> 01:59:50.392
you add so much code. The goal with
the book is basically to understand

01:59:50.452 --> 01:59:54.412
how the LLM works. It's not going to be a
production-level LLM, but once you have

01:59:54.432 --> 01:59:56.572
that, you can understand
the production-level LLM.

01:59:56.592 --> 02:00:00.251
- So you're trying to always build an
LLM that's going to fit on one GPU?

02:00:00.331 --> 02:00:03.992
- Yes. Most of them do. I have
some bonus materials on some

02:00:04.192 --> 02:00:08.152
MoE models. One or two of them
may require multiple GPUs,

02:00:08.552 --> 02:00:12.132
but the goal is to have it on one
GPU. And the beautiful thing is,

02:00:12.712 --> 02:00:16.592
you can self-verify. It's almost
like RLVR. When you code these from

02:00:16.672 --> 02:00:20.452
scratch, you can take an existing
model from the Hugging Face

02:00:20.512 --> 02:00:24.501
Transformers library. The
library is great, but if

02:00:24.532 --> 02:00:28.352
you want to learn about LLMs, it's not
the best place to start because the

02:00:28.412 --> 02:00:32.242
code is so complex to
fit so many use cases.

02:00:32.291 --> 02:00:35.912
Because people use it in production,
it has to be really sophisticated,

02:00:35.972 --> 02:00:39.032
really intertwined, and hard
to read. It's not linear.

02:00:39.052 --> 02:00:42.902
- It started as a fine-tuning
library, and then it grew to be the

02:00:42.992 --> 02:00:44.791
standard representation of
every model architecture.

02:00:45.612 --> 02:00:49.592
Hugging Face is the default place to get a
model, and Transformers is the software.

02:00:49.632 --> 02:00:56.672
It enables it so people can easily load
a model and do something basic with it.

02:00:56.712 --> 02:01:00.452
- And all frontier labs that have
open-weight models have a Transformers

02:01:00.552 --> 02:01:03.732
version of it, like from DeepSeek
to gpt-oss-120b. That's the

02:01:03.772 --> 02:01:07.692
canonical weight format
you can load. But even

02:01:07.712 --> 02:01:11.102
even Transformers, the library, is
not used in production. People use

02:01:11.232 --> 02:01:15.112
SGLang or vLLM, and it adds
another layer of complexity.

02:01:15.172 --> 02:01:19.032
- We should say that the Transformers
library has like 400 models.

02:01:19.112 --> 02:01:22.751
- So it's the one library that tries
to implement a lot of LLMs, and

02:01:23.552 --> 02:01:26.782
so you have a huge codebase,
basically. It's huge. It's

02:01:26.832 --> 02:01:30.192
like, I don't know, maybe millions—

02:01:30.212 --> 02:01:30.282
- That's crazy.

02:01:30.282 --> 02:01:34.132
- hundreds of thousands of lines
of code. Understanding the part

02:01:34.272 --> 02:01:37.712
you want to understand is finding the needle
in the haystack. But what's beautiful is

02:01:38.112 --> 02:01:41.802
you have a working implementation, so
you can work backwards. What I would

02:01:42.492 --> 02:01:46.452
recommend doing, or what I also do, is if I
want to understand, for example, how OLMo

02:01:46.472 --> 02:01:50.452
is implemented, I would look at the
weights in the model hub, the config file,

02:01:50.492 --> 02:01:54.272
and then you can see, "Oh,
they used so many layers. They

02:01:54.332 --> 02:01:58.182
use, let's say, Group Query Attention
or Multi-Head Attention in that case."

02:01:58.212 --> 02:02:01.952
Then you see all the components in a
human-readable, 100-line config file.

02:02:01.992 --> 02:02:05.642
And then you start, let's say, with
your GPT-2 model and add these things.

02:02:05.672 --> 02:02:09.592
The cool thing here is you can
then load the pretrained weights

02:02:09.712 --> 02:02:13.532
and see if they work in your
model. You want to match the

02:02:13.592 --> 02:02:17.572
same output that you get with a Transformer
model, and then you can use that,

02:02:17.612 --> 02:02:21.552
basically as a verifiable reward
to make your architecture correct.

02:02:21.572 --> 02:02:25.291
Sometimes it takes me a day. With
OLMo 3, the challenge was RoPE

02:02:25.312 --> 02:02:29.012
for the position embeddings.
They had a YaRN extension

02:02:29.072 --> 02:02:32.692
and there was some custom scaling there,

02:02:32.791 --> 02:02:36.501
and I couldn't quite match
these things. In this struggle,

02:02:36.751 --> 02:02:40.732
you kind of understand things. At the
end, you know you have it correct

02:02:40.772 --> 02:02:44.492
because you can unit test it. You
can check against the reference

02:02:44.552 --> 02:02:48.371
implementation. I think that's one
of the best ways to learn, really.

02:02:48.432 --> 02:02:51.232
To basically reverse-engineer something.

02:02:51.312 --> 02:02:54.832
- I think that is something everyone
interested in getting into AI

02:02:55.212 --> 02:02:59.132
today should do. That's why
I liked your book. I came to

02:02:59.192 --> 02:03:03.152
language models from the RL and
robotics field. I had never taken the

02:03:03.192 --> 02:03:06.902
time to just learn all the fundamentals.

02:03:06.932 --> 02:03:10.912
This transformer architecture
is so fundamental, just as deep

02:03:10.932 --> 02:03:14.832
learning was in the past,
and people need to do this.

02:03:14.842 --> 02:03:18.832
I think where a lot of
people get overwhelmed

02:03:18.892 --> 02:03:22.692
is, "How do I apply this to have
impact or find a career path?"

02:03:22.732 --> 02:03:26.412
Because language models make this
fundamental stuff so accessible,

02:03:26.532 --> 02:03:30.462
and people with motivation
will learn it. Then it's like,

02:03:30.472 --> 02:03:34.112
"How do I get cycles on goal
to contribute to research?"

02:03:34.132 --> 02:03:37.772
I'm actually fairly optimistic
because the field moves so fast

02:03:37.812 --> 02:03:41.782
that a lot of times the best
people don't fully solve a problem

02:03:41.892 --> 02:03:45.732
because there's a bigger problem to
solve that's very low-hanging fruit,

02:03:45.772 --> 02:03:49.732
so they move on. I think that a lot
of what I was trying to do in this

02:03:49.792 --> 02:03:53.652
RLHF book is take post-training
techniques and describe how

02:03:53.692 --> 02:03:57.612
people think about them influencing
the model and what people are doing.

02:03:57.652 --> 02:04:01.232
Then it's remarkable how many things

02:04:01.412 --> 02:04:05.252
I just think people stop
studying or don't pursue.

02:04:05.372 --> 02:04:07.792
I think people trying to go narrow
after doing the fundamentals is good,

02:04:08.732 --> 02:04:12.552
and then reading the relevant papers

02:04:12.592 --> 02:04:16.052
and being engaged in the ecosystem.
It's like you actually...

02:04:16.152 --> 02:04:19.832
actually... The proximity that
random people online have

02:04:19.872 --> 02:04:23.352
to the leading researchers—no
one knows who all the...

02:04:23.952 --> 02:04:27.872
The anonymous accounts on X and ML are
very popular, and no one knows who

02:04:27.912 --> 02:04:31.882
all these people are. It could just be random people
that study this stuff deeply, especially with

02:04:31.912 --> 02:04:35.792
the AI tools. To just be like, "I don't
understand this, keep digging into it," is a

02:04:35.832 --> 02:04:39.592
very useful thing. But there's
a lot of research areas that

02:04:39.632 --> 02:04:43.482
maybe have three papers that
you need to read, and then

02:04:43.512 --> 02:04:47.482
one of the authors will probably email
you back. But you have to put in a lot

02:04:47.512 --> 02:04:51.142
of effort into these emails to
understand the field. I think it would

02:04:51.212 --> 02:04:54.902
be for a newcomer easily weeks
of work to feel like they can

02:04:54.932 --> 02:04:58.752
truly grasp what is a very
narrow area, but I think going

02:04:58.762 --> 02:05:02.172
narrow after you have the fundamentals
will be very useful to people because

02:05:02.912 --> 02:05:06.892
I've become very interested in
character training, which is how you

02:05:07.232 --> 02:05:11.152
make the model funny or
sarcastic or serious,

02:05:11.212 --> 02:05:14.962
and what do you do to the
data to do this? A student

02:05:15.052 --> 02:05:18.512
at Oxford reached out to me and was like, "Hey,
I'm interested in this," and I advised him.

02:05:18.522 --> 02:05:22.352
And that paper now exists.
There's like two or

02:05:22.432 --> 02:05:26.212
three people in the world that were very
interested in this. He's a PhD student, which

02:05:26.252 --> 02:05:27.652
gives him an advantage, but

02:05:28.572 --> 02:05:32.232
for me, that was a topic I was waiting for
someone to be like, "Hey, I have time to spend

02:05:32.252 --> 02:05:36.232
cycles on this." I'm sure there's a lot more
very narrow things where you're just like,

02:05:36.312 --> 02:05:39.612
"It doesn't make sense that there was
no answer to this." I think it's just

02:05:40.352 --> 02:05:44.132
there's so much information coming that
people are like, "I can't grab onto any of

02:05:44.192 --> 02:05:48.712
these," but if you just stick in an area, I think
there's a lot of interesting things to learn.

02:05:48.752 --> 02:05:52.682
- Yeah, I think you can't try to do it all
because it would be very overwhelming and

02:05:52.712 --> 02:05:56.422
you would burn out. For me, for
example, I haven't kept up with

02:05:56.432 --> 02:06:00.352
computer vision in a long time; I just focused
on LLMs. But coming back to your book,

02:06:00.392 --> 02:06:04.341
I think this is a really great book and
a really good bang for the buck because

02:06:04.372 --> 02:06:08.012
if you want to learn about RLHF, I
wouldn't go out there and read RLHF

02:06:08.032 --> 02:06:10.382
papers because you would
be spending two years—

02:06:10.392 --> 02:06:11.222
- Some of them contradict.

02:06:11.232 --> 02:06:15.032
I've just edited the book, and there's
no chapter where I had to be like,

02:06:15.712 --> 02:06:19.492
"X papers say one thing and Y papers
say another, and we'll see what

02:06:19.532 --> 02:06:21.522
comes out to be true."

02:06:21.572 --> 02:06:25.372
- Just to go through the table of contents, what
are some ideas we might have missed in the

02:06:25.432 --> 02:06:29.172
bigger picture of post-training? First of
all, you did the problem setup, training

02:06:29.232 --> 02:06:32.932
overview, what are preferences,
preference data, and the optimization

02:06:33.032 --> 02:06:36.912
tools, reward modeling,
regularization, instruction tuning,

02:06:36.972 --> 02:06:43.452
rejection sampling, and
reinforcement learning. Then,

02:06:43.512 --> 02:06:47.092
Constitutional AI and AI feedback,
reasoning, and inference-time

02:06:47.152 --> 02:06:50.992
scaling to use in function calling,
synthetic data and distillation,

02:06:51.152 --> 02:06:54.292
evaluation, and then an
open questions section,

02:06:54.392 --> 02:06:58.072
over-optimization, style and
information, and then product

02:06:58.172 --> 02:07:01.992
UX, character and post-training.
What are some ideas worth

02:07:02.332 --> 02:07:05.952
mentioning that connect both the
educational and the research components?

02:07:06.012 --> 02:07:08.141
You mentioned character training,
which is pretty interesting.

02:07:08.251 --> 02:07:12.191
- Character training is interesting because there's
so little on it. We talked about how people

02:07:12.201 --> 02:07:16.162
engage with these models. We
feel good using them because

02:07:16.192 --> 02:07:19.872
they're positive, but that can go too far;
it can be too positive. And it's like,

02:07:19.882 --> 02:07:22.292
essentially, it's: How
do you change your data

02:07:23.172 --> 02:07:27.112
and decision-making to make it
exactly what you want? And like,

02:07:27.152 --> 02:07:30.782
OpenAI has this thing called a model
spec, which is essentially their

02:07:30.782 --> 02:07:34.772
internal guideline for what they want the
model to do, and they publish this to

02:07:34.792 --> 02:07:38.522
developers. So, essentially, you
can know what is a failure of

02:07:38.552 --> 02:07:42.502
OpenAI's training—where they have the
intentions and they haven't met them yet—

02:07:42.552 --> 02:07:46.042
versus what is something that they actually
wanted to do and that you don't like.

02:07:46.072 --> 02:07:49.892
And that transparency is very nice,
but all the methods for curating these

02:07:49.902 --> 02:07:53.792
documents and how easy it is to follow
them is not very well known. I think the

02:07:53.852 --> 02:07:57.792
way the book is designed is that the RL
chapter is obviously what people want because

02:07:57.832 --> 02:08:01.532
everybody hears about it with RLVR, and
it's the same algorithms and the same

02:08:01.572 --> 02:08:05.512
math, but you can use it in
very different documents.

02:08:05.532 --> 02:08:08.972
So I think the core of
RLHF is like how messy

02:08:09.082 --> 02:08:12.932
preferences are. It's essentially
a rehash of a paper I

02:08:12.952 --> 02:08:16.412
wrote years ago, but this is essentially
the chapter that'll tell you why

02:08:16.532 --> 02:08:20.132
RLHF is never ever fully solvable because,

02:08:21.092 --> 02:08:28.552
the way that even RL is set up, it
assumes that preferences can be

02:08:28.632 --> 02:08:32.572
quantified and that multiple
preferences can be reduced

02:08:32.652 --> 02:08:36.612
to single values. And I think it relates
in the economics literature to the

02:08:36.632 --> 02:08:40.592
Von Neumann-Morgenstern utility theorem,
and that is the chapter where all

02:08:40.652 --> 02:08:44.232
of that philosophical,
economic, and psychological

02:08:44.332 --> 02:08:48.312
context tells you what gets compressed
into doing RLHF. So it's like you

02:08:48.372 --> 02:08:52.212
have all of this and then later in the book
it's like: You use this RL map to make the

02:08:52.232 --> 02:08:55.972
number go up. And I think that's why
it'll be very rewarding for people to do

02:08:56.012 --> 02:08:59.892
research on, because quantifying
preferences is something

02:08:59.952 --> 02:09:03.902
that humans have designed
a problem in order to

02:09:03.942 --> 02:09:07.202
make preferences studyable. But there's
kind of fundamental debates, like,

02:09:08.042 --> 02:09:12.022
an example is in a language model response you
have different things you care about, like

02:09:12.042 --> 02:09:15.822
accuracy or style. And when you're
collecting the data, they all get compressed

02:09:15.862 --> 02:09:19.522
into: "I like this more
than another." And that is

02:09:19.562 --> 02:09:23.502
happening, and there's a lot of
research in other areas of the

02:09:23.542 --> 02:09:26.702
world that go into how you
should actually do this. I think

02:09:27.282 --> 02:09:28.802
social choice theory is the

02:09:29.682 --> 02:09:33.412
subfield of economics around how
you should aggregate preferences.

02:09:33.482 --> 02:09:37.462
And I went to a workshop
that published a white

02:09:37.482 --> 02:09:40.462
paper on: "How can you think about
using social choice theory for

02:09:40.582 --> 02:09:44.342
RLHF?" So I mostly would want people
that get excited about the math to

02:09:44.382 --> 02:09:48.082
come and find things where they
could stumble into this broader

02:09:48.182 --> 02:09:52.002
context. I think there's a fun thing:
I just keep a list of all the tech

02:09:52.042 --> 02:09:55.942
reports of reasoning models
I like. So in Chapter 14,

02:09:56.002 --> 02:09:59.882
where there's a short summary of RLVR,
there's just a gigantic table where I

02:09:59.922 --> 02:10:03.851
list every single reasoning
model that I like.

02:10:03.882 --> 02:10:08.412
I think in education, a lot of it needs
to be like, at this point, what I like,

02:10:08.412 --> 02:10:12.392
because the language models are so
good at the math. For example, the

02:10:12.442 --> 02:10:16.402
famous paper, Direct Preference Optimization,
which is a much simpler way of solving

02:10:16.422 --> 02:10:20.342
the problem than RL. The derivations
in the appendix skip steps

02:10:20.402 --> 02:10:24.312
of math. And for this book, I redid
the derivations and I'm like,

02:10:24.312 --> 02:10:27.782
"What the heck is this log trick
that they use to change the math?"

02:10:27.842 --> 02:10:30.972
But doing it with language models, they're
like, "This is the log trick." And I'm

02:10:31.022 --> 02:10:34.602
like, "I don't know if I like this,
that the math is so commoditized."

02:10:34.662 --> 02:10:38.872
I think some of the struggle
in reading this appendix-

02:10:38.872 --> 02:10:43.932
...and following the math
is good for learning.

02:10:43.962 --> 02:10:47.952
- Yeah, we're returning to this
often on the topic of education.

02:10:47.962 --> 02:10:51.682
You both have brought up the
word "struggle" quite a bit.

02:10:51.762 --> 02:10:55.712
So there is value. If you're not
struggling as part of this process,

02:10:55.722 --> 02:10:59.642
you're not fully following the
proper process for learning.

02:10:59.722 --> 02:11:02.342
proper process for learning, I suppose.

02:11:02.362 --> 02:11:06.242
- Some providers are working on models
for education designed to not give-

02:11:06.422 --> 02:11:10.262
actually, I haven't used them, but I'd
guess they're designed to not give

02:11:10.341 --> 02:11:11.841
all the information at once.

02:11:12.182 --> 02:11:16.162
And make people work for it. Training models
to do this would be a wonderful contribution.

02:11:16.202 --> 02:11:19.842
Where, like all of the stuff in the book,
you had to reevaluate every decision.

02:11:19.882 --> 02:11:24.682
decision for it- It's a great example.
There's a chance we work on it at Ai2,

02:11:24.722 --> 02:11:26.592
which I thought would be so fun.

02:11:26.602 --> 02:11:30.502
- It makes sense. I did something like
that the other day for video games.

02:11:30.602 --> 02:11:33.911
Sometimes for pastime I play
video games, like I like-

02:11:34.002 --> 02:11:37.982
Video games with puzzles, like
Zelda and Metroid. And there's this

02:11:38.042 --> 02:11:41.762
new game where I really got
stuck and was okay with it.

02:11:41.842 --> 02:11:45.602
I don't want to struggle for
two days, so I used an LLM.

02:11:45.682 --> 02:11:49.382
But then you say, "Hey, please don't add
spoilers. Just, you know, I'm here and there.

02:11:49.462 --> 02:11:53.312
What do I have to do next?" You can do
the same thing for math where you say,

02:11:53.402 --> 02:11:57.272
"Okay, I'm stuck at this point.
Don't give me the full solution,

02:11:57.362 --> 02:12:01.322
but what is something I could try?"
Where you carefully probe it.

02:12:01.362 --> 02:12:05.351
But the problem here is I
think it requires discipline.

02:12:05.362 --> 02:12:09.202
Many people enjoy math, but
there are also a lot of people

02:12:09.222 --> 02:12:13.131
who need to do it for their homework,
and then it's like a shortcut.

02:12:13.162 --> 02:12:17.022
We could develop an educational LLM,
but other LLMs are still there,

02:12:17.102 --> 02:12:20.102
and there's still a temptation
to use the other LLMs.

02:12:20.182 --> 02:12:23.982
- I think many people in college understand
the stuff they're passionate about-

02:12:24.042 --> 02:12:27.892
about- ...they're self-aware and they
understand it shouldn't be easy.

02:12:27.892 --> 02:12:31.062
I think we just have to
develop a good taste-

02:12:31.222 --> 02:12:34.872
...talk about research
taste, school taste about

02:12:34.982 --> 02:12:37.312
stuff that you should be struggling on-

02:12:37.622 --> 02:12:40.932
...and stuff you shouldn't be. It's tricky,
because you don't have good long-term vision

02:12:40.942 --> 02:12:44.922
sometimes you don't have
good long-term vision

02:12:44.962 --> 02:12:47.942
about what would be actually
useful to you in your career.

02:12:48.062 --> 02:12:51.691
But you have to develop that taste, yeah.

02:12:51.742 --> 02:12:55.482
- I was talking to my fiancee
or friends about this,

02:12:55.962 --> 02:12:59.682
there's this brief 10-year window
where all of the homework and all the

02:12:59.842 --> 02:13:03.642
exams could be digital. Before that, everybody
had to do all the exams in blue books

02:13:03.662 --> 02:13:07.622
because there was no other way. And now after AI,
everyone's going to need to be in blue books and

02:13:07.642 --> 02:13:11.522
oral exams because everyone could cheat so easily.
It's like this brief generation that had a

02:13:11.582 --> 02:13:14.882
different education system
where everything could be

02:13:15.002 --> 02:13:18.661
digital, but you still couldn't
cheat. And now it's just going back.

02:13:18.981 --> 02:13:20.722
It's just very funny.

02:13:20.802 --> 02:13:24.102
- You mention character training.
Just zooming out on a more general

02:13:24.142 --> 02:13:27.842
topic, for that project
how much compute was

02:13:27.862 --> 02:13:30.722
required? And in general,
to contribute as a

02:13:30.802 --> 02:13:34.702
researcher, are there places where not too

02:13:34.742 --> 02:13:38.012
much compute is required where you can
actually contribute as an individual

02:13:38.042 --> 02:13:39.282
researcher?

02:13:39.442 --> 02:13:43.162
- For the character training thing, I think
this research is built on fine-tuning

02:13:43.222 --> 02:13:47.122
about 7 billion parameter
models with LoRA, which is

02:13:47.182 --> 02:13:50.912
essentially only fine-tuning a small
subset of the weights of the model.

02:13:51.082 --> 02:13:55.002
I don't know exactly how many
GPU hours that would take.

02:13:55.042 --> 02:13:55.922
- But it's doable.

02:13:55.982 --> 02:13:59.922
- Not doable for every academic. The
situation for some academics is so dire

02:13:59.962 --> 02:14:03.912
that the only work you can do is doing
inference where you have closed models or open

02:14:03.982 --> 02:14:07.402
models and you get completions from them
and you can look at them and understand the

02:14:07.422 --> 02:14:11.222
models. And that's very well-suited
to evaluation, where you want to

02:14:11.262 --> 02:14:14.682
be the best at creating representative

02:14:14.722 --> 02:14:18.622
problems that the models fail on or
show certain abilities, which I think

02:14:18.632 --> 02:14:22.492
that you can break through
with this. I think that

02:14:22.542 --> 02:14:26.482
the top-end goal for a researcher
working on evaluation, if you

02:14:26.542 --> 02:14:29.952
want to have career momentum, is
that Frontier Labs pick up your

02:14:29.952 --> 02:14:33.902
evaluation. You don't need to have
every project do this. But if you

02:14:33.942 --> 02:14:37.922
go from a small university with no compute and
find something that Claude struggles with,

02:14:37.992 --> 02:14:41.862
and then the next Claude model has
it in the blog post, there's your

02:14:41.962 --> 02:14:45.662
career rocket ship. I think
that's hard, but if you want to

02:14:45.702 --> 02:14:49.622
scope the maximum possible impact
with minimum compute, it's something

02:14:49.642 --> 02:14:53.522
like that, which is just get very narrow
and it takes learning of where the

02:14:53.562 --> 02:14:57.362
models are going. So you need
to build a tool that tests

02:14:57.542 --> 02:15:01.462
where Claude 4.5 will fail.
If I'm going to start

02:15:01.502 --> 02:15:05.292
a research project, I need to think where the
models in eight months are going to be struggling.

02:15:05.782 --> 02:15:08.122
- But what about developing
totally novel ideas?

02:15:08.630 --> 02:15:12.450
- This is a trade-off. I think that if you're
doing a PhD, you could also be like,

02:15:13.210 --> 02:15:17.120
"It's too risky to work in language
models. I'm going way longer term,"

02:15:17.150 --> 02:15:19.130
which is like what is—

02:15:19.210 --> 02:15:22.730
what is the thing that's going to define
language model development in 10 years?

02:15:22.750 --> 02:15:26.630
I end up being a person that's
pretty practical. I mean, I went to

02:15:26.690 --> 02:15:30.630
my PhD where it was like, "I got into Berkeley.
Worst case, I get a master's, and then I go

02:15:30.730 --> 02:15:33.350
work in tech." I'm very
practical about it, so I'm like

02:15:34.750 --> 02:15:38.710
the life afforded to people to work at
these AI companies, the amount of...

02:15:38.830 --> 02:15:42.550
OpenAI's average compensation is over
a million dollars in stock a year per

02:15:42.590 --> 02:15:46.570
employee. For any normal
person in the US, to

02:15:46.630 --> 02:15:50.440
get into this AI lab is transformative for
your life. So I'm pretty practical about it.

02:15:50.710 --> 02:15:53.910
there's still a lot of upward mobility
working in language models if you're

02:15:53.950 --> 02:15:57.530
focused. And look at these jobs.
But from a research perspective,

02:15:57.550 --> 02:15:59.840
the transformative impact in these

02:16:00.830 --> 02:16:04.630
academic awards... to be the next
Yann LeCun is from not working on—

02:16:04.690 --> 02:16:07.330
not caring about language
model development very much.

02:16:07.350 --> 02:16:09.450
- It's a big financial
sacrifice in that case.

02:16:09.650 --> 02:16:13.550
- So I work with some awesome students, and
they're like, "Should I go work at an

02:16:13.590 --> 02:16:17.450
AI lab?" And I'm like, "You're getting
a PhD at a top school. Are you gonna

02:16:17.470 --> 02:16:21.440
leave to go to a lab?" I don't
know. If you go work at a top lab,

02:16:21.530 --> 02:16:25.410
I don't blame you. Don't go work at some random
startup that might go to zero. But if you're going to

02:16:25.450 --> 02:16:29.390
OpenAI, I'm like, "It could
be worth leaving a PhD for."

02:16:30.050 --> 02:16:33.930
- Let's more rigorously think
through this. So where would you

02:16:33.969 --> 02:16:37.830
give a recommendation for people to do
a research contribution? So the options

02:16:37.870 --> 02:16:43.490
are academia: get a PhD.
Spend five years publishing.

02:16:44.370 --> 02:16:46.750
Compute resources are
constrained. There's—

02:16:46.850 --> 02:16:53.389
there's research labs that are more
focused on open-weight models,

02:16:54.610 --> 02:17:01.610
and working there. Or closed
frontier research labs.

02:17:01.870 --> 02:17:04.090
So OpenAI, Anthropic, xAI, and so on.

02:17:04.190 --> 02:17:08.010
- The two gradients are: the more closed,
the more money you tend to get,

02:17:08.070 --> 02:17:12.910
but you also get less
credit. In terms of building

02:17:13.830 --> 02:17:18.930
a portfolio of things that
you've done, it's very clear

02:17:18.969 --> 02:17:22.650
what you have done as an academic.
Versus if you are going to

02:17:22.850 --> 02:17:26.570
trade this fairly reasonable

02:17:26.590 --> 02:17:30.520
progression for being a cog in the
machine, which could also be very fun.

02:17:30.549 --> 02:17:34.130
So I think it's very different
career paths. But the

02:17:34.170 --> 02:17:37.740
opportunity cost for being a researcher
is very high because PhD students are

02:17:37.770 --> 02:17:41.410
paid essentially nothing. So it ends
up rewarding people that have a

02:17:41.430 --> 02:17:45.370
fairly stable safety net, and they
realize that they can operate in the

02:17:45.410 --> 02:17:49.039
long term, wanting to do very interesting
work and get a very interesting job.

02:17:49.070 --> 02:17:53.030
So it is a privileged position to be like,

02:17:53.049 --> 02:17:58.170
"I'm gonna see out my PhD and figure it
out after because I want to do this."

02:17:59.070 --> 02:18:02.879
At the same time, the academic ecosystem
is getting bombarded by funding

02:18:02.990 --> 02:18:06.330
getting cut and stuff. So there's just
so many different trade-offs where I

02:18:06.389 --> 02:18:10.159
understand plenty of people that are like,
"I don't enjoy it. I can't deal with this

02:18:10.190 --> 02:18:14.120
funding search. My grant got cut
for no reason by the government,"

02:18:14.150 --> 02:18:18.010
or, "I don't know what's gonna
happen." So I think there's a lot of

02:18:18.110 --> 02:18:20.960
uncertainty and trade-offs
that, in my opinion, favor just

02:18:21.870 --> 02:18:25.790
taking the well-paying job with
meaningful impact. It's not like

02:18:25.830 --> 02:18:29.780
you're getting paid to sit around at OpenAI.
You're building the cutting edge of things

02:18:29.830 --> 02:18:34.750
that are— changing millions of
people's relationship to tech.

02:18:34.790 --> 02:18:38.410
- But publication-wise, they're being
more secretive, increasingly so.

02:18:38.510 --> 02:18:42.230
So you're publishing less and
less. And so you are having

02:18:42.290 --> 02:18:47.590
a positive impact at scale, but
you're a cog in the machine.

02:18:47.690 --> 02:18:51.670
- I think it honestly
hasn't changed that much.

02:18:51.770 --> 02:18:55.530
I have been in academia. I'm
not in academia anymore.

02:18:55.570 --> 02:18:59.469
wouldn't want to miss my time in academia.
But what I wanted to say before I get to that

02:18:59.510 --> 02:19:03.379
is that I think it hasn't changed
that much. I was working in

02:19:03.490 --> 02:19:07.180
computational biology, using
AI or machine learning methods

02:19:07.210 --> 02:19:15.110
with collaborators, and a lot of
people went from academia directly to

02:19:15.150 --> 02:19:19.090
Google. And I think it's the
same. Back then, professors were

02:19:19.130 --> 02:19:22.889
sad that their students went into industry

02:19:22.930 --> 02:19:26.920
because they couldn't carry on their
legacy. I think it's the same.

02:19:26.930 --> 02:19:30.860
It hasn't changed that much.
The only thing that has

02:19:30.889 --> 02:19:34.870
changed is the scale. Cool
stuff was always developed in

02:19:34.910 --> 02:19:38.830
industry that was closed.
You couldn't talk about it.

02:19:38.870 --> 02:19:42.730
And I think the difference
now is your preference.

02:19:42.809 --> 02:19:46.630
Do you like to publish your
work, or are you more in a

02:19:46.690 --> 02:19:50.650
closed lab? That's one difference.
The compensation, of course,

02:19:50.690 --> 02:19:54.430
is another, but it's
always been like that.

02:19:54.470 --> 02:19:58.010
It depends on where you feel
comfortable. And nothing is

02:19:58.050 --> 02:20:02.019
forever. Right now, there's
a third option, which is

02:20:02.030 --> 02:20:05.170
launching a startup. A lot
of people are doing that.

02:20:05.270 --> 02:20:09.250
It's a very risky move, but it can be

02:20:09.290 --> 02:20:13.210
a high-risk, high-reward situation,
whereas joining an industry lab

02:20:13.290 --> 02:20:17.270
is pretty safe. You also
have upward mobility.

02:20:17.350 --> 02:20:21.190
I think once you've been at an
industry lab, it's easier to find

02:20:21.230 --> 02:20:28.310
future jobs. But then again,
how much do you enjoy the team

02:20:28.430 --> 02:20:32.210
and working on proprietary
things versus how much you like

02:20:32.250 --> 02:20:35.570
publishing work? I mean,
publishing is stressful.

02:20:35.650 --> 02:20:39.590
Acceptance rates at
conferences can be arbitrary

02:20:39.610 --> 02:20:43.590
and very frustrating, but it's
high reward if you have a paper

02:20:43.630 --> 02:20:48.250
published. You feel good because your name
is on there. It's a high accomplishment.

02:20:48.260 --> 02:20:52.519
- I feel like my friends who are professors
seem happier than those who work at

02:20:52.519 --> 02:20:57.720
a frontier lab, to be honest.
There's a grounding there.

02:20:57.720 --> 02:21:00.800
The frontier labs
definitely do this 9-9-6,

02:21:00.800 --> 02:21:03.440
which is shorthand for
working all the time.

02:21:03.490 --> 02:21:07.330
- Can you describe 9-9-6? It's a
culture invented, I believe,

02:21:07.410 --> 02:21:13.890
in China and adopted in Silicon Valley.
What is 9-9-6? It's 9:00 AM to 9:00 PM,

02:21:14.150 --> 02:21:15.030
- Six days a week.

02:21:15.110 --> 02:21:20.610
- six days a week. What is that, 72 hours?
Okay. So, is this basically the standard

02:21:21.550 --> 02:21:26.850
in AI companies in Silicon Valley?
This kind of grind mindset.

02:21:26.890 --> 02:21:30.730
- Yeah, I mean, maybe not exactly like that,
but I think there is a trend towards it.

02:21:30.750 --> 02:21:34.310
And it's interesting. I think it
almost flipped because when I was in

02:21:34.320 --> 02:21:38.050
in academia, I felt like that. As
a professor, you write grants,

02:21:38.090 --> 02:21:41.869
you teach, and you do research.
It's like three jobs in one,

02:21:41.930 --> 02:21:45.850
and it's more than a full-time
job if you want to be successful.

02:21:45.890 --> 02:21:49.619
successful. And I feel like
now, like Nathan just said,

02:21:49.670 --> 02:21:53.380
the professors, in comparison
to a lab, I think they have

02:21:53.449 --> 02:21:57.279
less pressure or workload than
at a frontier lab because—

02:21:57.289 --> 02:22:00.510
- I think they work a lot. They're just
so fulfilled. By working with students—

02:22:00.529 --> 02:22:04.410
and having a constant runway of
mentorship and a mission that is

02:22:04.490 --> 02:22:08.130
very people-oriented, I think in a
era when things are moving very fast

02:22:08.609 --> 02:22:11.269
and are very chaotic, it's
very rewarding to people.

02:22:11.310 --> 02:22:14.500
- Yeah, and I think at a startup,
it's this pressure. It's like

02:22:15.390 --> 02:22:19.350
you have to make it. And it's really
important that people put in the time,

02:22:19.390 --> 02:22:23.300
but it is really hard because you
have to deliver constantly, and

02:22:23.850 --> 02:22:27.510
I've been at a startup. I had a good
time, but I don't know if I could do it

02:22:27.550 --> 02:22:31.109
forever. It's an interesting pace and it's

02:22:31.170 --> 02:22:35.010
exactly like we talked about in the
beginning. These models are leapfrogging

02:22:35.050 --> 02:22:38.930
each other, and they are just
constantly trying to take the

02:22:38.970 --> 02:22:42.109
next step compared to their competitors.
It's just ruthless right now.

02:22:42.150 --> 02:22:45.810
- I think this leapfrogging nature and
having multiple players is actually an

02:22:45.869 --> 02:22:49.670
underrated driver of language modeling
progress where competition is

02:22:49.949 --> 02:22:53.890
so deeply ingrained in people, and these

02:22:53.930 --> 02:22:57.890
companies have intentionally created
very strong cultures. Like, Anthropic is

02:22:57.949 --> 02:23:01.769
known to be so culturally, like, deeply

02:23:01.830 --> 02:23:05.750
committed and organized. I mean,
we hear so little from them, and

02:23:05.789 --> 02:23:09.670
everybody at Anthropic seems very
aligned. And it's like being in

02:23:09.710 --> 02:23:11.310
a culture that is super

02:23:12.170 --> 02:23:16.010
tight and having this competitive
dynamic is a thing that's gonna

02:23:16.050 --> 02:23:20.199
make you work hard and create
things that are better.

02:23:20.210 --> 02:23:23.730
But that comes at the cost of
human capital, which is like

02:23:24.410 --> 02:23:28.310
you can only do this for so long, and
people are definitely burning out.

02:23:28.369 --> 02:23:32.288
I wrote a post on burnout
as I've tread in and out

02:23:32.310 --> 02:23:36.230
of this myself, especially trying to
be a manager, full-mode training.

02:23:36.250 --> 02:23:39.910
It's a crazy job doing this. The
book Apple in China by Patrick

02:23:39.930 --> 02:23:43.850
McGee, he talked about how hard the Apple
engineers worked to set up the supply

02:23:43.910 --> 02:23:47.840
chains in China, and he was like, they
had "saving marriage" programs, and

02:23:47.850 --> 02:23:51.750
he told in a podcast, he
was like, "People died

02:23:51.810 --> 02:23:54.130
from this level of working
hard." So I think it's just like

02:23:55.330 --> 02:23:59.310
it's a perfect environment for
creating progress based on human

02:23:59.369 --> 02:24:03.210
expense, and there's
gonna be a lot of... the

02:24:03.250 --> 02:24:06.630
human expense is the 996 that we
started this with, which is like—

02:24:06.689 --> 02:24:08.710
... people do really grind.

02:24:08.750 --> 02:24:12.430
- I also read this book. I think they had a
code word for if someone had to go home

02:24:12.990 --> 02:24:16.430
to spend time with their family to save
the marriage, and it's crazy. Then the

02:24:16.490 --> 02:24:20.449
colleagues said, "Okay, this is like red
alert for this situation. We have to let

02:24:20.490 --> 02:24:24.439
that person go home this weekend."
But at the same time, I don't

02:24:24.490 --> 02:24:28.279
think they were forced to work. They were so
passionate about the product, I guess, that

02:24:28.330 --> 02:24:32.130
you get into that mindset. And
I had that sometimes as an

02:24:32.189 --> 02:24:36.090
academic, but also as an independent
person, I have that sometimes. I overwork,

02:24:36.170 --> 02:24:40.079
and it's unhealthy. I had back
issues, I had neck issues, because I

02:24:40.090 --> 02:24:44.060
did not take the breaks that I maybe
should have taken. But no one forced

02:24:44.109 --> 02:24:46.260
me to; it's because I wanted to
work, because it's exciting stuff.

02:24:46.269 --> 02:24:49.230
- That's what OpenAI and Anthropic are
like. They want to do this work.

02:24:49.289 --> 02:24:53.269
- Yeah, but there's also a
feeling of fervor that's

02:24:53.410 --> 02:24:57.210
building, especially in Silicon Valley,
aligned with the scaling laws idea, where

02:24:57.250 --> 02:25:00.939
there's this hype where the world
will be transformed in a scale of

02:25:00.970 --> 02:25:04.789
weeks and you want to be at the
center of it. And then, you know,

02:25:04.910 --> 02:25:08.570
I have this great fortune of having

02:25:08.630 --> 02:25:12.050
conversations with a wide
variety of human beings,

02:25:12.590 --> 02:25:16.570
and from there I get to see all these
bubbles and echo chambers across

02:25:16.609 --> 02:25:20.350
the world. It's fascinating to see how
we humans form them. And I think it's

02:25:20.410 --> 02:25:27.260
fair to say that Silicon Valley is a
kind of echo chamber, a kind of silo and

02:25:27.330 --> 02:25:31.170
bubble. I think bubbles are
actually really useful and

02:25:31.230 --> 02:25:34.970
effective. It's not necessarily a negative
thing because you could be ultra-productive.

02:25:34.990 --> 02:25:36.689
It could be the Steve Jobs

02:25:37.970 --> 02:25:41.730
reality distortion field, because
you just convince each other that

02:25:41.769 --> 02:25:45.329
breakthroughs are imminent, and
by convincing each other of

02:25:45.430 --> 02:25:48.830
that, you make the breakthroughs imminent.

02:25:48.850 --> 02:25:52.820
- Byrne Hobart wrote a book classifying
bubbles. One of them is financial bubbles,

02:25:52.970 --> 02:25:56.778
which is like speculation, which is bad,
and the other one is for build-outs,

02:25:56.850 --> 02:26:00.800
because it pushes people to build
these things. And I do think AI is in

02:26:00.869 --> 02:26:05.119
this, but I worry about it transitioning
to a financial bubble, which is

02:26:05.230 --> 02:26:08.189
- Yeah, but also in the space of ideas, that

02:26:08.210 --> 02:26:11.470
bubble—you are doing a reality distortion

02:26:11.730 --> 02:26:15.650
field, and that means you are
deviating from reality. And if

02:26:15.689 --> 02:26:22.109
you go too far from reality while
also working, you know, 996,

02:26:22.150 --> 02:26:25.949
you might miss some fundamental
aspects of the human experience,

02:26:26.010 --> 02:26:29.510
including beyond Silicon Valley. This
is a common problem in Silicon Valley:

02:26:30.050 --> 02:26:34.010
it's a very specific geographic
area. You might not understand the

02:26:34.050 --> 02:26:35.619
Midwest perspective, the full

02:26:36.730 --> 02:26:40.640
experience of all the other humans in
the United States and across the world,

02:26:40.689 --> 02:26:44.439
and you speak a certain way to each other,
you convince each other of a certain

02:26:44.510 --> 02:26:48.430
thing, and that can get you
into real trouble. Whether AI

02:26:48.439 --> 02:26:51.150
is a big success and becomes
a powerful technology

02:26:51.970 --> 02:26:55.930
or it's not, in either trajectory
you can get yourself into

02:26:55.990 --> 02:26:59.850
trouble. So you have to consider
all of that. Here you are, a young

02:26:59.869 --> 02:27:02.460
person trying to decide what
you want to do with your life.

02:27:02.490 --> 02:27:06.310
- The thing that is... I don't even
really understand this, but the

02:27:06.410 --> 02:27:10.340
SF AI memes have gotten to the point
where "permanent underclass" was

02:27:10.410 --> 02:27:13.519
one of them, which was the idea
that the last six months of

02:27:13.689 --> 02:27:17.430
2025 was the only time to
build durable value in an AI

02:27:17.510 --> 02:27:21.019
startup or model. Otherwise, all
the value will be captured by

02:27:21.070 --> 02:27:24.952
existing companies and you will
therefore be poor, which...

02:27:24.962 --> 02:27:28.822
that's an example of the SF
thing that goes so far. I still

02:27:28.882 --> 02:27:32.742
think for young people going to be
able to tap into it, if you're really

02:27:32.782 --> 02:27:36.402
passionate about wanting to have an
impact in AI, being physically in

02:27:36.482 --> 02:27:40.431
SF is the most likely place where
you're going to do this. But it has

02:27:40.442 --> 02:27:41.681
has trade-offs.

02:27:41.822 --> 02:27:45.782
- I think SF is an incredible
place, but there is a bit of

02:27:45.862 --> 02:27:49.501
a bubble. And if you go into
that bubble, which is extremely

02:27:49.601 --> 02:27:53.402
valuable, just get out also. Read history

02:27:53.521 --> 02:27:57.071
books, read literature, visit
other places in the world.

02:27:57.402 --> 02:28:00.921
Twitter and Substack are
not the entire world.

02:28:01.001 --> 02:28:04.942
- I would say, one of the people I worked
with is moving to SF, and it's like, I

02:28:05.001 --> 02:28:08.771
need to get him a copy of Season of the
Witch, which is a history of SF from

02:28:08.782 --> 02:28:16.711
1960 to 1985, which goes through
the hippie revolution, like all the

02:28:16.742 --> 02:28:20.542
gays taking over the city and that
culture emerging, and then the

02:28:20.761 --> 02:28:24.571
HIV/AIDS crisis and other things. And
it's just like, that is so recent, and

02:28:24.622 --> 02:28:28.581
so much turmoil and hurt,
but also love in SF.

02:28:28.601 --> 02:28:32.322
And it's like, no one knows about this. It's a
great book, Season of the Witch. I recommend it.

02:28:32.341 --> 02:28:34.601
A bunch of my SF friends who

02:28:35.542 --> 02:28:39.101
get out recommended it to me. And
I think that's just like living

02:28:39.181 --> 02:28:42.942
there... I lived there and I didn't
appreciate this context, and it's

02:28:43.021 --> 02:28:46.181
just so recent.

02:28:46.261 --> 02:28:53.542
- Yeah. Okay, let's... We talked a lot
about a lot of things. Certainly about

02:28:54.162 --> 02:28:58.152
the things that were exciting
last year. But this year,

02:28:58.152 --> 02:29:01.962
One of the things you guys mentioned
that's exciting is the scaling of text

02:29:02.021 --> 02:29:05.642
diffusion models, and just a different
exploration of text diffusion. Can you talk

02:29:05.742 --> 02:29:09.251
about what that is and what
the possibility it holds?

02:29:09.261 --> 02:29:13.382
So, different kinds of
approaches than the current LMs?

02:29:13.442 --> 02:29:17.181
- Yeah, so we talked a lot about the transformer
architecture and the autoregressive

02:29:17.282 --> 02:29:21.081
transformer architecture specifically,
like GPT. And it doesn't mean no one

02:29:21.122 --> 02:29:25.062
else is working on anything else.
So, people are always on the,

02:29:25.081 --> 02:29:28.802
let's say, lookout for the next big
thing. Because I think it would be almost

02:29:28.822 --> 02:29:32.671
stupid not to. Because sure,
right now, the transformer

02:29:32.702 --> 02:29:36.601
architecture is the thing, and it works
best, and there's, right now, nothing

02:29:36.742 --> 02:29:40.521
else out there. But, you know, it's always a
good idea to not put all your eggs into one

02:29:40.601 --> 02:29:44.511
basket. So, people are developing
other alternatives to the

02:29:44.822 --> 02:29:48.601
autoregressive transformer. One of
them would be, for example, text

02:29:48.662 --> 02:29:52.341
diffusion models. And listeners may
know diffusion models from image

02:29:52.421 --> 02:29:56.302
generation, like Stable Diffusion
popularized it. There was a paper on

02:29:56.362 --> 02:30:00.052
generating images. Back then, people
used GANs, Generative Adversarial

02:30:00.101 --> 02:30:03.862
Networks. And then there was this
diffusion process where you iteratively

02:30:03.902 --> 02:30:07.851
denoise an image, and that resulted
in really good quality images over

02:30:07.921 --> 02:30:11.902
time. Stable Diffusion was a company. Other
companies build their own diffusion models.

02:30:11.912 --> 02:30:15.601
And then people are now like, "Okay,
can we try this also for text?"

02:30:15.622 --> 02:30:19.412
Doesn't, you know, make intuitive sense
yet, because it feels like, okay, it's not

02:30:19.442 --> 02:30:23.322
something continuous like a pixel that we can
differentiate. It's discrete text, so how do

02:30:23.362 --> 02:30:30.862
we implement that denoising process? It's
kind of similar to the BERT models by

02:30:30.921 --> 02:30:34.841
Google. Like, when you go back to the original
transformer, they were the encoder and

02:30:34.882 --> 02:30:38.562
the decoder. The decoder is what we
are using right now in GPT and so

02:30:38.622 --> 02:30:41.921
forth. The encoder is more like a

02:30:42.021 --> 02:30:45.802
parallel technique where you
have multiple tokens that you

02:30:45.882 --> 02:30:49.862
fill in in parallel. GPT models,
they do autoregressive generation,

02:30:49.882 --> 02:30:53.712
completing the sentence one
token at a time. And in

02:30:53.722 --> 02:30:57.322
BERT models, you have a
sentence that has gaps.

02:30:57.662 --> 02:31:01.462
You mask them out, and then
one iteration is filling in

02:31:01.501 --> 02:31:04.782
these gaps. Text diffusion is
kind of like that, where you

02:31:04.862 --> 02:31:08.782
are starting with some random
text, and then you are

02:31:08.882 --> 02:31:12.562
filling in the missing parts or refining
them iteratively over multiple iterations.

02:31:12.601 --> 02:31:16.462
And the cool thing here
is that this can do

02:31:16.521 --> 02:31:18.702
multiple tokens at the
same time. It's like

02:31:19.601 --> 02:31:23.462
the promise of having it more efficient.
Now, the trade-off is, of course,

02:31:23.501 --> 02:31:27.341
how good is the quality? It
might be faster, and now

02:31:27.402 --> 02:31:31.322
you have this dimension of the denoising process.
The more steps you do, the better the text

02:31:31.362 --> 02:31:34.912
becomes. And people...

02:31:34.942 --> 02:31:38.931
I mean, you can scale in different
ways. They try to see if that is

02:31:38.982 --> 02:31:42.851
maybe a valid alternative to
the autoregressive model in

02:31:42.882 --> 02:31:46.761
terms of giving you the same
quality for less compute.

02:31:46.902 --> 02:31:50.622
Right now, there are papers that
suggest if you want to get the same

02:31:50.681 --> 02:31:54.562
quality, you have to crank up
the denoising steps, and then

02:31:54.601 --> 02:31:57.982
you end up spending the same compute you
would spend on an autoregressive model.

02:31:58.042 --> 02:32:01.921
The other downside is, while
being parallel sounds appealing,

02:32:01.942 --> 02:32:05.902
some tasks are not parallel. Like
reasoning tasks or tool use,

02:32:06.001 --> 02:32:09.921
maybe where you have to ask a
code interpreter to give you

02:32:09.962 --> 02:32:13.562
an intermediate result. That is tricky
with diffusion models. So, there are some

02:32:13.601 --> 02:32:17.101
hybrids, but the main idea is: how
can we parallelize it? It's an

02:32:17.402 --> 02:32:20.722
interesting avenue. I think
right now, there are mostly

02:32:20.822 --> 02:32:24.761
research models out there, like
LaMDA and some other ones.

02:32:24.822 --> 02:32:28.542
I saw some by startups, some
deployed models. There is no

02:32:28.782 --> 02:32:32.601
big diffusion model at scale yet,
like on the Gemini or ChatGPT level.

02:32:32.681 --> 02:32:36.642
But there was an announcement by Google,

02:32:36.662 --> 02:32:40.271
a site where they said they are
launching Gemini Diffusion, and they

02:32:40.581 --> 02:32:44.042
put it into context of their Gemini Nano 2

02:32:44.081 --> 02:32:47.742
model, and they said basically:
for the same quality on most

02:32:47.782 --> 02:32:51.162
benchmarks, we can generate
things much faster. You

02:32:51.222 --> 02:32:54.862
mentioned what's next. I don't think the
text diffusion model is going to replace

02:32:54.902 --> 02:32:58.521
autoregressive LLMs, but it
will be something maybe for

02:32:58.622 --> 02:33:02.202
quick, cheap, at-scale
tasks. Maybe the free

02:33:02.302 --> 02:33:07.921
tier in the future will
be something like that.

02:33:08.001 --> 02:33:11.921
- I think there are examples where it's already
being used. To paint an example of why this is

02:33:11.962 --> 02:33:15.501
better, for example, when
GPT-5 is taking 30 minutes to

02:33:15.562 --> 02:33:19.171
respond, it's generating one token at
a time. And this diffusion idea is

02:33:19.202 --> 02:33:23.181
essentially to generate all of
those tokens and the completion in

02:33:23.261 --> 02:33:26.482
one batch, which is why it could be
way faster. And I think it could be

02:33:26.542 --> 02:33:30.422
suited for... the startups I'm hearing
about are code startups where you have a

02:33:30.462 --> 02:33:34.221
code base, and you have somebody that's
effectively "vibe coding," and they say,

02:33:34.262 --> 02:33:37.742
"Make this change." And a
code diff is essentially a

02:33:37.882 --> 02:33:41.802
huge reply from the model, but
it doesn't have to have that

02:33:41.822 --> 02:33:45.312
much external context, and you can get it
really fast by using these diffusion models.

02:33:45.342 --> 02:33:49.182
One example I've heard is that they
use text diffusion to generate

02:33:49.242 --> 02:33:53.202
really long diffs, because doing it
with an autoregressive model would take

02:33:53.262 --> 02:33:57.202
minutes, and that time for a user-facing
product causes a lot of churn.

02:33:57.242 --> 02:34:01.112
Every second, you lose a lot of users.
So, I think it's going to be this

02:34:01.142 --> 02:34:02.222
thing where it's going to—

02:34:02.482 --> 02:34:06.382
...grow and have some applications, but I
actually thought that different types of models

02:34:06.402 --> 02:34:10.292
were going to be used for different
things much sooner than they have been,

02:34:10.342 --> 02:34:14.082
so I kind of trade off. I think the
tool-use point is the one that's stopping

02:34:14.122 --> 02:34:21.962
them from being most general purpose
because, for Claude Code and ChatGPT search,

02:34:22.002 --> 02:34:25.562
the autoregressive chain is interrupted
with some external tool, and

02:34:25.942 --> 02:34:28.402
I don't know how to do that
with the diffusion setup.

02:34:28.882 --> 02:34:32.781
- So what's the future of tool use this
year and then in the coming years? Do you

02:34:32.802 --> 02:34:36.662
think there's going to be a lot of developments
there, and how that's integrated into the entire

02:34:36.682 --> 02:34:37.282
stack?

02:34:37.382 --> 02:34:41.282
- I do think right now, it's mostly
on the proprietary LLM side,

02:34:41.302 --> 02:34:45.102
but I think we will see more of that
in the open-source tooling. And I

02:34:45.122 --> 02:34:48.762
think it is a huge unlock
because then you can really

02:34:48.802 --> 02:34:52.912
outsource certain tasks from
just memorization to actual—

02:34:53.762 --> 02:34:57.722
you know, instead of having the
LLM memorize what is 23 plus 5,

02:34:57.782 --> 02:34:58.942
just use a calculator.

02:34:58.962 --> 02:35:01.842
- So do you think that can
help solve hallucination?

02:35:01.962 --> 02:35:05.802
- Not solve it, but reduce it.
So the LLM still needs to know

02:35:06.142 --> 02:35:09.882
when to ask for a tool call. And the

02:35:09.942 --> 02:35:13.922
second one is, well, it doesn't mean the
internet is always correct. You can do

02:35:13.982 --> 02:35:17.602
a web search, but let's say I
asked who won the World Cup

02:35:17.642 --> 02:35:21.072
in, let's say, 1998; it still needs to
find the right website and get the right

02:35:21.082 --> 02:35:24.792
information. You can still go to the
incorrect website and give me incorrect

02:35:24.822 --> 02:35:28.702
information. So I don't think it
will fully solve that, but it is

02:35:28.762 --> 02:35:30.602
improving it in that sense.

02:35:31.482 --> 02:35:35.342
And so another cool paper
earlier this year—I think it was

02:35:35.352 --> 02:35:38.752
December 31st, so it's
not technically 2026,

02:35:38.752 --> 02:35:43.222
but close—the recursive language model.

02:35:43.342 --> 02:35:47.242
That's a cool idea to kind of
take this even a bit further.

02:35:47.322 --> 02:35:50.462
Just to explain, Nathan,
you also mentioned earlier,

02:35:51.402 --> 02:35:55.062
it's harder to do cool research in academia
because of the compute budget. If I

02:35:55.082 --> 02:35:59.062
recall correctly, they did everything with
GPT-5, so they didn't even use local models,

02:35:59.122 --> 02:36:02.982
but the idea is, let's say you have a
long-context task; instead of having the

02:36:03.062 --> 02:36:06.862
LLM solve all of it in one
shot or even in a chain,

02:36:06.942 --> 02:36:10.542
you break it down into sub-tasks.
You have the LLM decide

02:36:10.682 --> 02:36:13.762
what is a good sub-task, and then

02:36:14.302 --> 02:36:18.242
recursively call an LLM to solve
that. And I think something like

02:36:18.302 --> 02:36:22.222
that, adding tools—you know,
each one maybe you have

02:36:22.242 --> 02:36:25.942
a huge Q&amp;A task, so each one
goes to the web and gathers

02:36:25.982 --> 02:36:29.311
information, and then you pull it together
at the end and stitch it back together.

02:36:29.362 --> 02:36:34.452
I think there's going to be a lot of
unlock using things like that where

02:36:35.362 --> 02:36:39.302
you don't necessarily improve the LLM
itself; you improve how the LLM is

02:36:39.442 --> 02:36:43.262
used and what the LLM can use. One
downside right now with tool use

02:36:43.362 --> 02:36:46.862
is you have to give the LLM
permission to use tools. And

02:36:47.802 --> 02:36:50.982
that will take some trust, especially
if you want to unlock things

02:36:51.022 --> 02:36:54.822
like having an LLM answer emails for
you—or not even answer, but just

02:36:54.862 --> 02:36:58.722
sort them for you or select them for you or
something like that. I don't know if I would

02:36:58.782 --> 02:37:03.342
today give an LLM access to my emails,
right? I mean, this is a huge risk.

02:37:03.422 --> 02:37:07.162
- I think there's a cool... one last point
on the tool use thing. I think that

02:37:07.942 --> 02:37:11.922
you hinted at this, and we've both come at
this in our own ways, is that the open versus

02:37:12.022 --> 02:37:15.982
closed models use tools in very different
ways, where open models, people go to

02:37:16.002 --> 02:37:19.832
Hugging Face and download the model, and then the
person's going to be like, "What tool do I want?"

02:37:20.382 --> 02:37:24.262
I don't know, Exa is my preferred search
provider, but somebody else might care

02:37:24.282 --> 02:37:28.202
for a different search startup. Where you release
a model, it needs to be useful for multiple

02:37:28.282 --> 02:37:31.882
tools, for multiple use cases, which
is really hard because you're making a

02:37:31.942 --> 02:37:35.862
general reasoning engine model, which
is actually what gpt-oss-120b is

02:37:35.902 --> 02:37:39.662
good for. But on the closed
models, you're deeply integrating

02:37:40.022 --> 02:37:43.952
the specific tool into your experience,
and I think that open models will

02:37:44.002 --> 02:37:47.602
struggle to replicate some of the
things that I like to do with closed

02:37:47.662 --> 02:37:51.462
models, which will be like, you can
reference a mix of public and private

02:37:51.522 --> 02:37:55.512
information. And something that I keep
trying every three to six months,

02:37:55.622 --> 02:37:59.422
I try Claude Code on the web,
which is just prompting a model to

02:37:59.482 --> 02:38:03.222
make an update to some GitHub repository
that I have. And it's just like

02:38:03.282 --> 02:38:07.002
that set of secure cloud
environments is just so nice for

02:38:07.102 --> 02:38:10.342
just sending it off to do this
thing and then come back to

02:38:10.402 --> 02:38:16.862
me, and these will probably help define
some of the local open and closed

02:38:18.042 --> 02:38:21.962
niches. But I think initially, because
there was such a rush to get tool use

02:38:22.042 --> 02:38:25.982
working, the open models were on the back foot,
which is kind of inevitable. I think there's so

02:38:26.022 --> 02:38:29.982
much research, so many resources in
these frontier labs, but it will be

02:38:30.022 --> 02:38:33.822
fun when the open models solve this
because it's going to necessitate a bit

02:38:33.862 --> 02:38:37.482
more flexible and potentially interesting
model that might work with this recursive

02:38:37.562 --> 02:38:41.082
idea to be an orchestrator
and a tool use model,

02:38:41.122 --> 02:38:44.552
so hopefully the necessity drives
some interesting innovation there.

02:38:45.102 --> 02:38:48.762
- So, continual learning—this
is a longstanding

02:38:50.042 --> 02:38:53.962
topic, important problem. I think
that increases in importance as

02:38:53.982 --> 02:38:57.762
the cost of training the models
goes up. So can you explain what

02:38:57.822 --> 02:39:01.582
continual learning is and how important
it might be this year and in the coming

02:39:01.642 --> 02:39:02.642
years to make progress?

02:39:03.122 --> 02:39:06.562
- This relates a lot to this kind
of SF zeitgeist of, what is

02:39:06.642 --> 02:39:10.032
AGI, which is Artificial General
Intelligence, and what is

02:39:10.142 --> 02:39:13.902
ASI, Artificial Superintelligence, and
what are the language models that we

02:39:13.962 --> 02:39:17.842
have today capable of doing? I think
the language models can solve a lot

02:39:17.882 --> 02:39:21.842
of tasks, but a key milestone
among the AI community is

02:39:21.902 --> 02:39:25.682
essentially when AI could
replace any remote worker,

02:39:25.722 --> 02:39:29.482
taking in information and solving
digital tasks and doing them. And

02:39:29.502 --> 02:39:32.512
the limitation that's
highlighted by people is

02:39:32.602 --> 02:39:36.306
that a language model will not learn
from feedback the same way that an

02:39:36.326 --> 02:39:40.266
employee does. So if you hire an
editor, the editor will mess up, but

02:39:40.306 --> 02:39:44.146
you will tell them. And if you hired a good editor,
they don't do it again. But language models don't

02:39:44.206 --> 02:39:44.586
have this

02:39:45.666 --> 02:39:49.566
ability to modify themselves and learn very
quickly. So the idea is, if we are going to

02:39:49.646 --> 02:39:53.126
actually get to something that
is a true, general adaptable

02:39:53.166 --> 02:39:56.766
intelligence that can go into any remote
work scenario, it needs to be able to learn

02:39:56.826 --> 02:39:59.056
quickly from feedback
and on-the-job learning.

02:40:00.186 --> 02:40:04.046
I'm personally more bullish on language
models being able to just provide

02:40:04.066 --> 02:40:08.006
them with very good context.
You said, maybe offline, that

02:40:08.026 --> 02:40:11.886
you can write extensive documents
to models where you say,

02:40:11.906 --> 02:40:15.826
"I have all this information. Here are
all the blog posts I've ever written.

02:40:15.886 --> 02:40:19.726
I like this type of writing. My voice is
based on this." But many people don't provide

02:40:19.746 --> 02:40:23.666
this to models, and the models
weren't designed to take this amount

02:40:23.706 --> 02:40:27.555
of context previously. Agentic
models are just starting. So it's

02:40:27.586 --> 02:40:31.286
this kind of trade-off: do we need
to update the weights of this model

02:40:31.466 --> 02:40:34.806
with this continual learning thing
to make them learn fast? Or the

02:40:34.826 --> 02:40:38.746
counterargument is we just need to provide
them with more context and information,

02:40:38.786 --> 02:40:42.606
and they will have the appearance of learning
fast by having a lot of context and being

02:40:42.646 --> 02:40:43.306
smart.

02:40:43.346 --> 02:40:46.606
- So we should mention the terminology
here. Continual learning refers to

02:40:46.646 --> 02:40:52.846
changing the weights continuously so
that the model adapts and adjusts

02:40:53.006 --> 02:40:56.506
based on the new incoming

02:40:56.526 --> 02:41:00.346
information, doing so continually,
rapidly, and frequently.

02:41:00.466 --> 02:41:03.786
And then the thing you mentioned
on the other side of it

02:41:04.486 --> 02:41:08.386
generally will be referred to
as in-context learning. As

02:41:08.426 --> 02:41:12.226
you learn stuff, there's a
huge context window. You can

02:41:12.286 --> 02:41:15.776
just keep loading it with extra information
every time you prompt the system,

02:41:15.826 --> 02:41:21.706
which I think both legitimately
can be seen as learning.

02:41:21.746 --> 02:41:24.226
It's just a different place
where you're doing the learning.

02:41:24.326 --> 02:41:28.136
- I think, to be honest with you,
continual learning — updating

02:41:28.186 --> 02:41:31.916
weights — we already have that in
different flavors. If you think about

02:41:31.966 --> 02:41:35.806
how... I think the
distinction here is: do you

02:41:35.866 --> 02:41:39.676
do that on a personalized custom
model for each person, or

02:41:39.766 --> 02:41:43.765
do you do it on a global model
scale? I think we have that already,

02:41:43.866 --> 02:41:47.786
going from GPT-5 to 5.1 and 5.2. It's

02:41:47.826 --> 02:41:51.426
maybe not immediate, but it is a
curated update, a quick curated update

02:41:51.466 --> 02:41:55.146
where there was feedback about things
they couldn't do, feedback by the

02:41:55.186 --> 02:41:58.606
community. They updated the weights,
next model, and so forth. So it

02:41:58.686 --> 02:42:06.256
is a flavor of that. Another even
finer-grained example is like

02:42:06.346 --> 02:42:10.106
RLVR; you run it, it
updates. The problem is

02:42:10.166 --> 02:42:13.986
you can't just do that for each person because
it would be too expensive to update the

02:42:14.026 --> 02:42:17.876
weights for each person, and I think
that's the problem. Unless you get...

02:42:17.906 --> 02:42:21.826
Even at OpenAI scale, building
the data centers, it would be too

02:42:21.866 --> 02:42:25.786
expensive. I think that is only
feasible once you have something

02:42:25.826 --> 02:42:29.726
on the device where the cost is on the
consumer. Like what Apple tried to do with the

02:42:29.766 --> 02:42:33.466
Apple Foundation models, putting them
on the phone, where they learn from

02:42:33.486 --> 02:42:33.886
experience.

02:42:33.966 --> 02:42:41.806
- A bit of a related topic, but this kind
of, maybe anthropomorphized term: memory.

02:42:42.106 --> 02:42:46.046
What are different ideas for the mechanism of
how to add memory to these systems as we're

02:42:46.066 --> 02:42:49.606
increasingly seeing?
Personalized memory especially?

02:42:49.666 --> 02:42:52.696
- Right now, it's mostly basically

02:42:52.746 --> 02:42:56.736
stuffing things into the context
and then just recalling that.

02:42:56.746 --> 02:43:04.586
But again, I think it's expensive because
you have to—you can cache it, but still

02:43:04.786 --> 02:43:08.546
you spend tokens on that. And the
second one is you can only do

02:43:08.726 --> 02:43:12.706
so much. I think it's more like a preference
or style. I mean, a lot of people do

02:43:12.746 --> 02:43:16.196
that when they solve math
problems. You say it's way so you

02:43:16.226 --> 02:43:20.046
can add previous knowledge and stuff,
but you also give it certain preference

02:43:20.066 --> 02:43:23.976
prompts: "do what I preferred last
time," or something like that. But

02:43:23.986 --> 02:43:31.156
it doesn't unlock new capabilities. So
for that, one thing people still use is

02:43:31.186 --> 02:43:34.895
LoRA adapters. These are basically,
instead of updating the whole weight

02:43:34.946 --> 02:43:38.926
matrix, there are two smaller weight
matrices that you kind of have

02:43:38.966 --> 02:43:42.646
in parallel or overlays like
the delta. But yeah, you can

02:43:43.026 --> 02:43:45.086
do that to some extent, but then again,

02:43:45.946 --> 02:43:49.456
it is economics. There
were also papers, for

02:43:49.506 --> 02:43:53.406
example, LoRA learns
less but forgets less.

02:43:53.426 --> 02:43:57.286
It's like, there's no free lunch. If you
want to learn more, you need to use more

02:43:57.306 --> 02:44:01.126
weights, but it gets more expensive. And
then again, if you learn more, you forget

02:44:01.186 --> 02:44:04.916
more, and you have to find that
Goldilocks zone basically.

02:44:04.926 --> 02:44:08.736
- We haven't really mentioned it much,
but implied in this discussion is

02:44:08.746 --> 02:44:13.186
context length also. Is there a lot
of innovation that's possible there?

02:44:13.326 --> 02:44:17.286
- I think the colloquially accepted
thing is that it's a compute and data

02:44:17.346 --> 02:44:21.206
problem where you can...
and sometimes small

02:44:21.306 --> 02:44:24.796
architecture things like attention
variants. We talked about

02:44:24.826 --> 02:44:28.755
hybrid attention models, which
is essentially if you have what

02:44:28.786 --> 02:44:32.476
looks like a state space model within
your transformer. And those are

02:44:32.526 --> 02:44:36.106
better suited because you have to
spend less compute to model the

02:44:37.206 --> 02:44:40.636
furthest along token. I think that,

02:44:41.066 --> 02:44:45.976
those aren't free because they have to
be accompanied by a lot of compute or

02:44:47.046 --> 02:44:51.026
the right data. How many sequences
of 100,000 tokens do you have in

02:44:51.066 --> 02:44:54.846
the world, and where do you get
these? It just ends up being pretty

02:44:54.866 --> 02:44:58.836
expensive to scale them. We've gotten
pretty quickly to a million tokens

02:44:58.906 --> 02:45:02.846
of input context length. I would
expect it to keep increasing and

02:45:02.866 --> 02:45:06.846
get to 2 million or 5 million this year,
but I don't expect it to go to 100

02:45:06.886 --> 02:45:10.606
million. That would be like a true
breakthrough, and I think those

02:45:10.646 --> 02:45:14.546
breakthroughs are possible. I think of the continual
learning thing as a research problem where

02:45:14.606 --> 02:45:18.466
there could be a breakthrough that
just makes transformers work way

02:45:18.566 --> 02:45:22.206
better at this and it's cheap. These things
could happen with so much scientific

02:45:22.266 --> 02:45:27.926
attention. But turning the crank, it'll
be consistent increases over time.

02:45:27.986 --> 02:45:31.746
- Looking at the extremes, I think there's,
again, no free lunch. So, the one

02:45:31.786 --> 02:45:35.686
extreme to make it cheap: you have, let's
say, an RNN that has a single state

02:45:35.746 --> 02:45:38.826
where you save everything from
the previous stuff. It's like a

02:45:39.526 --> 02:45:43.430
specific fixed-size thing,
so you never really grow the

02:45:43.450 --> 02:45:46.940
memory because you are stuffing
everything into one state, but

02:45:46.970 --> 02:45:50.900
then the longer the context gets, the
more information you forget because

02:45:50.950 --> 02:45:54.830
you can't compress everything
into one state. Then on the

02:45:54.870 --> 02:45:58.530
other hand, you have the transformers, which
try to remember every token, which is great

02:45:58.610 --> 02:46:02.530
sometimes if you want to look up specific
information, but very expensive because you have the

02:46:02.550 --> 02:46:06.230
KV cache that grows, the
dot product that grows. But

02:46:06.270 --> 02:46:10.250
then, like you said, the Mamba layers—I
mean, they kind of have the same problem.

02:46:10.290 --> 02:46:14.010
Like an RNN, you try to compress everything
into one state; you're a bit more selective

02:46:14.050 --> 02:46:17.950
there. But then I think it's like
this Goldilocks zone again. With

02:46:18.010 --> 02:46:21.830
Nemotron 3, they found a good
ratio of how many attention

02:46:21.850 --> 02:46:25.250
layers do you need for the global
information where everything is accessible

02:46:25.690 --> 02:46:28.940
compared to having these compressed
states. And I think that's

02:46:28.970 --> 02:46:32.950
how we will scale more—by finding better,

02:46:32.990 --> 02:46:36.160
let's say, ratios in the
Goldilocks zone, like between

02:46:37.230 --> 02:46:41.190
making computing cheap enough
to run, but then also making

02:46:41.230 --> 02:46:45.110
it powerful enough to be
useful. And one more plug here,

02:46:45.170 --> 02:46:48.890
the Recursive Language Model
paper, that is one of the

02:46:48.930 --> 02:46:52.810
papers that tries to kind of address the
long context thing. So what they found

02:46:52.870 --> 02:46:56.600
is essentially instead of stuffing
everything into this long context

02:46:57.030 --> 02:47:00.590
if you break it up into
multiple smaller tasks, so you

02:47:00.810 --> 02:47:04.390
save memory by having multiple
smaller cores, you can actually get

02:47:04.830 --> 02:47:08.790
better accuracy than having the
LLM try everything all at once.

02:47:08.830 --> 02:47:12.790
I mean, it's a new paradigm. We will see,
you know, there might be other flavors of

02:47:12.830 --> 02:47:16.510
that. So I think with that, we
will still make improvement on

02:47:16.530 --> 02:47:20.270
long context, but then also, like
Nathan said, I think the problem is for

02:47:20.310 --> 02:47:24.270
pre-training itself, we don't have as
many long context documents as other

02:47:24.350 --> 02:47:28.090
documents. So it's harder
to study basically

02:47:28.130 --> 02:47:31.720
how LLMs behave and stuff
like that on that level.

02:47:31.750 --> 02:47:35.090
- There are some rules of thumb where essentially
you pre-train a language model, like OLMo.

02:47:35.130 --> 02:47:38.810
we pre-trained at like 8K context
length and then extended to

02:47:38.990 --> 02:47:42.930
32K with training. And there are some rules
of thumb where you're essentially doubling

02:47:42.970 --> 02:47:46.530
the training context length, it takes
like 2X compute, and then you can

02:47:46.590 --> 02:47:50.280
normally like 2 to 4X the
context length again.

02:47:50.610 --> 02:47:54.430
So I think a lot of it ends up being
kind of compute bound at pre-training,

02:47:54.470 --> 02:47:58.070
which is in this... Like we talked about,
everyone talks about this big increase in

02:47:58.130 --> 02:48:01.850
compute for the top labs this year, and
that should reflect in some longer context

02:48:01.890 --> 02:48:05.620
windows. But I think on the post-training side,
there are some more interesting things. As we have

02:48:05.650 --> 02:48:09.479
agents, the agents are gonna manage
this context on their own, where now

02:48:09.630 --> 02:48:13.570
agents, people that use Claude Code a lot dread
the compaction, which is when Claude takes its

02:48:13.590 --> 02:48:17.490
entire full 100,000 tokens of work
and compacts it into a bulleted

02:48:17.530 --> 02:48:21.410
list. But what the next
models will do—and I'm sure

02:48:21.730 --> 02:48:25.410
people are already working on this—is
essentially the model can control when it

02:48:25.450 --> 02:48:29.050
compacts and how. So you can essentially
train your RL algorithm where

02:48:29.090 --> 02:48:30.979
compaction is an action-

02:48:30.990 --> 02:48:34.910
...where it shortens the history and
then the problem formulation will be, "I

02:48:34.950 --> 02:48:38.930
want to keep the maximum evaluation
scores that I have gotten

02:48:39.390 --> 02:48:43.290
while the model compacts its history to
the minimum length." Because then you

02:48:43.350 --> 02:48:47.230
have the minimum amount of tokens that
you need to do this kind of compounding

02:48:47.250 --> 02:48:51.050
autoregressive prediction. So there are actually
pretty nice problem setups in this, where

02:48:51.070 --> 02:48:54.930
the... Like these agentic models
learn to use their context in a

02:48:54.950 --> 02:48:56.910
different way than just plow forward.

02:48:56.930 --> 02:49:00.350
- One interesting recent example
would be DeepSeek-V3.2,

02:49:00.590 --> 02:49:04.330
where they had a sparse attention
mechanism where they have

02:49:04.390 --> 02:49:08.370
essentially a very efficient,
small, lightweight indexer. And

02:49:08.410 --> 02:49:12.380
instead of attending to all tokens, it
selects: "What tokens do I actually need?"

02:49:12.390 --> 02:49:16.230
I mean, it almost comes back
to the original idea of

02:49:16.290 --> 02:49:20.090
attention where you are selective, but
attention is always on, you have maybe zero

02:49:20.170 --> 02:49:24.090
weight on some of them, but you use them all. But
they are even more like, "Let's just mask that out

02:49:24.130 --> 02:49:27.950
or not even do that."

02:49:28.010 --> 02:49:31.970
And even with sliding window attention
in OLMo, that is also kind of that idea.

02:49:32.010 --> 02:49:35.830
You have a rolling window where you keep it
fixed, because you don't need everything.

02:49:35.910 --> 02:49:39.430
Occasionally, some layers you might, but
it's wasteful. But right now, I think,

02:49:39.490 --> 02:49:43.390
if you use everything, you're on the safe
side—it gives you the best bang for the buck

02:49:43.430 --> 02:49:47.150
because you never miss information.
And I think this year will be more

02:49:47.270 --> 02:49:51.259
about figuring out, like you
said, how to be smarter about

02:49:51.290 --> 02:49:55.090
that. Right now, people want to have
the next state-of-the-art, and the

02:49:55.110 --> 02:49:58.890
state-of-the-art happens to
be the brute-force, expensive

02:49:58.930 --> 02:50:02.750
thing. And then once you have
that, as you said, keep that

02:50:02.820 --> 02:50:07.090
accuracy, but let's see how we can
do that cheaper now, with tricks.

02:50:07.150 --> 02:50:08.590
- Yeah. All this scaling thing.

02:50:08.600 --> 02:50:12.570
The reason we get the Claude
4.5 Sonnet model first is

02:50:12.610 --> 02:50:16.000
because you can train it faster and you're
not hitting these compute walls as soon.

02:50:16.010 --> 02:50:19.840
They can just try a lot more things and get
the model faster, even though the bigger

02:50:19.870 --> 02:50:22.020
model is actually better.

02:50:22.090 --> 02:50:25.690
- I think we should say that there's a lot of
exciting stuff going on in the AI space.

02:50:25.790 --> 02:50:29.070
My mind has recently
been really focused on

02:50:29.110 --> 02:50:32.920
robotics. Today, we almost
entirely didn't talk

02:50:32.970 --> 02:50:36.730
about robotics. There's a lot
of stuff on image generation,

02:50:36.770 --> 02:50:40.610
video generation. I think it's fair

02:50:40.650 --> 02:50:44.390
to say that the most exciting
research work in terms of the

02:50:44.430 --> 02:50:48.290
amount, intensity, and fervor is in the

02:50:48.410 --> 02:50:51.810
LLM space, which is why I think it's
justified for us to focus on the

02:50:51.970 --> 02:50:55.580
LLMs that we're discussing.
But it'd be nice to bring in

02:50:55.610 --> 02:50:59.410
certain things that might be
useful. For example, world models—

02:50:59.450 --> 02:51:03.120
there's growing excitement on that.
Do you think there will be any

02:51:03.370 --> 02:51:06.790
use in this coming year for
world models in the LLM space?

02:51:06.870 --> 02:51:10.730
Yes, I do think so. Also with LLMs,

02:51:10.750 --> 02:51:14.330
what's interesting here is
that if we unlock more LLM

02:51:14.350 --> 02:51:18.230
capabilities, it also automatically
unlocks all the other fields because

02:51:18.250 --> 02:51:24.610
it makes progress faster. A lot of
researchers and engineers use LLMs for

02:51:24.690 --> 02:51:28.570
coding. So even if they work on
robotics, if you optimize these LLMs

02:51:28.610 --> 02:51:32.280
that help with coding,
it pays off. But then,

02:51:32.630 --> 02:51:35.890
yes, world models are interesting.
It's basically where you

02:51:35.970 --> 02:51:39.780
have the model run a simulation
of the world in a sense, like a

02:51:39.970 --> 02:51:43.680
little toy thing of the real
thing, which can, again,

02:51:43.710 --> 02:51:47.606
unlock capabilities
regarding data the LLM is

02:51:47.626 --> 02:51:54.046
not aware of. It can simulate things.
And I think LLMs happen to work

02:51:55.386 --> 02:51:58.886
well by pre-training and
doing next-token prediction.

02:51:59.686 --> 02:52:03.186
But we could do this even
more sophisticatedly in a

02:52:03.226 --> 02:52:07.126
sense. I think there was a paper by

02:52:07.146 --> 02:52:10.656
Meta, a paper called World
Models. So where they

02:52:10.746 --> 02:52:14.306
basically apply the concept of
world models to LLMs again,

02:52:14.346 --> 02:52:17.666
where instead of just having
next-token prediction and

02:52:18.086 --> 02:52:21.746
verifiable rewards, checking the answer
correctness, they also make sure the

02:52:21.806 --> 02:52:25.116
intermediate variables are correct.
You know, it's kind of like

02:52:25.126 --> 02:52:28.946
the model is learning basically a
code environment in a sense. And I

02:52:28.986 --> 02:52:32.146
think this makes a lot of sense.
It's just expensive to do,

02:52:32.186 --> 02:52:38.946
but it is making things more
sophisticated, like modeling

02:52:40.226 --> 02:52:43.946
the whole thing, not just
the result. And so it can

02:52:44.006 --> 02:52:51.846
add more value. I remember when I
was a grad student, there is a...

02:52:51.906 --> 02:52:55.786
competition called CASP, I
think, where they do protein

02:52:55.866 --> 02:52:59.746
structure prediction. They predict
the structure of a protein

02:52:59.766 --> 02:53:03.746
that is not solved yet
at that point. So in a

02:53:03.766 --> 02:53:07.466
sense, this is actually great, and I think
we need something like that for LLMs also,

02:53:07.486 --> 02:53:11.426
where you do the benchmark, but no one
does. You hand in the results, but no one

02:53:11.466 --> 02:53:14.646
knows the solution. And then after
the fact, someone reveals that. But,

02:53:15.606 --> 02:53:19.586
AlphaFold, when it came
out, it crushed this

02:53:19.666 --> 02:53:23.436
benchmark. I mean, there
were also multiple

02:53:23.466 --> 02:53:27.436
iterations, but I remember the
first one. I'm not an expert in

02:53:27.486 --> 02:53:30.936
that subject, but the first one
explicitly modeled the physical

02:53:31.026 --> 02:53:34.786
interactions of the... You know,
the physics of the molecule.

02:53:34.846 --> 02:53:38.726
Also the angles, impossible angles. And then
in the next version, I think they got rid of

02:53:38.766 --> 02:53:42.686
this, and just with brute force, scaling
it up. And I think with LLMs, we are

02:53:42.746 --> 02:53:46.726
currently in this brute force scaling because
it just happens to work. But I do think at some

02:53:46.766 --> 02:53:49.546
point it might make
sense to bring back this

02:53:49.906 --> 02:53:53.506
thing. And I think with world
models, I think that is

02:53:53.546 --> 02:53:57.475
where I think that might be
actually quite cool. I mean, yeah.

02:53:57.506 --> 02:54:03.306
And of course, also for robotics,
which is completely unrelated to LLMs.

02:54:03.366 --> 02:54:07.286
- Yeah. And robotics is very explicit.
So there's the problem of locomotion

02:54:07.306 --> 02:54:08.066
or manipulation.

02:54:08.076 --> 02:54:11.966
Locomotion is much more solved, especially
in the learning domain. But there's a

02:54:12.006 --> 02:54:14.856
lot of value, just like with the
initial protein folding systems,

02:54:14.906 --> 02:54:20.516
bringing in the traditional model-based
methods. So you don't... it's unlikely

02:54:21.606 --> 02:54:25.406
that you can just learn the
manipulation or the whole body, local

02:54:25.426 --> 02:54:27.986
manipulation problem end to end.

02:54:28.086 --> 02:54:33.166
That's the dream. But then you realize when
you look at the magic of the human hand

02:54:33.226 --> 02:54:37.146
and the complexity of the real world,
it's really hard to learn this all the

02:54:37.166 --> 02:54:40.786
way through, the way I
guess AlphaFold 2 didn't.

02:54:40.846 --> 02:54:44.386
- I'm excited about the robotic learning
space. I think it's collectively

02:54:44.446 --> 02:54:48.286
getting supercharged by all the
excitement and investment in

02:54:48.326 --> 02:54:51.626
language models generally, where
the infrastructure for training

02:54:51.726 --> 02:54:55.706
transformers, which is a general
modeling thing, is becoming

02:54:55.766 --> 02:54:59.586
world-class industrial tooling,

02:54:59.626 --> 02:55:03.186
where wherever there was a limitation
for robotics, it's just way better.

02:55:03.226 --> 02:55:07.116
There's way more compute. And then on top
of that, they take these language models

02:55:07.186 --> 02:55:11.176
as kind of central units where you can
do interesting explorative work around

02:55:11.226 --> 02:55:14.746
something that already
works. And then I see it

02:55:14.786 --> 02:55:18.556
emerging as, kind of like we talked
about, Hugging Face transformers and

02:55:18.606 --> 02:55:22.216
Hugging Face. I think when I was at Hugging Face, I was
trying to get this to happen, but it was too early.

02:55:22.216 --> 02:55:25.906
It's like these open
robotic models on Hugging

02:55:25.926 --> 02:55:29.766
Face, and having people be able to
contribute data and fine-tune them.

02:55:29.806 --> 02:55:33.726
I think we're much closer now that the
investment in robotics and self-driving

02:55:33.766 --> 02:55:37.736
cars is related and it enables this,
where once you get to the point

02:55:37.746 --> 02:55:41.626
where you can have this sort of ecosystem where
somebody can download a robotics model and

02:55:41.666 --> 02:55:45.556
maybe fine-tune it to their robot
or share datasets across the world.

02:55:45.586 --> 02:55:49.516
There's some work in this
area like RTX, I think it was

02:55:49.606 --> 02:55:53.586
a few years ago, where people are starting to
do that. But once they have this ecosystem,

02:55:53.626 --> 02:55:55.766
it'll look very different.
And then this whole

02:55:56.566 --> 02:56:00.466
post-ChatGPT boom is putting more
resources into that, which I think

02:56:00.486 --> 02:56:02.206
is a very good area for doing research.

02:56:02.426 --> 02:56:06.026
- This is also resulting in much
better, more accurate, and more

02:56:06.086 --> 02:56:10.066
realistic simulators being built, closing
the sim-to-real gap in the robotic

02:56:10.126 --> 02:56:14.056
space. But, you know, you mentioned
a lot of excitement in the

02:56:14.146 --> 02:56:17.386
robotics space and a lot of
investment. The downside of

02:56:17.466 --> 02:56:21.286
that, which happens in
hype cycles, I personally

02:56:21.326 --> 02:56:24.736
believe, and most robotics
people believe, that it's not...

02:56:24.736 --> 02:56:28.536
Robotics is not going to be solved at the

02:56:28.646 --> 02:56:32.326
time scale as being
implicitly or explicitly

02:56:32.366 --> 02:56:36.346
promised. And so what happens when
there's all these robotics companies

02:56:36.386 --> 02:56:42.066
that spring up and then they don't have
a product that works? Then there's

02:56:42.106 --> 02:56:45.536
going to be this kind of
crash of excitement, which is

02:56:45.586 --> 02:56:49.486
nerve-wracking. Hopefully something
else will come in and keep swooping

02:56:49.566 --> 02:56:53.776
in so that the continued development
of some of these ideas keeps going.

02:56:53.786 --> 02:56:57.646
- I think it's also related to the continual
learning issue, essentially, where

02:56:57.966 --> 02:57:01.766
the real world is so complex. With LLMs,

02:57:01.846 --> 02:57:05.466
you don't really need to have
something learn for the user,

02:57:05.506 --> 02:57:09.326
because there are a lot of things
everyone has to do. Everyone maybe wants

02:57:09.386 --> 02:57:13.166
to, I don't know, fix their
grammar in their email or

02:57:13.226 --> 02:57:17.016
code or something like that. It's more constrained,
so you can kind of prepare the model for

02:57:17.066 --> 02:57:20.886
that. But preparing the robot for the
real world is harder. I mean, you

02:57:20.906 --> 02:57:24.666
have the robotic foundation
models, and you can learn

02:57:24.686 --> 02:57:28.646
certain things like grasping
things. But then again,

02:57:28.686 --> 02:57:32.366
everyone's house is different.
It's so different, and that is,

02:57:32.426 --> 02:57:36.226
I think, where the robot would have
to learn on the job, essentially.

02:57:36.306 --> 02:57:39.866
And that, I guess, is the
bottleneck right now: how to,

02:57:39.926 --> 02:57:42.406
customize it on the fly, essentially.

02:57:42.466 --> 02:57:46.425
- I don't think I can
possibly understate the

02:57:46.466 --> 02:57:50.062
importance of the thing that doesn't
get talked about almost at all

02:57:50.322 --> 02:57:53.552
by robotics folks or
anyone, which is safety.

02:57:53.662 --> 02:57:57.332
All the interesting complexities we talk
about learning, all the failure modes and

02:57:57.462 --> 02:58:00.902
failure cases, everything we've been talking
about with LLMs—sometimes they fail in

02:58:00.962 --> 02:58:05.982
interesting ways. All of that is
fun and games in the LLM space.

02:58:06.002 --> 02:58:13.181
In the robotic space, in people's homes,
across millions of minutes and billions

02:58:13.242 --> 02:58:17.002
of interactions, you really
are almost allowed to fail

02:58:17.382 --> 02:58:21.341
never. When you have
embodied systems that are

02:58:21.402 --> 02:58:25.841
put out there in the real world,
you just have to solve so many

02:58:27.242 --> 02:58:31.122
problems you never thought you'd have to
solve when just thinking about the general

02:58:31.181 --> 02:58:32.722
robot learning problem.

02:58:32.782 --> 02:58:36.761
- I'm so bearish on in-home learned

02:58:36.822 --> 02:58:40.601
robots for consumer purchase. I'm very
bullish on self-driving cars, and I'm

02:58:40.642 --> 02:58:44.552
very bullish for robotic automation,
e.g., like Amazon distribution

02:58:44.552 --> 02:58:48.422
where Amazon has built whole new
distribution centers designed for robots

02:58:48.482 --> 02:58:52.422
first rather than humans. There's a
lot of excitement in AI circles about

02:58:52.521 --> 02:58:54.072
AI enabling automation

02:58:54.222 --> 02:58:57.822
and mass-scale manufacturing, and I do think that
the path to robots doing that is more reasonable,

02:58:57.962 --> 02:59:01.761
where it's a thing that is

02:59:01.782 --> 02:59:05.722
designed and optimized to do a
repetitive task that a human could

02:59:05.742 --> 02:59:09.402
conceivably do but doesn't
want to. And then I'm much,

02:59:09.462 --> 02:59:13.042
but it's also going to take
a lot longer than people

02:59:13.052 --> 02:59:16.962
probably predict. I think the leap from

02:59:17.021 --> 02:59:20.862
AI singularity to we can now scale
up mass manufacturing in the

02:59:20.922 --> 02:59:24.362
US because we have a massive
AI advantage is one that is

02:59:25.782 --> 02:59:30.532
troubled by a lot of political
and other challenging problems.

02:59:31.722 --> 02:59:37.181
- Let's talk about timelines,
specifically timelines to AGI or

02:59:37.822 --> 02:59:43.742
ASI. Is it fair, as a starting point,
to say that nobody really agrees on the

02:59:43.782 --> 02:59:46.242
definitions of AGI and ASI?

02:59:46.362 --> 02:59:48.582
- I kind of think there's a
lot of disagreement, but

02:59:49.942 --> 02:59:53.862
I've been getting pushback where a lot of people
kind of say the same thing, which is like a

02:59:53.922 --> 02:59:57.442
thing that could reproduce
most digital economic

02:59:57.542 --> 03:00:00.672
work. So, the remote worker
is a fairly reasonable

03:00:00.802 --> 03:00:04.271
example. And I think OpenAI's
definition is somewhat

03:00:04.422 --> 03:00:08.302
related to that, which is like
an AI that can do a lot of

03:00:08.341 --> 03:00:12.062
economically valuable tasks—which I don't
really love as a definition, but I think

03:00:12.101 --> 03:00:15.082
it could be a grounding point,

03:00:15.181 --> 03:00:19.072
because language models today,
while immensely powerful,

03:00:19.122 --> 03:00:23.042
are not this remote worker
drop-in. And there are things that

03:00:23.082 --> 03:00:26.892
could be done by an AI that
are way harder than remote

03:00:26.942 --> 03:00:30.902
work, which are like finding an unexpected

03:00:30.922 --> 03:00:34.662
scientific discovery that you couldn't even posit,
which would be an example of something that

03:00:34.702 --> 03:00:38.302
somebody says is an artificial
superintelligence problem. Or,

03:00:38.341 --> 03:00:45.292
taking in all medical records and
finding linkages across certain

03:00:45.382 --> 03:00:49.242
illnesses that people didn't know, or
figuring out that some common drug can

03:00:49.302 --> 03:00:52.601
treat some niche cancer. They would
say that that is a superintelligence

03:00:52.702 --> 03:00:56.902
thing. So these are kind of natural
tiers. My problem with it is that it

03:00:57.822 --> 03:01:01.582
becomes deeply entwined with the quest
for meaning of AI and these religious

03:01:01.681 --> 03:01:06.622
aspects to it. So there's
different paths you can take it.

03:01:06.662 --> 03:01:10.601
- And I don't even know if the
remote worker is a good definition

03:01:10.642 --> 03:01:14.622
because what exactly is
that? I actually, I mean, I

03:01:14.702 --> 03:01:17.582
like... I don't know if you
like the originally titled

03:01:17.681 --> 03:01:25.062
AI27 report. They focus more on code and
research taste, so the target there is the

03:01:25.101 --> 03:01:28.681
superhuman coder. So they have
several milestone systems:

03:01:28.761 --> 03:01:31.722
Superhuman coders,
superhuman AI researcher,

03:01:31.802 --> 03:01:35.771
then superintelligent AI
researcher, and then the full ASI,

03:01:35.822 --> 03:01:38.841
artificial superintelligence. But

03:01:39.902 --> 03:01:44.021
after you develop the superhuman coder,
everything else follows quickly.

03:01:45.261 --> 03:01:50.912
There, the task is to have fully
autonomous, automated coding.

03:01:52.062 --> 03:01:55.422
So any kind of coding you need
to do in order to perform

03:01:55.482 --> 03:01:59.372
research is fully
automated. And from there,

03:01:59.462 --> 03:02:03.362
humans would be doing AI research
together with that system, and they will

03:02:03.442 --> 03:02:07.401
quickly be able to develop a system that
can actually do the research for you.

03:02:07.482 --> 03:02:14.562
That's the idea. And initially their
prediction was 2027, 2028, and now they've

03:02:15.122 --> 03:02:18.122
pushed it back by three to four years to

03:02:18.242 --> 03:02:21.822
2031 (mean prediction).
Probably my prediction is even

03:02:21.902 --> 03:02:25.782
beyond 2031, but at least you can, in a

03:02:25.862 --> 03:02:31.422
concrete way, think about how difficult
it is to fully automate programming.

03:02:31.462 --> 03:02:35.402
- Yeah, I disagree with some of their
presumptions and dynamics on how

03:02:35.742 --> 03:02:39.642
it would play out, but I think
they did good work in the

03:02:39.662 --> 03:02:43.502
scenario-defining milestones that are
concrete and tell a useful story, which is

03:02:43.542 --> 03:02:46.672
why the reach for this AI 2027 document

03:02:46.802 --> 03:02:50.742
transcended Silicon Valley. It's
because they told a good story and they

03:02:50.761 --> 03:02:52.982
did a lot of rigorous work to do this.

03:02:53.021 --> 03:02:56.882
I think the camp that I fall
into is that AI is so-called

03:02:56.922 --> 03:03:00.792
"jagged," which will be excellent at some
things and really bad at some things.

03:03:00.802 --> 03:03:04.462
I think that when they're close to this

03:03:04.562 --> 03:03:08.422
automated software engineer, what it will
be good at is traditional ML systems

03:03:08.442 --> 03:03:12.392
and frontend, the model is
excellent at; but distributed ML,

03:03:12.392 --> 03:03:16.011
the models are actually quite bad at
because there's so little training data

03:03:16.042 --> 03:03:20.032
on doing large-scale distributed learning.
This is something we already see,

03:03:20.062 --> 03:03:23.692
and I think this will just get amplified.
And then it's kind of messier in these

03:03:23.742 --> 03:03:27.922
trade-offs, like how you think
AI research works and so on.

03:03:28.042 --> 03:03:31.122
- So you think basically a superhuman
coder is almost unachievable,

03:03:31.202 --> 03:03:34.922
because of the jagged nature of the
thing, you're just always going to

03:03:34.982 --> 03:03:38.552
have gaps in capabilities?

03:03:38.562 --> 03:03:42.462
- I think it's assigning completeness to
something where the models are already

03:03:42.502 --> 03:03:46.261
superhuman at some types of code.
I think that will continue.

03:03:46.302 --> 03:03:49.962
And people are creative, so they'll
utilize these incredible abilities

03:03:50.002 --> 03:03:53.978
to fill in the weaknesses of the models
and move really fast. There'll always

03:03:54.038 --> 03:03:57.938
be this dance for a long
time between the humans

03:03:57.978 --> 03:04:01.578
enabling the thing that the model
can't do. And the best AI researchers

03:04:01.598 --> 03:04:04.338
are the ones that can
enable this superpower.

03:04:04.358 --> 03:04:08.018
And I think those lines lead to what we already
see. I think like Claude Code for building a

03:04:08.058 --> 03:04:11.518
website, you can stand up a beautiful
website in a few hours or do data

03:04:11.528 --> 03:04:15.258
going to keep getting better, and
we'll pick up some new coding skills

03:04:15.298 --> 03:04:23.288
along the way. Linking to
what's happening in big tech,

03:04:23.338 --> 03:04:27.058
this AI 2027 report leans into the

03:04:27.118 --> 03:04:30.288
singularity idea, whereas
I think research is messy,

03:04:30.678 --> 03:04:34.558
social and largely in the data
in ways that AI models can't

03:04:34.578 --> 03:04:38.018
process. But what we do have today
is really powerful and these

03:04:39.258 --> 03:04:42.637
tech companies are all collectively buying
into this with tens of billions of dollars of

03:04:42.678 --> 03:04:46.618
investment. So we are going to
get some much better version

03:04:46.678 --> 03:04:50.458
of ChatGPT, a much better version of
Claude Code than we already have.

03:04:50.478 --> 03:04:54.038
I think it's just hard to predict
where that is going, but the

03:04:55.458 --> 03:04:59.348
bright clarity of that future is why some of
the most powerful people in the world are

03:04:59.358 --> 03:05:02.168
putting so much money into this.
And I think it's just kind of

03:05:03.358 --> 03:05:06.748
small differences between like—we don't
actually know what a better version of

03:05:06.758 --> 03:05:13.298
ChatGPT is, but also, can it automate AI
research? I would say probably not, at

03:05:13.378 --> 03:05:17.168
least in this timeframe. Big tech
is going to spend $100 billion much

03:05:17.198 --> 03:05:22.758
faster than we get an automated AI researcher
that enables an AI research singularity.

03:05:22.818 --> 03:05:26.598
- So you think your prediction
would be— if this is

03:05:26.658 --> 03:05:30.778
even a useful milestone or
more than 10 years out?

03:05:30.958 --> 03:05:34.857
- I would say less than that on the software
side, but I think longer than that on

03:05:34.918 --> 03:05:36.538
things like research.

03:05:36.818 --> 03:05:42.918
- Well, let's just for fun try to imagine
a world where all software writing

03:05:42.978 --> 03:05:45.698
is fully automated. Can
you imagine that world?

03:05:46.598 --> 03:05:50.137
- By the end of this year, the amount of
software that'll be automated will be so

03:05:50.208 --> 03:05:54.158
high. But it'll be things like
trying to train a model with

03:05:54.278 --> 03:05:57.778
RL and you need to have
multiple bunches of GPUs

03:05:57.818 --> 03:06:01.958
communicating with each other. That'll
still be hard, but it'll be much easier.

03:06:02.018 --> 03:06:04.637
- One way to think about this—
the full automation of

03:06:04.658 --> 03:06:12.278
programming—is just thinking of lines
of useful code written, the fraction of

03:06:12.378 --> 03:06:16.338
that to the number of humans in the
loop. So presumably there'll be

03:06:16.378 --> 03:06:20.328
for a long time humans in the loop of
software writing. It'll just be fewer and

03:06:20.438 --> 03:06:24.338
fewer relative to the amount
of code written. Right?

03:06:24.398 --> 03:06:28.218
And the superhuman coder—I think
the presumption there is it

03:06:28.278 --> 03:06:32.258
goes to zero, the number of humans
in the loop. What does that world

03:06:32.318 --> 03:06:36.038
look like when the number of
humans in the loop is in the

03:06:36.098 --> 03:06:39.398
hundreds, not in the
hundreds of thousands?

03:06:39.458 --> 03:06:42.938
- I think software engineering will
be driven more to system design

03:06:42.998 --> 03:06:46.878
and goals of outcomes, where I do
think software is largely going to

03:06:46.918 --> 03:06:50.738
be. I think this has been happening
over the last few weeks, where people

03:06:50.778 --> 03:06:54.678
have gone from a month ago saying, "Oh
yeah, agents are kind of slop," which

03:06:54.738 --> 03:07:00.678
is a famous Karpathy quote, to
what is a little bit of a meme—the

03:07:00.778 --> 03:07:04.287
industrialization of software when anyone
can just create software with their

03:07:04.378 --> 03:07:08.218
fingerprints. I do think we are closer
to that side of things, and it takes

03:07:08.258 --> 03:07:11.978
direction and understanding
how systems work

03:07:12.118 --> 03:07:15.918
to extract the best from the language
models. I think it's hard to accept the

03:07:15.938 --> 03:07:19.918
gravity of how much is going to change
with software development and how many

03:07:19.978 --> 03:07:22.507
more people can do things without
ever looking at the code.

03:07:22.518 --> 03:07:26.098
- I think what's interesting is to think
about whether these systems will be

03:07:26.137 --> 03:07:29.938
independent—completely independent in
the sense that, while I have no doubt

03:07:29.947 --> 03:07:33.378
that LLMs will kind of at some
point solve coding in a sense,

03:07:33.458 --> 03:07:37.298
like calculators solve calculating,
right? So at some point, humans

03:07:37.318 --> 03:07:41.018
developed a tool where you never need
a human to calculate that number.

03:07:41.038 --> 03:07:44.988
You just type it in, and it's
an algorithm. You can do it in

03:07:45.198 --> 03:07:49.058
that sense. And I think that's
the same probably for coding. But

03:07:49.387 --> 03:07:53.378
the question isn't... I think what will happen
is, you will just say, "Build that website."

03:07:53.398 --> 03:07:57.137
It will make a really good website, and
then you maybe refine it. But will it

03:07:57.378 --> 03:08:03.758
do things independently where... Will
you still be having humans asking

03:08:03.858 --> 03:08:07.298
the AI to do something? Like will
there be a person to say, "Build that

03:08:07.358 --> 03:08:12.118
website?" Or will there be AI that
just builds websites or something?

03:08:12.158 --> 03:08:15.778
- I think talking about
building websites is—

03:08:15.978 --> 03:08:16.748
- Too simple.

03:08:16.758 --> 03:08:20.658
- The problem with websites and
the problem with the web,

03:08:20.698 --> 03:08:25.828
you know, HTML and all that kind of stuff,
it's very resilient to just ... slop.

03:08:25.998 --> 03:08:29.538
It will show you slop; it's good
at showing slop. I would rather

03:08:30.158 --> 03:08:36.558
think of safety-critical systems,
like asking AI to end-to-end generate

03:08:37.878 --> 03:08:41.646
something that manages
logistics, or manages cars,

03:08:41.658 --> 03:08:45.738
a fleet of cars—all that kind of stuff.
So it end-to-end generates that for you.

03:08:45.798 --> 03:08:49.598
- I think a more intermediate example is
take something like Slack or Microsoft

03:08:49.637 --> 03:08:54.178
Word. I think if organizations
allow it, AI could very easily

03:08:54.858 --> 03:08:58.378
implement features end-to-end and
do a fairly good job for like

03:08:58.658 --> 03:09:02.438
things that you want to try.
You want to add a new tab in

03:09:02.498 --> 03:09:06.038
Slack that you want to use, and I think
AI will be able to do that pretty well.

03:09:06.078 --> 03:09:09.058
- Actually, that's a really great
example. How far away are we from that?

03:09:09.068 --> 03:09:11.698
- Like this year.

03:09:11.758 --> 03:09:15.338
- See, I don't know. I don't know.

03:09:15.378 --> 03:09:17.798
- I guess I don't know how bad production
codebases are, but I think that

03:09:18.637 --> 03:09:22.558
within... on the order of a few years, a
lot of people are going to be pushed to

03:09:22.658 --> 03:09:26.518
be more of a designer and product
manager, where you have multiple of these

03:09:26.598 --> 03:09:30.558
agents that can try things for you and they
might take one to two days to implement

03:09:30.598 --> 03:09:34.468
a feature or attempt to fix a bug.
And you have these dashboards,

03:09:34.498 --> 03:09:38.208
which I think Slack is actually a good dashboard
where your agents will talk to you and

03:09:38.258 --> 03:09:41.798
you'll then give feedback.
But things like,

03:09:42.278 --> 03:09:46.018
if I make a website, like, "Do you
want a passable logo?" I think these

03:09:46.058 --> 03:09:49.978
cohesive design things and the
style is going to be very hard

03:09:50.038 --> 03:09:54.018
for models and deciding on
what to add the next time.

03:09:54.058 --> 03:09:57.878
- I just... Okay. I hang out with a
lot of programmers and some of them

03:09:57.918 --> 03:10:05.864
are a little bit on the skeptical side
in general. That's just their vibe. I

03:10:05.934 --> 03:10:09.613
just think there's a lot of complexity
involved in adding features to complex

03:10:09.684 --> 03:10:13.874
systems. Like, if you look
at the browser, Chrome.

03:10:13.934 --> 03:10:17.734
If I wanted to add a feature,
if I wanted to have tabs

03:10:17.754 --> 03:10:21.334
as opposed to up top, I
want them on the left side.

03:10:21.374 --> 03:10:26.074
Interface-wise, right? I think we're
not... This is not a next-year thing.

03:10:26.134 --> 03:10:29.774
- One of the Claude releases this year, one
of their tests was: we give it a piece of

03:10:29.814 --> 03:10:33.754
software and leave Claude to run to
recreate it entirely, and it could already

03:10:33.814 --> 03:10:37.394
almost rebuild Slack from
scratch, just given the

03:10:37.434 --> 03:10:41.124
parameters of the software and left
in a sandbox environment to do that.

03:10:41.124 --> 03:10:44.174
- So the "from scratch" part,
I like almost better.

03:10:44.194 --> 03:10:47.754
- So it might be that smaller and newer
companies are advantaged, and they're like,

03:10:48.334 --> 03:10:53.724
"We don't have the bloat and complexity,
and therefore this feature exists."

03:10:53.734 --> 03:10:57.634
- And I think this gets to the point you
mentioned, that some people you talk

03:10:57.674 --> 03:11:01.454
to are skeptical. I think that's
not because the LLM can't do

03:11:01.854 --> 03:11:05.274
X, Y, Z. It's because people
don't want it to do it this way.

03:11:05.334 --> 03:11:09.224
- Some of that could be a skill issue
on the human side. We have to be

03:11:09.254 --> 03:11:13.104
honest with ourselves. And some of that
could be an underspecification issue.

03:11:13.154 --> 03:11:20.084
So, programming, it's like you're
just assuming... This is like an

03:11:20.134 --> 03:11:24.054
issue with communication in relationships
and friendships. You're assuming the

03:11:24.094 --> 03:11:27.944
LLM is supposed to read your mind.
This is where spec-driven design is

03:11:27.974 --> 03:11:32.574
really important. Using natural
language to specify what you want.

03:11:32.634 --> 03:11:36.554
- If you talk to people at the labs,
they use these in their training

03:11:36.594 --> 03:11:40.394
and production code. Claude Code is
built with Claude Code, and they all

03:11:40.454 --> 03:11:44.254
use these things extensively. Dario
talks about how much of Claude's

03:11:44.514 --> 03:11:49.484
code... It's like these people are slightly
ahead in terms of the capabilities

03:11:49.954 --> 03:11:53.894
they have and what they
probably spend on inference.

03:11:53.934 --> 03:11:57.614
They could spend 10 to 100x as
much as we're spending on a lowly

03:11:57.734 --> 03:12:02.794
$100 or $200 a month plan. They
truly let it rip. And I think that,

03:12:03.694 --> 03:12:07.594
with the pace of progress
that we have, it seems like-

03:12:07.614 --> 03:12:11.134
a year ago we didn't have Claude Code
and we didn't really have reasoning

03:12:11.144 --> 03:12:15.034
models. The difference between sitting
here today and what we can do with these

03:12:15.074 --> 03:12:18.954
models is significant,
and there's a lot of

03:12:18.994 --> 03:12:23.874
low-hanging fruit to improve them. The
failure modes are pretty dumb. Like-

03:12:23.954 --> 03:12:27.904
"Claude, you tried to use a CLI command I
don't have installed 14 times, and then

03:12:27.954 --> 03:12:31.874
I sent you the command to run."
That, from a modeling perspective,

03:12:31.914 --> 03:12:34.604
is pretty fixable. So I don't know.

03:12:34.614 --> 03:12:38.414
- I agree with you. I've been
becoming more and more bullish in

03:12:38.474 --> 03:12:42.394
general. Speaking to what you're
articulating, I think it is a

03:12:42.454 --> 03:12:46.274
human skill issue.
Anthropic is leading the

03:12:46.334 --> 03:12:50.314
way, along with other
companies, in understanding

03:12:50.354 --> 03:12:54.334
how to best use the models for programming;
therefore, they're effectively

03:12:54.354 --> 03:12:57.954
using them. There are a lot of
programmers on the outskirts who

03:12:58.014 --> 03:13:01.794
don't... I mean, there's not a really good

03:13:01.804 --> 03:13:04.824
guide on how to use them. People
are trying to figure it out, but-

03:13:04.834 --> 03:13:08.774
- It might be very expensive. The
entry point might be $2,000 a

03:13:08.854 --> 03:13:13.714
month, which is only for tech companies
and rich people. That could be it.

03:13:13.754 --> 03:13:17.454
- But it might be worth it. If
the final result is a working

03:13:17.514 --> 03:13:21.474
software system, it might be worth it. By
the way, it's funny how we converged from

03:13:21.514 --> 03:13:25.044
the discussion of timeline to AGI
to something more pragmatic and

03:13:25.134 --> 03:13:28.834
useful. Is there anything
concrete, interesting,

03:13:28.994 --> 03:13:32.664
useful, and profound to be said
about the timeline to AGI and

03:13:32.754 --> 03:13:39.054
ASI? Or are these discussions a bit
too detached from the day to day?

03:13:39.094 --> 03:13:42.454
- There are interesting bets. A lot
of people are trying to do RLVR—

03:13:42.474 --> 03:13:46.434
Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable
Rewards—in real scientific domains,

03:13:46.494 --> 03:13:50.454
where startups with hundreds of millions
of funding have wet labs where they're

03:13:50.494 --> 03:13:54.234
having language models propose
hypotheses that are tested in the real

03:13:54.294 --> 03:14:00.074
world. I would say that they're early,
but with the pace of progress, it's like-

03:14:00.084 --> 03:14:04.074
...maybe they're early by six months
and they make it because they

03:14:04.094 --> 03:14:08.084
were there first, or maybe they're
early by eight years; you don't know.

03:14:08.134 --> 03:14:14.894
That type of moonshot to branch
this momentum into other sciences

03:14:15.554 --> 03:14:18.774
would be very transformative. If,

03:14:19.154 --> 03:14:23.114
AlphaFold moments happen in all
sorts of other scientific domains

03:14:23.174 --> 03:14:27.094
by a startup solving this. I think
there are startups—maybe Harmonic is

03:14:27.154 --> 03:14:30.994
one—where they're going all in
on language models plus Lean for

03:14:31.034 --> 03:14:34.624
math. You had another guest where
you talked about this recently, and

03:14:34.654 --> 03:14:38.424
we don't know exactly
what's going to fall out of

03:14:38.534 --> 03:14:42.334
spending $100 million on that
model. Most of them will

03:14:42.374 --> 03:14:46.114
fail, but a couple might be big
breakthroughs that are very

03:14:46.154 --> 03:14:49.854
different than ChatGPT or
Claude Code type software

03:14:50.374 --> 03:14:54.074
experiences. A tool that's only good for a

03:14:54.134 --> 03:14:57.703
PhD mathematician but makes
them 100X effective...

03:14:58.114 --> 03:15:02.044
- I agree. I think this will happen
in a lot of domains, especially

03:15:02.154 --> 03:15:05.934
domains that have a lot of resources,

03:15:05.974 --> 03:15:09.824
like finance, legal, and
pharmaceutical companies.

03:15:09.914 --> 03:15:13.554
But then again, is it really
AGI? Because we are now

03:15:13.634 --> 03:15:17.614
specializing it again. Is it really
that much different from back

03:15:17.634 --> 03:15:21.374
in the day when we had specialized
algorithms? It's just the same thing,

03:15:21.474 --> 03:15:25.454
way more sophisticated, but I don't know,

03:15:25.474 --> 03:15:29.414
is there a threshold for AGI? I think
the real cool thing here is that

03:15:29.454 --> 03:15:33.314
we have foundation models we
can specialize. That's like the

03:15:33.354 --> 03:15:37.234
breakthrough. Right now, I think we
are not there yet because, first,

03:15:37.534 --> 03:15:39.054
it's too expensive, but also,

03:15:39.974 --> 03:15:43.374
ChatGPT doesn't just give away their
model to customize it. I think

03:15:44.014 --> 03:15:47.934
once that's true... And I can
imagine this as a business model,

03:15:47.994 --> 03:15:51.574
where OpenAI says at some point,

03:15:51.584 --> 03:15:55.394
"Hey, Bank of America, for $100
million we will do your custom model,"

03:15:55.434 --> 03:15:59.154
something like that. I think
that will be the huge economic

03:15:59.234 --> 03:16:01.844
value-add. The other thing, though, is

03:16:02.034 --> 03:16:05.958
also... Companies, I mean,
what is the differentiating

03:16:06.058 --> 03:16:09.658
factor? If everyone uses the
same LLM, if everyone uses

03:16:09.738 --> 03:16:13.628
ChatGPT, they will all do
the same thing. Well, if

03:16:13.938 --> 03:16:17.418
everyone is moving in lockstep,
but companies want to have a

03:16:17.458 --> 03:16:21.438
competitive advantage, there is
no way around using some of their

03:16:21.478 --> 03:16:26.638
private data and specializing.
It's gonna be interesting.

03:16:26.718 --> 03:16:30.548
- Seeing the pace of progress, it does
feel like things are coming. I don't

03:16:30.578 --> 03:16:35.858
think the AGI and ASI thresholds
are particularly useful.

03:16:35.918 --> 03:16:39.818
- I think the real question, and
this relates to the remote worker

03:16:39.918 --> 03:16:47.318
thing, is: when are we going to see a
big, obvious leap in economic impact?

03:16:47.958 --> 03:16:51.558
Because currently there's
not been an obvious leap in

03:16:51.718 --> 03:16:55.608
the economic impact of
LLM models, for example.

03:16:55.678 --> 03:16:59.348
And that's, you know, aside
from AGI or ASI, all that

03:16:59.498 --> 03:17:06.328
stuff, there's a real question of, "When
are we going to see a GDP..." "...jump?"

03:17:06.338 --> 03:17:10.118
- Yeah, what is the GDP made up
of? A lot of it is financial

03:17:10.238 --> 03:17:13.638
services, so I don't know what this is.

03:17:13.778 --> 03:17:13.948
- Right, GDP is a-

03:17:13.948 --> 03:17:17.618
- It's just hard for me to
think about the GDP bump, but

03:17:18.778 --> 03:17:22.578
I would say that software development
becomes valuable in a different

03:17:22.658 --> 03:17:25.818
way, when you no longer have
to look at the code anymore.

03:17:25.878 --> 03:17:29.798
When Claude Code will make
you a small business.

03:17:29.838 --> 03:17:33.098
Which is essentially, Claude can set up your
website, your bank account, your email, and your

03:17:33.598 --> 03:17:37.578
whatever else. And you just have
to express what you're trying

03:17:37.638 --> 03:17:40.638
to put into the world. That's not just an

03:17:41.498 --> 03:17:45.228
enterprise market, but it is hard. I don't
know how you get people to try doing

03:17:45.278 --> 03:17:49.138
that. I guess if ChatGPT can do
it—people are trying ChatGPT.

03:17:49.218 --> 03:17:53.158
- I think it boils down to the scientific
question of, "How hard is tool use

03:17:53.258 --> 03:17:57.218
to solve?" Because a lot of
the stuff you're implying,

03:17:57.228 --> 03:18:01.098
the remote work stuff, is tool
use. It's like... computer

03:18:01.258 --> 03:18:04.998
use, like how you have an
LLM that goes out there,

03:18:05.058 --> 03:18:08.938
this agentic system, and does
something in the world, and

03:18:08.998 --> 03:18:11.398
only screws up 1% of the time.

03:18:11.958 --> 03:18:12.527
- Computer use-

03:18:12.527 --> 03:18:12.538
- Or less.

03:18:12.578 --> 03:18:16.388
- ...is a good example of what labs care about
and we haven't seen a lot of progress on.

03:18:16.398 --> 03:18:20.388
We saw multiple demos in 2025 of, like,

03:18:20.418 --> 03:18:24.978
Claude can use your computer, or OpenAI
had operator, and they all suck.

03:18:24.988 --> 03:18:28.818
They're investing money in this,
and I think that'll be a good

03:18:28.858 --> 03:18:31.198
example. Whereas actually,
something where it just seems

03:18:32.518 --> 03:18:35.918
like taking over the whole
screen seems a lot harder

03:18:35.998 --> 03:18:39.907
than having an API that they
can call in the back end.

03:18:39.958 --> 03:18:43.818
For some of that, you have to set up a different
environment for them all to work in. They're

03:18:43.838 --> 03:18:47.378
not working on your MacBook; they
are individually interfacing with

03:18:47.718 --> 03:18:51.698
Google and Amazon and Slack, and they
handle all these things in a very

03:18:51.778 --> 03:18:55.878
different way than humans do. So some
of this might be structural blockers.

03:18:55.938 --> 03:18:59.538
- Also, specification-wise,
I think the problem is

03:18:59.598 --> 03:19:03.498
for arbitrary tasks, well, you
still have to specify what you

03:19:03.578 --> 03:19:07.478
want your LLM to do. And how
do you do that? What is the

03:19:07.518 --> 03:19:11.218
environment? How do you specify? You
can say what the end goal is, but

03:19:11.298 --> 03:19:15.278
if it can't solve the end goal...
with LLMs, if you ask it for text, it

03:19:15.318 --> 03:19:19.138
can always clarify or do
sub-steps. How do you put that

03:19:19.178 --> 03:19:23.138
information into a system that, let's say,
books a travel trip for you? You can say,

03:19:23.158 --> 03:19:27.138
"You screwed up my credit card information,"
but even to get it to that point,

03:19:27.178 --> 03:19:31.018
even to get it to that point,
how do you, as a user, guide the

03:19:31.078 --> 03:19:36.028
model before it can even attempt that?
I think the interface is really hard.

03:19:36.078 --> 03:19:39.318
- Yeah, it has to learn a lot
about you specifically.

03:19:39.398 --> 03:19:43.358
And this goes to continual learning,
about the general mistakes

03:19:43.428 --> 03:19:48.318
that are made throughout, and then
mistakes that are made through you.

03:19:48.378 --> 03:19:51.478
- All the AI interfaces are getting
set up to ask humans for input.

03:19:51.538 --> 03:19:54.108
I think Claude Code we talked about a lot.

03:19:54.108 --> 03:19:58.038
It asks feedback and questions. If
it doesn't have enough specification

03:19:58.058 --> 03:20:02.008
on your plan or your desired goal, it starts
to ask questions, "Would you rather?"

03:20:02.018 --> 03:20:04.998
We talked about Memory,
which saves across chats.

03:20:06.258 --> 03:20:10.178
Its first implementation is kind
of odd, where it'll mention my

03:20:10.238 --> 03:20:11.308
dog's name or something in a chat.

03:20:11.308 --> 03:20:15.258
I'm like, "You don't need to be
subtle about this. I don't care."

03:20:15.298 --> 03:20:18.998
But things that are emerging,
ChatGPT has the Pulse feature.

03:20:19.018 --> 03:20:22.978
Which is like a curated
couple of paragraphs with

03:20:23.018 --> 03:20:26.998
links to something to look at,
and people talk about how models

03:20:27.038 --> 03:20:30.538
are going to ask you
questions. Which I think is a

03:20:30.618 --> 03:20:34.598
very... It's probably going to
work. The language model knows

03:20:34.638 --> 03:20:37.848
you had a doctor appointment and asks,
"Hey, how are you feeling after that?"

03:20:37.848 --> 03:20:41.758
Which again goes into the territory
where humans are very susceptible

03:20:41.798 --> 03:20:45.748
to this, and there's a lot of
social change to come. But also,

03:20:45.778 --> 03:20:49.668
they're experimenting with having the
models engage. Some people like this

03:20:49.698 --> 03:20:53.598
Pulse feature, which processes your
chats and automatically searches

03:20:53.638 --> 03:20:58.957
for information and puts it in the app.
So there are a lot of things coming.

03:20:58.978 --> 03:21:02.838
- I used that feature before, and I
always feel bad because it does

03:21:02.858 --> 03:21:06.818
that every day, and I rarely check
it out. It's like, how much compute

03:21:06.898 --> 03:21:11.948
is burned on something I don't even look
at, you know? It's kind of like, "Oh..."

03:21:11.958 --> 03:21:15.558
- There's also a lot of idle compute
in the world, so don't feel too bad.

03:21:16.378 --> 03:21:20.358
- Okay. Do you think new
ideas might be needed?

03:21:20.378 --> 03:21:24.258
Is it possible that the path to
AGI, however we define that,

03:21:24.298 --> 03:21:28.798
to solve computer use more generally,
to solve biology and chemistry

03:21:30.018 --> 03:21:37.658
and physics—sort of the Dario Amodei
definition of AGI? Do you think it's

03:21:37.698 --> 03:21:45.238
possible that totally new ideas
are needed? Non-LLM, non-RL ideas?

03:21:45.538 --> 03:21:49.828
What might they look like? We're
going into philosophy land a bit.

03:21:50.818 --> 03:21:54.618
- For something like a singularity
to happen, I would say yes.

03:21:54.698 --> 03:21:58.278
The new ideas could be architectures
or training algorithms,

03:21:58.318 --> 03:22:02.148
fundamental deep learning
things. But in that nature,

03:22:02.218 --> 03:22:06.210
they're pretty hard to predict.
I think we won't get very

03:22:06.269 --> 03:22:10.250
far even without those advances.
We might get the software

03:22:10.390 --> 03:22:14.109
solution, but it might stop at
software and not do computer use

03:22:14.150 --> 03:22:17.869
without more innovation. So I think
that a lot of progress will be

03:22:17.910 --> 03:22:21.810
coming, but if you're gonna zoom
out, there's still ideas in the

03:22:21.849 --> 03:22:24.830
next 30 years that are
gonna look like that was a

03:22:24.869 --> 03:22:28.650
major scientific innovation
that enabled the

03:22:28.710 --> 03:22:32.849
next chapter of this. And I don't know
if it comes in one year or in 15 years.

03:22:32.990 --> 03:22:36.949
- Yeah. I wonder if the bitter lesson holds
true for the next 100 years, what that looks

03:22:37.009 --> 03:22:37.810
like.

03:22:37.869 --> 03:22:41.730
- If scaling laws are fundamental in deep
learning, I think the bitter lesson

03:22:41.769 --> 03:22:45.310
will always apply, which is
compute will become more

03:22:45.369 --> 03:22:49.179
abundant, but even within
abundant compute, the ones

03:22:49.210 --> 03:22:53.000
that have a steeper scaling
law slope or a better offset—

03:22:53.029 --> 03:22:56.050
like, this is a 2D plot of
performance and compute—and like

03:22:56.869 --> 03:23:01.529
even if there's more compute available,
the ones that get 100x out of it will win.

03:23:01.589 --> 03:23:06.050
- It might be something like literally
computer clusters orbiting Earth

03:23:07.689 --> 03:23:09.529
with solar panels.

03:23:09.589 --> 03:23:13.460
- The problem with that is heat dissipation.
You get all the radiation from the sun

03:23:13.589 --> 03:23:17.550
and don't have any air to dissipate heat.
But there is a lot of space to put clusters.

03:23:17.570 --> 03:23:21.429
There's a lot of solar energy there and
you could figure out the heat dissipation,

03:23:21.490 --> 03:23:25.330
as there is a lot of energy and there
probably could be engineering will to solve

03:23:25.390 --> 03:23:27.410
the heat problem— so there could be.

03:23:27.470 --> 03:23:30.410
- Is it possible—and we should say
that it definitely is possible—

03:23:30.449 --> 03:23:39.130
that we're basically going to be
plateauing this year? Not in terms of—

03:23:39.150 --> 03:23:43.009
the system capabilities, but
what they actually mean for

03:23:43.089 --> 03:23:50.449
human civilization. So on the coding
front, really nice websites will be built.

03:23:50.589 --> 03:23:52.869
Very nice auto-complete.

03:23:53.670 --> 03:24:01.109
Very nice way to understand code bases
and maybe help debug, but really just a

03:24:01.150 --> 03:24:04.810
very nice helper on the coding
front. It can help research

03:24:04.880 --> 03:24:08.550
mathematicians do some
math. It can help you with

03:24:08.609 --> 03:24:12.310
shopping. It's a nice
helper. It's Clippy on

03:24:12.369 --> 03:24:19.769
steroids. What else? It may be a good
education tool and all that kind of stuff,

03:24:19.849 --> 03:24:23.689
but computer use turns out
extremely difficult to

03:24:23.750 --> 03:24:27.689
solve. So I'm trying to frame the cynical

03:24:27.750 --> 03:24:31.609
case in all these domains
where there's not a really

03:24:31.730 --> 03:24:35.689
huge economic impact, but realize
how costly it is to train these

03:24:35.730 --> 03:24:39.650
systems at every level, both the
pre-training and the inference,

03:24:39.689 --> 03:24:43.529
how costly the inference is,
the reasoning, all of that.

03:24:43.630 --> 03:24:47.210
Like, is that possible? And how
likely is that, do you think?

03:24:47.650 --> 03:24:51.330
- When you look at the models, there are
so many obvious things to improve and

03:24:51.750 --> 03:24:55.630
it takes a long time to train
these models and to do this art,

03:24:55.710 --> 03:24:59.650
and it'll take us with the ideas
that we have multiple years

03:24:59.750 --> 03:25:03.390
to actually saturate in terms
of whatever benchmark or

03:25:03.490 --> 03:25:07.310
performance we are searching
for. It might serve very narrow

03:25:07.330 --> 03:25:11.210
niches; like the average
ChatGPT 800 million user might

03:25:11.250 --> 03:25:15.009
not get a lot of benefit out of this,
but it is going to serve different

03:25:15.050 --> 03:25:17.949
populations by getting
better at different things.

03:25:18.349 --> 03:25:21.910
- But I think what everybody's
chasing now is a

03:25:22.009 --> 03:25:25.949
general system that's useful
to everybody. So, okay, so if

03:25:26.009 --> 03:25:27.970
that's not... That can plateau, right?

03:25:28.189 --> 03:25:31.769
- I think that dream is actually kind of
dying. As you talked about with the

03:25:31.849 --> 03:25:33.369
specialized models where it's like...

03:25:34.650 --> 03:25:38.970
And multimodal is often... Video generation
is a totally different thing. Thing.

03:25:39.050 --> 03:25:41.369
- "That dream is kind of
dying" is a big statement,

03:25:42.210 --> 03:25:46.089
because I don't know if it's dying.
If you ask the actual frontier

03:25:46.109 --> 03:25:48.410
lab people, they... I mean,
they're still chasing it, right?

03:25:48.490 --> 03:25:52.310
- I do think they are still rushing
to get the next model out,

03:25:52.369 --> 03:25:56.310
which will be much better than the...
"Much" is a relative term, but it will

03:25:56.369 --> 03:26:00.269
be better than the previous one.
And I can't see them slowing down.

03:26:00.330 --> 03:26:03.830
I just think the gains
will be made or felt more

03:26:03.869 --> 03:26:07.349
through not only scaling the model, but

03:26:07.929 --> 03:26:11.830
now... I feel like there's a lot of tech
debt. It's like, "Well, let's just put the

03:26:11.869 --> 03:26:12.869
better model in there."

03:26:13.990 --> 03:26:17.820
Better model, better model. And now
people are like, "Okay, let's also

03:26:17.910 --> 03:26:20.060
at the same time improve
everything around it too."

03:26:20.060 --> 03:26:23.619
Like the engineering of the
context and inference scaling.

03:26:23.649 --> 03:26:27.410
The big labs will still keep
doing that. And now also the

03:26:27.449 --> 03:26:31.210
smaller labs will catch up,
because now they are hiring more.

03:26:31.230 --> 03:26:35.109
There will be more people and
LLMs. It's kind of like a circle.

03:26:35.189 --> 03:26:39.140
They also make them more productive and
it's just... It's like amplification.

03:26:39.189 --> 03:26:43.170
I think what we can expect is
amplification, but not like a change

03:26:43.230 --> 03:26:46.929
of any... not like a paradigm change.
I don't think that is true, but

03:26:46.990 --> 03:26:50.039
everything will be just amplified
and amplified, and I can see that

03:26:50.070 --> 03:26:52.769
continuing for a long time, you know?

03:26:52.810 --> 03:26:56.630
- Yeah. I guess my statement that the
dream is dying depends on exactly

03:26:56.670 --> 03:27:00.220
what you think it's gonna be doing.
Like, Claude Code is a general model

03:27:00.250 --> 03:27:04.509
that can do a lot of things,
but it's not necessarily...

03:27:05.330 --> 03:27:09.289
It depends a lot on integrations. I bet
Claude Code could do a fairly good job

03:27:09.330 --> 03:27:13.269
of doing your email, and the hardest part
is figuring out how to give information

03:27:13.330 --> 03:27:17.250
to it and how to get it to
be able to send your emails.

03:27:17.310 --> 03:27:21.189
But that's just kind of like... I
think it goes back to what is the

03:27:21.310 --> 03:27:25.289
"one model to rule everything" ethos,
which is just like a thing in the

03:27:25.330 --> 03:27:29.098
cloud that handles your entire digital
life and is way smarter than everybody.

03:27:29.250 --> 03:27:32.779
It's like it's operating in a...

03:27:34.330 --> 03:27:38.990
So it's an interesting leap of faith
to go from "Claude Code becomes that,"

03:27:39.890 --> 03:27:45.730
which in some ways is... There are some
avenues for that, but I do think that the

03:27:46.589 --> 03:27:49.109
rhetoric of the industry
is a little bit different.

03:27:49.210 --> 03:27:52.830
- I think the immediate thing
we will feel next as a normal

03:27:52.949 --> 03:27:56.740
person using LLMs will probably
be related to something

03:27:56.789 --> 03:28:00.509
trivial, like making figures.
Right now, LLMs are terrible at

03:28:00.550 --> 03:28:04.390
making figures. Is it because we
are getting served the cheap models

03:28:04.470 --> 03:28:08.859
with much less inference compute
than behind the scenes? Maybe some.

03:28:09.970 --> 03:28:13.939
Like, there are some ways to get
better figures, but if you ask today,

03:28:13.939 --> 03:28:17.905
..."Draw a flowchart of X, Y, Z,"
it's most of the time terrible.

03:28:18.006 --> 03:28:21.936
And it is a very simple task for
a human. I think it's almost

03:28:22.426 --> 03:28:25.086
easier sometimes to draw something
than to write something.

03:28:25.145 --> 03:28:28.885
- Yeah, the multimodal understanding does
feel like something that is odd...

03:28:28.965 --> 03:28:31.205
...that it's not better solved.

03:28:31.285 --> 03:28:35.125
- I think we're not saying one obvious
thing that we're not realizing,

03:28:35.186 --> 03:28:39.145
that's a gigantic thing that's hard
to measure, which is making all of

03:28:39.186 --> 03:28:46.065
human knowledge accessible—
—to the entire world.

03:28:46.866 --> 03:28:50.586
One thing that is hard to articulate
is the huge difference between

03:28:50.645 --> 03:28:54.305
Google Search and an LLM. I
feel like I can basically

03:28:54.446 --> 03:29:04.155
ask an LLM anything and get an answer, and
it's doing less and less hallucination.

03:29:04.166 --> 03:29:07.965
And that means understanding my own life,

03:29:08.065 --> 03:29:11.885
figuring out a career trajectory,
solving the problems all around me,

03:29:11.965 --> 03:29:15.926
learning about anything
through human history.

03:29:16.746 --> 03:29:21.346
I feel like nobody's
really talking about that,

03:29:22.385 --> 03:29:25.746
because they just immediately take
it for granted that this is awesome.

03:29:25.766 --> 03:29:29.666
That's why everybody's using it:
because you get answers for stuff.

03:29:29.785 --> 03:29:33.625
Think about the impact across time.

03:29:33.666 --> 03:29:37.565
This is not just in the United
States; it's all across the world.

03:29:37.606 --> 03:29:40.746
Kids throughout the world being
able to learn these ideas—

03:29:41.145 --> 03:29:48.385
the impact that has across time is
probably... ...That's the real impact.

03:29:48.405 --> 03:29:52.125
Talk about GDP; it won't be
like a leap. It'll be...

03:29:52.705 --> 03:29:56.465
...that's how we get to Mars,
that's how we build these things,

03:29:56.526 --> 03:30:00.315
that's how we have a million new OpenAIs
and all the innovation from there.

03:30:00.366 --> 03:30:06.465
It's this quiet force that permeates
everything: human knowledge.

03:30:06.506 --> 03:30:10.446
- I agree with you. In a sense, it
makes knowledge more accessible,

03:30:10.465 --> 03:30:13.666
but it also depends on what the topic is.

03:30:13.866 --> 03:30:21.125
For something like math, you can
ask it questions and it answers,

03:30:21.186 --> 03:30:28.935
but if you want to learn a topic from
scratch, the sweet spot is still elsewhere.

03:30:28.946 --> 03:30:32.885
There are really good math
textbooks laid out linearly,

03:30:32.946 --> 03:30:36.785
and that is a proven
strategy to learn a topic.

03:30:36.805 --> 03:30:38.666
It makes sense, if you start from zero,

03:30:39.785 --> 03:30:43.606
to use information-dense
text to soak it up,

03:30:43.866 --> 03:30:47.606
but then you use the LLM to
make infinite exercises. Like,

03:30:47.666 --> 03:30:51.496
you have problems in a certain area
or have questions that something's-

03:30:51.586 --> 03:30:55.485
uncertain about certain
things, you ask it to

03:30:55.645 --> 03:30:58.285
generate example problems, you solve them,

03:30:59.266 --> 03:31:02.805
and you need more background
knowledge, you ask it to generate

03:31:02.866 --> 03:31:08.616
that. But then... it won't
give you anything, let's

03:31:08.645 --> 03:31:12.416
say, that is not in the textbook.
It's just packaging it differently,

03:31:12.586 --> 03:31:13.465
if that makes sense.

03:31:13.485 --> 03:31:17.086
But then there are things I feel
like where it also adds value in a

03:31:17.166 --> 03:31:21.145
more timely sense, where there is no good

03:31:21.166 --> 03:31:24.965
alternative besides a human doing
it on the fly. For example, if

03:31:25.026 --> 03:31:28.826
you're planning to go to
Disneyland and you try to

03:31:28.866 --> 03:31:32.705
figure out which tickets to
buy for which park when, well,

03:31:32.766 --> 03:31:36.595
there is no textbook on that. There
is no information-dense resource.

03:31:36.625 --> 03:31:40.285
There's only the sparse internet, and
then there is a lot of value in the

03:31:40.366 --> 03:31:44.305
LLM. You just ask it. You have
constraints on traveling these days.

03:31:44.315 --> 03:31:48.235
I want to go there and there. Please
figure out what I need, when and

03:31:48.246 --> 03:31:51.746
from where, what it costs and
stuff like that, and it is a very

03:31:51.805 --> 03:31:55.326
customized, on-the-fly package.

03:31:56.006 --> 03:31:59.654
And this is like one of a thousand
examples of personalized-

03:31:59.705 --> 03:32:05.145
Personalization is essentially pulling
information from the sparse internet, the

03:32:05.205 --> 03:32:06.926
non-information-dense thing where

03:32:07.926 --> 03:32:11.746
there's no better version that exists.
It just doesn't exist. You make it

03:32:11.826 --> 03:32:12.586
almost from scratch.

03:32:12.625 --> 03:32:16.045
- And if it does exist, it's full of-
speaking of Disney World, full of-

03:32:16.106 --> 03:32:24.026
what would you call it? Ad slop. It's
impossible. Take any city in the world,

03:32:25.065 --> 03:32:29.106
what are the top 10 things to do?
An LLM is just way better to ask

03:32:29.116 --> 03:32:29.955
than anything on the internet.

03:32:29.985 --> 03:32:33.904
- Well, for now, that's because they're
subsidized and they're gonna be paid for

03:32:33.965 --> 03:32:35.826
by ads.

03:32:35.926 --> 03:32:36.895
- Oh my goodness.

03:32:37.026 --> 03:32:38.246
- It's coming.

03:32:38.285 --> 03:32:44.485
- No. No. I mean, I'm hoping there's a
very clear indication what's an ad

03:32:44.496 --> 03:32:46.256
and what's not an ad in that context.

03:32:46.305 --> 03:32:50.205
- That's something I mentioned a
few years ago. If, I don't know,

03:32:50.285 --> 03:32:54.145
if you are looking for a new
running shoe, well, is it a

03:32:54.205 --> 03:32:58.065
coincidence that Nike maybe comes
up first? Maybe, maybe not.

03:32:58.125 --> 03:33:02.065
But I think there are clear laws.
You have to be clear about that.

03:33:02.125 --> 03:33:06.506
I think that's what everyone fears.
It's the subtle message in there,

03:33:07.346 --> 03:33:10.955
but that also brings us
to the topic of ads,

03:33:11.086 --> 03:33:15.006
where I think this was a
thing. Hopefully, I think for-

03:33:15.026 --> 03:33:18.815
in 2025, just because I think it's

03:33:18.866 --> 03:33:22.846
they're still not making money
in other ways right now.

03:33:22.916 --> 03:33:26.746
Having ad spots in there... but
the thing is, they couldn't,

03:33:26.805 --> 03:33:31.735
because there are alternatives without
ads and people would just flock-

03:33:31.735 --> 03:33:34.946
to the other products.
It's also just crazy how-

03:33:35.045 --> 03:33:38.666
yeah, how they're one-upping
each other, spending

03:33:39.106 --> 03:33:41.645
so much money to just get the users.

03:33:41.686 --> 03:33:44.794
- I think so. Like, some Instagram
ads— I don't use Instagram,

03:33:44.794 --> 03:33:51.006
but I understand the appeal of paying
a platform to find users who will

03:33:51.086 --> 03:33:56.606
genuinely like your product, and that is
the best case of things like Instagram ads.

03:33:56.625 --> 03:34:00.026
But there are also plenty of cases
where advertising is very awful for

03:34:00.065 --> 03:34:02.885
incentives, and I think that a world where

03:34:03.785 --> 03:34:07.686
the power of AI can integrate with that
positive view of, "I am a person and

03:34:07.805 --> 03:34:11.766
I have a small business and I
want to make the best, I don't

03:34:11.805 --> 03:34:15.785
know, damn steak knives in the world,
and I want to sell them to somebody

03:34:15.826 --> 03:34:19.465
who needs them." And if AI can make
that sort of advertising thing

03:34:19.705 --> 03:34:23.362
work even better, that's very good
for the world, especially with

03:34:23.372 --> 03:34:26.982
digital infrastructure, because
that's how the modern web has been

03:34:27.021 --> 03:34:30.542
built. But that's not to say that

03:34:30.601 --> 03:34:34.462
addicting feeds so that you
can show people more content

03:34:34.521 --> 03:34:38.382
is a good thing. So, I think that's even
what OpenAI would say, is they want to

03:34:38.442 --> 03:34:42.161
find a way that can make
the monetization upside of

03:34:42.202 --> 03:34:45.042
ads while still giving their users agency.

03:34:45.081 --> 03:34:49.072
And I personally would think that Google is
probably going to be better at figuring out

03:34:49.101 --> 03:34:52.421
how to do this, because
they already have ad supply

03:34:53.122 --> 03:34:56.902
and if they figure out how to turn
this demand in their Gemini app into

03:34:56.942 --> 03:35:00.032
useful ads, then they can turn it on. And

03:35:01.341 --> 03:35:04.921
somebody will figure it out—I don't know
if it's this year, but there will be

03:35:04.942 --> 03:35:06.161
experiments with it.

03:35:06.261 --> 03:35:09.702
- I do think what holds companies back
right now is really just that the

03:35:09.742 --> 03:35:13.661
competition is not doing it. It's
more like a reputation thing.

03:35:13.742 --> 03:35:17.601
It's just, I think people are just
afraid right now of ruining or

03:35:17.642 --> 03:35:19.992
losing their reputation, losing users,

03:35:19.992 --> 03:35:23.062
because it would make headlines if
someone launched these ads. But—

03:35:23.181 --> 03:35:27.142
- Unless they were great, but the first ads
won't be great because it's a hard problem

03:35:27.161 --> 03:35:28.021
that we don't know how to solve.

03:35:28.062 --> 03:35:32.021
- Yeah, I think also the first version of
that will likely be something like on X,

03:35:32.062 --> 03:35:35.782
like the timeline where you have a
promoted post sometimes in between.

03:35:35.802 --> 03:35:39.562
It'll be something where it will say "promoted"
or something small, and then there will be an

03:35:39.622 --> 03:35:43.021
image. I think right now the problem
is: who makes the first move?

03:35:43.081 --> 03:35:46.581
- If we go 10 years out, the
proposition for ads is that

03:35:47.222 --> 03:35:50.011
you will make so much money on
ads by having so many users

03:35:50.011 --> 03:35:54.362
that you can use this to fund better R&amp;D
and make better models, which is why

03:35:54.782 --> 03:35:58.761
YouTube is dominating the market for any—

03:35:58.962 --> 03:36:02.661
Netflix is scared of
YouTube. They have the ads,

03:36:02.702 --> 03:36:06.562
they make—I pay $28 a month for
Premium. They make at least $28 a month

03:36:06.802 --> 03:36:10.761
off of me and many other people.
And they're just creating

03:36:10.862 --> 03:36:14.702
such a dominant position in video. So
I think that's the proposition: that

03:36:15.001 --> 03:36:17.952
ads can make you have
a sustained advantage.

03:36:17.952 --> 03:36:21.542
in what you're spending per
user. But there's so much

03:36:21.622 --> 03:36:26.171
money in it right now that
somebody starting that flywheel

03:36:26.181 --> 03:36:28.942
is scary because it's a long-term bet.

03:36:29.081 --> 03:36:33.062
- Do you think there'll be some
crazy big moves this year

03:36:33.382 --> 03:36:39.402
business-wise? Like Google or Apple
acquiring Anthropic or something like this?

03:36:40.122 --> 03:36:43.851
- Dario will never sell, but we are
starting to see some types of

03:36:43.882 --> 03:36:46.690
consolidation with Groq for $20 billion

03:36:46.761 --> 03:36:50.622
and Scale AI for almost
$30 billion and countless

03:36:50.702 --> 03:36:54.442
other deals like this that are
structured in a way that is

03:36:54.542 --> 03:36:58.362
detrimental to the Silicon
Valley ecosystem, which is this

03:36:58.402 --> 03:37:02.202
licensing deal where not
everybody gets brought along,

03:37:02.261 --> 03:37:06.251
rather than a full acquisition that
benefits the rank-and-file employee

03:37:06.282 --> 03:37:09.942
by getting their stock vested.
That's a big issue for culture to

03:37:09.982 --> 03:37:13.462
address because the startup
ecosystem is the lifeblood where,

03:37:14.402 --> 03:37:20.521
if you join a startup, even if it's not
successful, it might get acquired on a

03:37:20.542 --> 03:37:24.402
cheap premium and you'll get
paid out for this equity.

03:37:24.411 --> 03:37:27.581
These licensing deals are taking
the top talent a lot of the time.

03:37:27.622 --> 03:37:31.501
The deal for Groq to
NVIDIA is rumored to be

03:37:31.521 --> 03:37:35.261
better to the employees, but it is
still this antitrust-avoiding thing.

03:37:35.271 --> 03:37:39.030
But I think that this trend of
consolidation will continue.

03:37:39.062 --> 03:37:43.042
Me and many smart people I
respect have been expecting

03:37:43.081 --> 03:37:46.042
consolidation to have
happened sooner, but it seems

03:37:46.122 --> 03:37:49.442
like some of these things
are starting to turn,

03:37:49.482 --> 03:37:55.202
but at the same time, companies are
raising ridiculous amounts of money for

03:37:55.212 --> 03:37:59.122
reasons where I'm like, "I don't
know why you're taking that money."

03:37:59.181 --> 03:38:04.702
So it's mixed this year, but some
consolidation pressure is starting.

03:38:04.742 --> 03:38:08.421
- What kind of surprising consolidation
will we see? You say Anthropic

03:38:08.501 --> 03:38:12.192
is a "never." I mean, Groq is a big
one. Groq with a Q, by the way.

03:38:12.482 --> 03:38:16.402
- Yeah. There's just a lot of startups
and a very high premium on AI startups.

03:38:16.462 --> 03:38:19.161
So there could be a lot of

03:38:19.171 --> 03:38:19.642
- that kind of stuff, yeah.

03:38:19.661 --> 03:38:23.542
- $10 billion range acquisitions, which
is really big for a startup that was

03:38:23.581 --> 03:38:26.402
maybe founded a year ago. I think

03:38:26.742 --> 03:38:30.661
Manus.ai... this company based in
Singapore that Meta-founded was

03:38:30.702 --> 03:38:34.622
founded eight months ago and then had
a $2 billion exit. I think there will

03:38:34.681 --> 03:38:39.921
be some other multi-billion dollar
acquisitions, like Perplexity.

03:38:39.931 --> 03:38:39.982
- Like Perplexity, right?

03:38:40.001 --> 03:38:43.600
- Yeah, people rumor them to
Apple. I think there's a lot of

03:38:43.642 --> 03:38:47.632
of pressure and liquidity
in AI. There's pressure on

03:38:47.661 --> 03:38:49.732
big companies to have outcomes and-

03:38:50.081 --> 03:38:54.042
I would guess that a big
acquisition gives people leeway

03:38:54.052 --> 03:38:56.462
to then tell the next
chapter of that story.

03:38:56.501 --> 03:39:00.222
- I guess Cursor—we've been talking
about code—somebody acquires Cursor.

03:39:00.322 --> 03:39:01.632
if somebody acquires Cursor...

03:39:02.042 --> 03:39:05.782
- They're in such a good position
by having so much user data.

03:39:05.802 --> 03:39:09.761
And we talked about continual learning. They
had one of the most interesting sentences

03:39:09.802 --> 03:39:13.742
in a blog post, which is that they had
their new Composer model, which was

03:39:13.962 --> 03:39:17.931
a fine-tune of one of these large Mixture
of Expert models from China. You can

03:39:17.962 --> 03:39:22.452
know that by asking it or because the
model sometimes responds in Chinese—

03:39:22.452 --> 03:39:26.341
...which none of the American models do. And
they had a blog post where they're like,

03:39:26.362 --> 03:39:30.222
"We're updating the model weights every
90 minutes based on real-world feedback

03:39:30.261 --> 03:39:34.202
from people using it." Which is like
the closest thing to real-world RL

03:39:34.261 --> 03:39:36.581
happening on a model, and it's just
mentioned in one of their blog posts—

03:39:36.642 --> 03:39:36.952
- That's incredible.

03:39:36.952 --> 03:39:38.032
- which is super cool.

03:39:38.062 --> 03:39:41.982
- And by the way, I should say I use Composer
a lot because one of the benefits it

03:39:42.021 --> 03:39:43.282
has is that it's fast.

03:39:43.362 --> 03:39:45.261
- I need to try it 'cause
everybody says this.

03:39:45.302 --> 03:39:51.202
- And there'll be some IPOs potentially.
You think Anthropic, OpenAI, xAI.

03:39:51.222 --> 03:39:52.442
- They can all raise so much money

03:39:53.242 --> 03:39:57.042
so easily that they don't feel a need to.
So long as fundraising is easy, they're not

03:39:57.101 --> 03:40:00.152
going to IPO because public
markets apply pressure.

03:40:00.152 --> 03:40:03.622
I think we're seeing in China that the
ecosystem's a little different with both

03:40:03.661 --> 03:40:07.452
MiniMax and Z.ai applying for,

03:40:07.482 --> 03:40:11.362
filing IPO paperwork, which will be interesting
to see how the Chinese market reacts.

03:40:11.542 --> 03:40:15.521
I actually would guess that it's
going to be similarly hypey to

03:40:15.562 --> 03:40:19.521
the US, so long as all this is going and
not based on the reality that they're both

03:40:19.542 --> 03:40:23.462
losing a ton of money. I wish
more of the gigantic American

03:40:23.521 --> 03:40:27.501
AI startups were public because it would be very
interesting to see how they're spending money

03:40:27.542 --> 03:40:31.096
and have more insight. And
also just to give people

03:40:31.266 --> 03:40:34.826
access to investing in these, because
I think they're some of the most

03:40:35.446 --> 03:40:36.645
formidable companies—they're the

03:40:37.466 --> 03:40:41.366
companies of the era. And the
tradition is now for so many of the

03:40:41.426 --> 03:40:45.206
big startups in the US to not go public.
It's like we're still waiting for Stripe and

03:40:45.506 --> 03:40:48.746
the IPO, but Databricks definitely
didn't. They raised like a Series G

03:40:49.466 --> 03:40:53.006
or something. And I just feel
like it's kind of a weird

03:40:53.086 --> 03:40:55.136
equilibrium for the
market where it's like,

03:40:56.106 --> 03:40:58.486
I would like to see these
companies go public and

03:40:59.526 --> 03:41:01.706
evolve in that way that a company can.

03:41:01.726 --> 03:41:05.486
- Do you think 10 years from now some
of the frontier model companies are

03:41:05.546 --> 03:41:08.026
still around? Anthropic, OpenAI?

03:41:08.466 --> 03:41:12.366
- I definitely don't see it as a
winner-takes-all unless there truly

03:41:12.466 --> 03:41:16.166
is some algorithmic secret that
one of them finds that lets this

03:41:16.246 --> 03:41:20.166
flywheel. Because the development path
is so similar for all of them. Google

03:41:20.206 --> 03:41:24.126
and OpenAI have all the same
products, and then Anthropic's more

03:41:24.166 --> 03:41:28.046
focused, but when you talk to people it
sounds like they're solving a lot of the same

03:41:28.286 --> 03:41:31.686
problems. So I think... and there's
offerings that'll spread out. There's a lot

03:41:31.726 --> 03:41:36.366
of... it's a very big cake being made that
people are going to take money out of.

03:41:36.706 --> 03:41:43.676
- I don't want to trivialize it, but OpenAI
and Anthropic are primarily LLM service

03:41:43.706 --> 03:41:46.946
providers. And some of the
other companies like Google and

03:41:47.746 --> 03:41:51.196
xAI, linked to X, do other stuff

03:41:51.206 --> 03:41:55.266
too. And so it's very possible,
if AI becomes more commodified,

03:41:56.446 --> 03:42:00.626
that the companies just
providing LLMs will die.

03:42:00.726 --> 03:42:04.656
- I think the advantage they have is a
lot of users, and I think they will

03:42:04.706 --> 03:42:11.326
just pivot. Like Anthropic, I
think, pivoted. I don't think they

03:42:11.386 --> 03:42:15.356
originally planned to work on
code, but they found, "Okay, this

03:42:15.406 --> 03:42:19.346
is a nice niche, and now we are comfortable
and we push on this niche." I can see

03:42:19.386 --> 03:42:23.346
the same thing... Let's say
hypothetically, I'm not sure

03:42:23.386 --> 03:42:26.966
if it will be true, but let's say Google
takes all the market share of the general

03:42:27.026 --> 03:42:31.636
chatbot. Maybe OpenAI will then
focus on some other sub-topic.

03:42:31.686 --> 03:42:37.606
They have too many users to go
away in the foreseeable future.

03:42:37.666 --> 03:42:40.876
- I think Google is always ready to
say, "Hold my beer," with AI models.

03:42:40.906 --> 03:42:43.826
- I think the question is if
the companies can support the

03:42:43.846 --> 03:42:47.786
valuations. I see the AI companies being

03:42:47.846 --> 03:42:51.516
looked at in some ways like
AWS, Azure, and GCP are,

03:42:51.606 --> 03:42:55.526
all competing in the same space and all
very successful businesses. There's a

03:42:55.566 --> 03:42:59.506
chance that the API market is
so unprofitable that they go

03:42:59.566 --> 03:43:03.386
up and down the stack to products and hardware.
They have so much cash that they can build

03:43:03.426 --> 03:43:07.236
power plants and data centers, which is
a durable advantage now. But there's

03:43:07.306 --> 03:43:11.246
also a reasonable outcome that
these APIs are so valuable and

03:43:11.266 --> 03:43:15.146
so flexible for developers that
they become something like

03:43:15.206 --> 03:43:20.506
AWS. But AWS and Azure are also
going to have these APIs, so

03:43:21.506 --> 03:43:25.446
having five or six people competing in the
API market is hard. So maybe that's why

03:43:25.486 --> 03:43:27.086
they get squeezed out.

03:43:27.126 --> 03:43:31.926
- You mentioned "RIP Llama." Is
there a path to winning for Meta?

03:43:32.006 --> 03:43:38.726
- I think nobody knows. They're moving a
lot, so they're signing licensing deals

03:43:38.806 --> 03:43:42.666
with Black Forest Labs, which
is an image generation company,

03:43:42.706 --> 03:43:46.106
or Midjourney. So I think in some ways

03:43:46.146 --> 03:43:50.066
on the product and consumer-facing
AI front, it's too

03:43:50.106 --> 03:43:54.046
early to tell. I think they have
some people who are excellent

03:43:54.326 --> 03:43:58.306
and very motivated being close to
Zuckerberg. So I think there's still a

03:43:58.386 --> 03:44:03.895
story to unfold there. Llama is a
bit different, where Llama was the

03:44:04.846 --> 03:44:08.166
most focused expression of the
organization. And I don't see Llama

03:44:08.206 --> 03:44:12.166
being supported to that extent.
I think it was a very successful

03:44:12.286 --> 03:44:15.586
brand for them. So they still
might participate in the

03:44:15.646 --> 03:44:19.146
open ecosystem or continue the
Llama brand into a different

03:44:19.186 --> 03:44:21.036
service, because people
know what Llama is.

03:44:21.046 --> 03:44:22.966
- You think there's a Llama 5?

03:44:24.326 --> 03:44:26.486
- Not an open-weight one.

03:44:26.606 --> 03:44:34.406
- It's interesting. I think Llama was the
pioneering open-weight model. With Llama 1,

03:44:34.486 --> 03:44:38.386
2, and 3, there was a lot
of love. But I think then,

03:44:38.426 --> 03:44:42.266
hypothesizing or speculating,
I think the leaders

03:44:42.386 --> 03:44:46.126
at Meta, like the upper executives,
they... I think they got

03:44:46.206 --> 03:44:50.076
very excited about Llama because they saw how
popular it was in the community. And then

03:44:50.666 --> 03:44:54.486
I think the problem was trying to,
let's say, monetize the open—or not

03:44:54.506 --> 03:44:58.366
monetize the open source,
but use it to make a bigger

03:44:58.486 --> 03:45:05.046
splash. It felt almost forced, like
developing these very big Llama 4 models

03:45:05.106 --> 03:45:08.346
to be on top of the

03:45:08.406 --> 03:45:12.296
benchmarks. But I don't think the
goal of Llama models is to be on top

03:45:12.346 --> 03:45:16.206
of the benchmarks beating, let's say, ChatGPT
or other models. I think the goal was to

03:45:16.286 --> 03:45:20.266
have a model that people can use,
trust, modify, and understand.

03:45:20.306 --> 03:45:23.926
So that includes having smaller models.
They don't have to be the best models.

03:45:23.936 --> 03:45:27.796
And what happened was, these models
were, of course... the benchmarks

03:45:28.746 --> 03:45:32.386
suggested that they were better than
they were because they had specific

03:45:32.426 --> 03:45:36.326
models trained on preferences so that they
performed well on benchmarks. That's kind of,

03:45:36.346 --> 03:45:39.726
like, this overfitting thing to force
it to be the best. But then at the same

03:45:39.766 --> 03:45:43.686
time, they didn't do the small models
that people could use. And I think

03:45:43.766 --> 03:45:46.946
that no one could run these big models
then. And then there was kind of a

03:45:47.006 --> 03:45:50.416
weird thing. I think it's just
because people got too excited

03:45:50.466 --> 03:45:54.556
about headlines pushing the
frontier. I think that's it.

03:45:54.556 --> 03:45:56.726
- And too much on the benchmarking side.

03:45:56.806 --> 03:45:57.306
- It's too much work.

03:45:57.316 --> 03:46:00.946
- I think it imploded under internal

03:46:00.966 --> 03:46:04.786
political fighting and misaligned
incentives. The researchers want to

03:46:04.826 --> 03:46:07.876
build the best models, but
there's a layer of organization—

03:46:07.876 --> 03:46:11.686
...and management that is trying to demonstrate
that they do these things. And then

03:46:11.726 --> 03:46:19.526
there are rumors about how, for example,
some horrible technical decision was made.

03:46:19.586 --> 03:46:24.326
It just seems like it got so bad
that it all just crashed out.

03:46:24.826 --> 03:46:28.086
- Yeah, but we should also
give huge props to Mark

03:46:28.126 --> 03:46:31.982
Zuckerberg. I think it comes
from Mark, actually, from

03:46:32.182 --> 03:46:35.222
Mark Zuckerberg, from the top of the
leadership, saying open source is

03:46:35.262 --> 03:46:39.101
important. The fact that
that leadership exists

03:46:39.222 --> 03:46:42.902
means there could be a Llama 5,
where they learn the lessons from

03:46:42.962 --> 03:46:47.122
benchmarking and say, "We're
going to be GPT-OSS—"

03:46:47.282 --> 03:46:51.552
"...and provide a really awesome
library of open source."

03:46:51.642 --> 03:46:55.342
- What people say is that there's
a debate between Mark and

03:46:55.422 --> 03:46:59.042
Alexandr Wang, who is very bright,
but much more against open

03:46:59.101 --> 03:47:02.942
source. And to the extent that he has
a lot of influence over the AI org, it

03:47:02.962 --> 03:47:06.822
seems much less likely, because it
seems like Mark brought him in for a

03:47:06.962 --> 03:47:10.862
fresh leadership eye in directing AI. And

03:47:10.922 --> 03:47:14.802
if being open or closed is no longer
the defining nature of the model, I

03:47:14.842 --> 03:47:18.682
don't expect that to be a defining
argument between Mark and

03:47:18.782 --> 03:47:22.582
Alex. They're both very bright,
but I just have a hard time

03:47:23.202 --> 03:47:26.642
understanding all of it because
Mark wrote this piece in July of

03:47:27.822 --> 03:47:31.782
2024, which was probably the best

03:47:31.822 --> 03:47:35.422
blog post at the time, saying
"The Case for Open Source AI."

03:47:36.142 --> 03:47:40.021
And then July 2025 came around and it was,
"We're reevaluating our relationship with

03:47:40.142 --> 03:47:42.771
open source." So it's just kind of...

03:47:42.782 --> 03:47:46.592
- But I think also the problem...
Not the problem, but I think,

03:47:46.622 --> 03:47:50.392
well, we may have been a bit too
harsh, and that caused some of that.

03:47:50.442 --> 03:47:54.172
Because I mean, we as open source
developers or the community...

03:47:54.182 --> 03:47:58.142
Even though the model was
maybe not what everyone hoped

03:47:58.202 --> 03:48:01.882
for, it got a lot of backlash.
And I think that was unfortunate

03:48:01.962 --> 03:48:05.582
because I can see that as a
company, they were hoping for

03:48:05.742 --> 03:48:09.662
positive headlines. And
instead of just getting

03:48:09.762 --> 03:48:13.482
no headlines or positive headlines,
in turn they got negative

03:48:13.492 --> 03:48:17.382
headlines. And then it kind of
reflected bad on the company.

03:48:17.742 --> 03:48:21.101
I think that is also something
where it's maybe a spite reaction,

03:48:21.122 --> 03:48:25.042
almost like, "Okay, we tried to
do something nice, we tried to

03:48:25.142 --> 03:48:28.922
give you something cool, like an
open source model, and now you are

03:48:28.962 --> 03:48:32.942
kind of being negative about
us, even for the company."

03:48:32.982 --> 03:48:36.782
So in that sense, it looks like, "Well,
maybe then we'll change our mind."

03:48:36.822 --> 03:48:38.682
I guess. I don't know.

03:48:38.782 --> 03:48:43.882
- Yeah, that's where the
dynamics of discourse on

03:48:44.062 --> 03:48:48.002
X can lead us, as a community, astray.

03:48:48.012 --> 03:48:51.722
Because sometimes it feels random. People
pick the thing they like and don't

03:48:51.762 --> 03:48:59.062
like. I mean, you can see the same thing
with Grok 4.1 and Grok Code Fast 1.0.

03:48:59.101 --> 03:49:08.742
I don't think, vibe-wise, people love it
publicly. But a lot of people use it.

03:49:09.702 --> 03:49:12.942
So if you look to Reddit and
X, they don't really give it

03:49:13.062 --> 03:49:17.662
praise from the programming
community, but they use it.

03:49:17.682 --> 03:49:21.562
And the same thing with probably Llama.
I don't understand the dynamics of

03:49:21.662 --> 03:49:24.442
either positive hype or negative
hype. I don't understand it.

03:49:25.042 --> 03:49:28.742
- I mean, one of the stories of 2025
is the US filling the gap of Llama,

03:49:29.402 --> 03:49:33.941
which is the rise of these Chinese
open-weight models, models-

03:49:34.012 --> 03:49:37.952
to the point where that was the single
issue I've spent a lot of energy on lately,

03:49:37.982 --> 03:49:41.751
trying to do policy work to
get the US to invest in this.

03:49:41.882 --> 03:49:43.382
- So just tell me the story of ADAM.

03:49:43.482 --> 03:49:47.101
- The ADAM Project started as me
calling it the American DeepSeek

03:49:47.142 --> 03:49:51.092
Project, which doesn't really work for
DC audiences, but it's the story of

03:49:51.122 --> 03:49:54.771
the most impactful thing I can
do with my career, which is

03:49:54.822 --> 03:49:58.712
that these Chinese open-weight models
are cultivating a lot of power,

03:49:58.742 --> 03:50:02.342
and there is a lot of demand for
building on these open models,

03:50:02.382 --> 03:50:06.122
especially in enterprises in the US that
are very cagey about Chinese models.

03:50:06.222 --> 03:50:10.062
- The ADAM Project, American Truly

03:50:10.222 --> 03:50:14.042
Open Models, is a US-based initiative
to build and host high-quality,

03:50:14.122 --> 03:50:17.442
genuinely open-weight AI models
and supporting infrastructure

03:50:17.582 --> 03:50:21.271
explicitly aimed at competing
with and catching up to

03:50:21.322 --> 03:50:25.562
China's rapidly advancing
open-source AI ecosystem.

03:50:25.642 --> 03:50:29.601
- I think the one-sentence summary
would be that... or two sentences.

03:50:29.642 --> 03:50:33.182
One is a proposition that open models
are going to be an engine for AI

03:50:33.282 --> 03:50:37.182
research because that is what people
start with; therefore, it's important to

03:50:37.242 --> 03:50:40.662
own them. And the second
one is, therefore, the US

03:50:41.342 --> 03:50:45.082
should be building the best models so
that the best research happens in the

03:50:45.122 --> 03:50:49.101
US, and those US companies
take the value from being the

03:50:49.161 --> 03:50:52.862
home of where AI research is
happening. And without more

03:50:52.902 --> 03:50:56.842
investment in open models—we have plots
on the website where it's like, "Qwen,

03:50:56.882 --> 03:51:00.542
Qwen, Qwen, Qwen"—it's
all these models that are

03:51:00.582 --> 03:51:04.482
excellent from these Chinese companies
that are cultivating influence

03:51:04.862 --> 03:51:08.802
internationally. I think the US is

03:51:08.922 --> 03:51:12.822
spending way more on AI, and the
ability to create open models that

03:51:12.842 --> 03:51:16.622
are a generation beyond what
the cutting edge of closed labs

03:51:16.682 --> 03:51:20.542
costs roughly $100 million,
which is a lot of money, but

03:51:20.582 --> 03:51:24.142
not a lot of money to these
companies. Therefore, we need a

03:51:24.162 --> 03:51:27.682
centralizing force of people who
want to do this. And I think

03:51:29.162 --> 03:51:32.922
we got engagement from people pretty
much across the full stack, whether

03:51:32.982 --> 03:51:33.922
it's policy.

03:51:33.992 --> 03:51:36.702
- So there has been support
from the administration?

03:51:36.782 --> 03:51:39.642
- I don't think anyone
technically in government has

03:51:41.002 --> 03:51:44.882
signed it publicly, but I know
people that have worked in AI

03:51:44.942 --> 03:51:48.202
policy, in both the Biden and Trump
administrations, are very supportive

03:51:48.242 --> 03:51:52.110
of promoting open-source models
in the US. I think, for example,

03:51:52.162 --> 03:51:56.021
AI2 got a grant from the NSF
for $100 million over four

03:51:56.082 --> 03:52:00.042
years, which is the biggest CS grant the

03:52:00.101 --> 03:52:05.502
NSF has ever awarded, and it's for AI2
to attempt this. It's a starting point.

03:52:05.542 --> 03:52:09.351
But the best thing happens when there are
multiple organizations building models,

03:52:09.422 --> 03:52:13.362
because they can cross-pollinate
ideas and build this ecosystem.

03:52:13.422 --> 03:52:17.342
I don't think it works if it's
just Llama releasing models,

03:52:17.442 --> 03:52:21.402
because Llama could go away.
The same thing applies for AI2;

03:52:21.442 --> 03:52:28.582
I can't be the only one building models.
It becomes a lot of time spent on

03:52:29.382 --> 03:52:33.242
talking to people, whether in
policy... I know NVIDIA is

03:52:33.282 --> 03:52:37.262
very excited about this. I think Jensen
Huang has been talking about the urgency

03:52:37.342 --> 03:52:41.222
for this, and they've done a
lot more in 2025, where the

03:52:41.262 --> 03:52:44.966
Nemotron models are more of a focus.
They've started releasing some

03:52:45.046 --> 03:52:48.905
data along with NVIDIA's
open models, and very few

03:52:48.946 --> 03:52:52.836
companies do this, especially
of NVIDIA's size, so there

03:52:52.886 --> 03:52:56.565
are signs of progress. We hear about
Reflection AI, where they say their

03:52:57.606 --> 03:53:01.525
two billion dollar fundraise is dedicated
to building US open models, and I feel

03:53:01.565 --> 03:53:05.405
and their announcement tweet
reads like a blog post, right?

03:53:06.186 --> 03:53:11.466
I think that cultural tide is
starting to turn. In July,

03:53:12.586 --> 03:53:16.436
four or five DeepSeek-caliber
Chinese open-weight models and

03:53:16.506 --> 03:53:20.405
and zero from the US. That's
the moment where I realized,

03:53:20.446 --> 03:53:24.126
like, "Oh, I guess I have to spend energy on
this because nobody else is gonna do it."

03:53:24.206 --> 03:53:28.106
So it takes a lot of people contributing
together, and I don't say that,

03:53:28.146 --> 03:53:31.886
the Adam Project isn't the thing that's
helping to move the ecosystem, but it's

03:53:31.946 --> 03:53:35.586
people like me doing this sort
of thing to get the word out.

03:53:35.666 --> 03:53:39.516
- Do you like the 2025 America's
AI Action Plan? That

03:53:39.546 --> 03:53:43.446
includes open source stuff. The
White House AI Action Plan includes

03:53:43.466 --> 03:53:47.146
a dedicated section titled "Encourage
Open-Source and Open-Weight

03:53:47.206 --> 03:53:51.146
AI," defining such models and
arguing they have unique value for

03:53:51.186 --> 03:53:52.426
innovation and startups.

03:53:52.485 --> 03:53:55.846
- Yeah. I mean, the AI
Action Plan is a plan,

03:53:55.905 --> 03:53:59.636
but largely, I think it's maybe the most

03:53:59.666 --> 03:54:03.496
coherent policy document that has come
out of the administration, and I hope

03:54:04.065 --> 03:54:08.006
that it largely succeeds. I know people
that have worked on the AI Action Plan and

03:54:08.046 --> 03:54:11.966
the challenges of taking policy and
making it real. I have no idea how

03:54:11.985 --> 03:54:15.796
to do this as an AI researcher,
but largely a lot of things in

03:54:15.846 --> 03:54:19.576
that were very real, and there's
a huge build-out of AI in the

03:54:19.586 --> 03:54:23.565
country. There are a lot of issues that
people are hearing about, from water use to

03:54:23.586 --> 03:54:27.526
whatever, and we should be able to
build things in this country, but also,

03:54:27.546 --> 03:54:31.326
we need to not ruin places in
our country in the process of

03:54:31.346 --> 03:54:35.266
building it, and it's worthwhile
to spend energy on. I

03:54:35.286 --> 03:54:38.846
think that's a role the federal
government plays. They set the agenda.

03:54:38.866 --> 03:54:42.505
And with AI, setting the agenda
that open-weight should be a

03:54:42.586 --> 03:54:46.426
first consideration is a large part of

03:54:46.466 --> 03:54:48.946
what they can do and then
people think about it.

03:54:49.006 --> 03:54:52.926
- Also, for education and talent
for these companies, it's very

03:54:52.946 --> 03:54:55.766
important because otherwise,
if there are only closed

03:54:55.886 --> 03:54:59.766
models, how do you get
the next generation of

03:54:59.806 --> 03:55:02.916
people contributing at some point?
Because otherwise, you will

03:55:02.946 --> 03:55:06.485
point only be able to learn after you

03:55:06.905 --> 03:55:10.686
joined a company. But at
that point, how do you hire

03:55:10.866 --> 03:55:14.246
talented people? How do you identify
talented people? I think open source

03:55:14.326 --> 03:55:18.006
is essential for a lot of
things, but also even just for

03:55:18.065 --> 03:55:21.655
educating the population and
training the next generation of

03:55:21.706 --> 03:55:23.996
researchers. It's the
way, or the only way.

03:55:24.026 --> 03:55:27.766
- The way that I could've gotten this
to go more viral was to tell a

03:55:27.866 --> 03:55:31.806
story of Chinese AI integrating
with an authoritarian state,

03:55:31.846 --> 03:55:35.766
being ASI and taking over the world, and therefore
we need our own American models. But it's very

03:55:35.786 --> 03:55:39.666
intentional why I talk about
innovation and science in the US

03:55:39.746 --> 03:55:43.595
because I think it's both more
realistic as an outcome, but also

03:55:43.626 --> 03:55:47.786
it's a world that I
would like to manifest.

03:55:47.866 --> 03:55:51.846
- I would say, though, also
even any open-weight

03:55:51.905 --> 03:55:55.006
model, I do think, is a valuable model.

03:55:55.046 --> 03:55:59.405
- Yeah. And my argument is that we should be
in a leading position. But I think it's

03:56:00.686 --> 03:56:04.606
worth saying it simply because there
are still voices in the AI ecosystem

03:56:04.666 --> 03:56:09.546
that say we should consider banning the
release of open models due to safety risks.

03:56:09.565 --> 03:56:13.326
And I think it's worth adding
that, effectively, that's

03:56:13.366 --> 03:56:17.246
impossible without making the US have
its own great firewall, which is

03:56:17.306 --> 03:56:20.826
also known to not work that well because

03:56:21.286 --> 03:56:24.926
the cost for training these models, whether
it's one to a hundred million dollars, is

03:56:24.935 --> 03:56:28.896
attainable to a huge amount of people

03:56:28.926 --> 03:56:32.866
in the world that want to have influence, so
these models will be trained all over the

03:56:32.886 --> 03:56:37.466
world. And we want the models,
especially when, like,

03:56:38.306 --> 03:56:42.126
I mean, there are safety concerns, but we
want this information and tools to flow

03:56:42.146 --> 03:56:45.946
freely across the world and into the
US so that people can use them and

03:56:45.985 --> 03:56:50.276
learn from them. Stopping that would be
such a restructuring of our internet

03:56:50.276 --> 03:56:51.565
that it seems impossible.

03:56:51.606 --> 03:56:55.386
- Do you think maybe in that case the
big open-weight models from China are

03:56:55.446 --> 03:56:59.326
actually a good thing in a sense, like,
for the US companies? Because maybe

03:56:59.346 --> 03:57:03.246
the US companies you mentioned earlier
are usually one generation behind

03:57:03.386 --> 03:57:07.266
in terms of what they release open source
versus what they are using? For example,

03:57:07.346 --> 03:57:10.746
gpt-oss might not be the cutting-edge
model. Gemini 3 might not

03:57:10.786 --> 03:57:14.746
be, but they do that because they know this
is safe to release. But then when they

03:57:14.806 --> 03:57:18.746
see, these companies see, for
example, there is DeepSeek-V3.2,

03:57:18.786 --> 03:57:22.586
which is really awesome, and
it gets used and there is no

03:57:22.626 --> 03:57:26.606
backlash, there is no security risk, that
could then, again, encourage them to

03:57:26.626 --> 03:57:30.046
release better models. Maybe that, in
a sense, is a very positive thing.

03:57:30.106 --> 03:57:33.286
- A hundred percent. These Chinese companies
have set things into motion that I

03:57:33.326 --> 03:57:38.146
think would potentially not have happened
if they were not all releasing models.

03:57:38.186 --> 03:57:44.416
So I think it was like I'm almost sure
that those discussions have been had

03:57:44.416 --> 03:57:45.446
by leadership.

03:57:45.485 --> 03:57:49.446
- Is there a possible future where
the dominant AI models in the

03:57:49.485 --> 03:57:50.926
world are all open source?

03:57:50.966 --> 03:57:54.846
- Depends on the trajectory of progress that
you predict. If you think saturation in

03:57:54.926 --> 03:57:58.596
progress is coming within a
few years, so essentially,

03:57:58.646 --> 03:58:02.466
within the time where financial support
is still very good, then open models

03:58:02.526 --> 03:58:06.506
will be so optimized and so much cheaper
to run that they'll win out. This

03:58:06.546 --> 03:58:10.426
goes back to open source ideas
where so many more people will be

03:58:10.506 --> 03:58:14.046
putting money into optimizing
the serving of these

03:58:14.126 --> 03:58:17.836
open-weight common architectures
that they will become standards, and

03:58:17.886 --> 03:58:21.276
then you could have chips dedicated to
them, and it'll be way cheaper than

03:58:21.306 --> 03:58:25.286
the offerings from these closed
companies that are custom.

03:58:25.306 --> 03:58:29.276
- We should say that the AI27
report kinda predicts one

03:58:29.326 --> 03:58:32.496
of the things it does from a narrative
perspective is that there will be a lot of

03:58:32.526 --> 03:58:35.426
centralization. As the AI
systems get smarter and

03:58:35.506 --> 03:58:39.356
smarter, national security
concerns will arise, and

03:58:39.446 --> 03:58:43.366
you'll centralize the labs, and they'll
become super secretive, and there'll

03:58:43.405 --> 03:58:44.726
be this whole race

03:58:45.062 --> 03:58:48.652
- ...from a military perspective of how
do you... between China and the US.

03:58:48.722 --> 03:58:52.382
And so all of these fun
conversations we're having about

03:58:52.542 --> 03:58:56.402
LLMs... the generals and the soldiers will

03:58:56.462 --> 03:59:00.181
come into the room and be like, "All
right. We're now in the Manhattan

03:59:00.282 --> 03:59:02.862
Project stage of this whole thing."

03:59:02.942 --> 03:59:06.302
- I think in 2025, '26, '27, I don't think

03:59:06.761 --> 03:59:10.622
something like that is even remotely
possible. You can make the same argument

03:59:10.662 --> 03:59:14.642
for computers, right? You can say,
"Computers are capable and we don't want

03:59:14.662 --> 03:59:21.302
the general public to get them." Or chips,
even AI chips, but you see how Huawei

03:59:21.341 --> 03:59:25.162
makes chips now. It took
a few years, but... and I

03:59:25.181 --> 03:59:29.082
don't think there is a way you
can contain knowledge like that.

03:59:29.122 --> 03:59:32.882
I think in this day and age, it is

03:59:33.021 --> 03:59:37.722
impossible, like the internet. I
don't think this is a possibility.

03:59:37.802 --> 03:59:41.502
- On the Manhattan Project
thing, I think that a

03:59:41.542 --> 03:59:45.502
Manhattan Project-like thing for open
models would be pretty reasonable, because

03:59:45.521 --> 03:59:48.002
it wouldn't cost that much.
But I think that will come.

03:59:48.822 --> 03:59:52.782
It seems like culturally, the companies
are changing. But I agree with Sebastian

03:59:52.792 --> 03:59:58.722
on all of that. I don't see it
happening nor being helpful.

03:59:58.761 --> 04:00:02.412
- Yeah. The motivating force
behind the Manhattan Project was

04:00:02.421 --> 04:00:08.002
civilizational risk. It's harder to
motivate that for open-source models.

04:00:08.042 --> 04:00:10.382
- There's no civilizational risk.

04:00:10.502 --> 04:00:14.382
- On the hardware side,
we mentioned NVIDIA a

04:00:14.421 --> 04:00:18.802
bunch of times. Do you think Jensen
and NVIDIA will keep winning?

04:00:18.902 --> 04:00:22.812
- I think they have to iterate
and manufacture a lot.

04:00:22.862 --> 04:00:26.722
And I think they probably...
what they're doing,

04:00:26.782 --> 04:00:30.042
they do innovate, but I think there's

04:00:30.142 --> 04:00:34.082
always the chance that someone
does something fundamentally

04:00:34.091 --> 04:00:37.982
different, gets very lucky, and
then does something. But the

04:00:38.021 --> 04:00:41.982
problem is adoption. The moat of NVIDIA

04:00:42.021 --> 04:00:45.802
is probably not just the GPU. It's
more like the CUDA ecosystem, and that

04:00:45.862 --> 04:00:49.752
has evolved over two decades.
Even back when I was a

04:00:49.802 --> 04:00:53.582
grad student, I was in a lab
doing biophysical simulations,

04:00:53.601 --> 04:00:57.222
molecular dynamics, and we had a
Tesla GPU back then just for the

04:00:57.242 --> 04:01:01.062
computations. It was about
15 years ago now. And

04:01:01.181 --> 04:01:05.122
they built this up for a long time,
and that's the moat, I think.

04:01:05.142 --> 04:01:09.101
It's not the chip itself,
although they have the

04:01:09.142 --> 04:01:12.942
money to iterate, build, and
scale. But then it's really

04:01:13.142 --> 04:01:17.071
about compatibility. If you're
at that scale, why would

04:01:17.142 --> 04:01:19.062
you go with something risky where

04:01:19.071 --> 04:01:21.431
there are only a few chips
they can make per year?

04:01:21.431 --> 04:01:25.021
You go with the big one. But
then I do think with LLMs

04:01:25.341 --> 04:01:30.132
now, it will be easier to
design something like CUDA.

04:01:30.132 --> 04:01:33.882
It took 15 years because it was hard,
but now that we have LLMs, we can

04:01:33.942 --> 04:01:35.702
maybe replicate CUDA.

04:01:35.742 --> 04:01:39.902
- And I wonder if there will be a
separation of training and inference

04:01:39.962 --> 04:01:47.042
compute as we stabilize, and more
compute is needed for inference.

04:01:47.082 --> 04:01:51.042
- That's supposed to be the point of
the Groq acquisition. And that's why

04:01:51.261 --> 04:01:52.571
part of what Vera Rubin is-

04:01:52.571 --> 04:01:55.972
where they have a new chip with no
high-bandwidth memory, which is one of the-

04:01:55.982 --> 04:01:59.482
or very little, which is one of
the most expensive pieces. It's

04:01:59.521 --> 04:02:03.261
designed for pre-fill, which
is the part of inference

04:02:03.322 --> 04:02:07.231
where you essentially do a lot of matrix
multiplications. And then you only need

04:02:07.242 --> 04:02:10.902
the memory when you're doing this autoregressive
generation, and you have the KV cache

04:02:11.142 --> 04:02:14.982
swaps. So they have this new GPU
that's designed for that specific

04:02:15.082 --> 04:02:19.002
use case, and then the
cost of ownership per FLOP

04:02:19.021 --> 04:02:22.122
or whatever is actually way
lower. But I think that

04:02:22.982 --> 04:02:26.862
NVIDIA's fate lies in the diffusion
of AI still. Their biggest clients

04:02:26.902 --> 04:02:30.832
are still these hyperscale
companies. Like, Google obviously

04:02:30.902 --> 04:02:34.442
can make TPUs. Amazon is making Trainium.

04:02:34.452 --> 04:02:40.351
Microsoft will try to do its own things.
And so long as the pace of AI progress is

04:02:40.421 --> 04:02:44.341
high, NVIDIA's platform is the most
flexible and people will want that. But if

04:02:44.382 --> 04:02:49.782
there's stagnation, then creating bespoke
chips, there's more time to do it.

04:02:50.181 --> 04:02:54.142
- It's interesting that NVIDIA
is quite active in trying to

04:02:54.162 --> 04:02:55.822
develop all kinds of different products.

04:02:55.862 --> 04:03:01.601
- They try to create areas of commercial
value that will use a lot of GPUs.

04:03:01.622 --> 04:03:05.282
- Mm-hmm. But they keep innovating
and they're doing a lot of

04:03:05.302 --> 04:03:06.851
incredible research, so...

04:03:06.902 --> 04:03:10.021
- Everyone says the company's super
oriented around Jensen and how

04:03:11.382 --> 04:03:15.062
operationally plugged in he is. And
it sounds so unlike many other big

04:03:15.101 --> 04:03:18.992
companies that I've heard about. And so
long as that's the culture, I think that

04:03:19.042 --> 04:03:22.761
we can expect that to keep progress
happening. And it's like he's still in

04:03:22.822 --> 04:03:26.421
the Steve Jobs era of Apple.
So long as that is how it

04:03:26.482 --> 04:03:30.382
operates, I'm pretty optimistic for their

04:03:31.021 --> 04:03:34.982
situation because it's like, it is
their top-order problem, and I don't

04:03:35.021 --> 04:03:38.782
know if making these chips for the
whole ecosystem is the top goal of all

04:03:38.921 --> 04:03:43.502
these other companies. They'll do a good
job, but it might not be as good of a job.

04:03:43.582 --> 04:03:47.552
- Since you mentioned Jensen,
I've been reading a lot about

04:03:47.582 --> 04:03:51.271
history and about singular figures in
history. What do you guys think about the

04:03:51.322 --> 04:03:54.782
single man/woman view of
history? How important are

04:03:54.841 --> 04:03:58.502
individuals for steering the direction
of history in the tech sector?

04:03:58.542 --> 04:04:02.332
So, you know, what's NVIDIA
without Jensen? You mentioned

04:04:02.421 --> 04:04:06.552
Steve Jobs. What's Apple
without Steve Jobs? What's xAI

04:04:07.482 --> 04:04:11.722
without Elon or DeepMind without Demis?

04:04:11.761 --> 04:04:16.442
- People make things earlier and
faster, whereas scientifically,

04:04:17.462 --> 04:04:21.382
many great scientists credit being in the
right place at the right time and still making

04:04:21.402 --> 04:04:24.982
the innovation, where eventually
someone else will still have the

04:04:25.062 --> 04:04:32.742
idea. So I think that in that way, Jensen
is helping manifest this GPU revolution

04:04:33.442 --> 04:04:37.302
much faster and much more
focused than it would happen

04:04:37.322 --> 04:04:41.242
without having a person there. And this is
making the whole AI build-out faster. But I

04:04:41.302 --> 04:04:45.222
do still think that eventually,
something like ChatGPT would have

04:04:45.261 --> 04:04:48.582
happened and a build-out like this would have
happened, but it probably would not have

04:04:48.642 --> 04:04:55.130
been as fast. I think that's the
sort of flavor that is applied.

04:04:55.150 --> 04:04:58.430
- These individual people, there are people
who are placing bets on something.

04:04:58.470 --> 04:05:02.050
Some get lucky, some don't. But if you don't
have these people at the helm, it would be more

04:05:02.330 --> 04:05:05.990
diffused. It's almost like investing
in an ETF versus individual

04:05:06.090 --> 04:05:10.070
stocks. Individual stocks
might go up or down more

04:05:10.109 --> 04:05:13.990
heavily than an ETF, which is more balanced.
It will eventually go up over time. We'll

04:05:14.029 --> 04:05:17.890
get there. But it's just
like, you know, the focus I

04:05:17.930 --> 04:05:19.750
think is the thing. Passion and focus.

04:05:19.789 --> 04:05:23.769
- Isn't there a real case to be made
that without Jensen, there's not a

04:05:23.810 --> 04:05:26.710
reinvigoration of the
deep learning revolution?

04:05:26.750 --> 04:05:30.400
- It could've been 20 years
later, is what I would say.

04:05:30.410 --> 04:05:35.529
Or like another AI winter could
have come if GPUs weren't around.

04:05:35.570 --> 04:05:38.810
- That could change history completely
because you could think of all the other

04:05:39.150 --> 04:05:40.039
technologies that

04:05:40.910 --> 04:05:44.560
could've come in the meantime, and the
focus of human civilization would get...

04:05:44.590 --> 04:05:48.109
Silicon Valley would be
captured by different hype.

04:05:48.150 --> 04:05:52.010
- But I do think there's certainly
an aspect where it was all

04:05:52.029 --> 04:05:55.810
planned, the GPU trajectory. But on the
other hand, it's also a lot of lucky

04:05:55.869 --> 04:05:59.750
coincidences or good
intuition. Like the investment

04:05:59.869 --> 04:06:03.789
into, let's say, biophysical
simulations. I mean, I think it

04:06:03.810 --> 04:06:07.289
started with video games and then it just
happened to be good at linear algebra

04:06:07.750 --> 04:06:11.310
because video games require a lot of linear
algebra. And then you have the biophysical

04:06:11.390 --> 04:06:15.310
simulations. But still, I
don't think the master plan

04:06:15.349 --> 04:06:19.330
was AI. I think it happened to be Alex

04:06:19.349 --> 04:06:23.330
Krizhevsky. So someone took
these GPUs and said, "Hey, let's

04:06:23.390 --> 04:06:26.550
try to train a neural network on that."
It happened to work really well, and

04:06:26.560 --> 04:06:30.449
I think it only happened because
you could purchase those GPUs.

04:06:30.510 --> 04:06:33.880
- Gaming would've created a
demand for faster processors if

04:06:33.890 --> 04:06:37.029
NVIDIA had gone out of
business in the early days.

04:06:37.050 --> 04:06:38.369
That's what I would think. I think that

04:06:39.890 --> 04:06:46.019
the GPUs would've been different,
but I think GPUs would still exist

04:06:46.090 --> 04:06:49.869
at the time of AlexNet and at the time
of the Transformer. It was just hard to

04:06:49.890 --> 04:06:53.849
know if it would be one company
as successful or multiple smaller

04:06:53.949 --> 04:06:57.630
companies with worse chips.
But I don't think that's a

04:06:58.750 --> 04:07:01.470
100-year delay. It might
be a decade delay.

04:07:01.510 --> 04:07:05.490
- Well, it could be one, two, three,
four, five-decade delay. I just can't

04:07:05.670 --> 04:07:08.659
see Intel or AMD doing what NVIDIA did.

04:07:08.689 --> 04:07:11.490
- I don't think it would be
a company that exists.

04:07:11.630 --> 04:07:13.670
I think it would be a different
company that would rise.

04:07:13.689 --> 04:07:15.260
- Like Silicon Graphics or something.

04:07:15.670 --> 04:07:18.670
- So yeah, some company that
has died would have done it.

04:07:19.310 --> 04:07:22.630
- But just looking at it,
it seems like these

04:07:22.750 --> 04:07:26.269
singular figures, these
leaders, have a huge impact

04:07:27.109 --> 04:07:31.090
on the trajectory of the world. Obviously,
there are incredible teams behind them.

04:07:31.460 --> 04:07:37.580
But, you know, having that kind of
very singular, almost dogmatic focus-

04:07:37.650 --> 04:07:40.730
-is necessary to make progress.

04:07:40.769 --> 04:07:44.670
- Yeah, I mean, even with GPT, it wouldn't
exist if there wasn't a person,

04:07:44.730 --> 04:07:47.349
Ilya, who pushed for this scaling, right?

04:07:47.369 --> 04:07:50.240
- Yeah, Dario Amodei was also
deeply involved in that.

04:07:50.250 --> 04:07:54.170
If you read some of the histories from
OpenAI, it seems wild thinking about

04:07:54.269 --> 04:07:57.910
how early these people were like, "We need
to hook up 10,000 GPUs and take all of

04:07:57.949 --> 04:08:01.849
OpenAI's compute and train one model."
There were a lot of people who didn't want

04:08:01.869 --> 04:08:02.449
to do that.

04:08:02.470 --> 04:08:06.410
- Which is an insane thing to
believe. To believe in scaling

04:08:06.550 --> 04:08:09.609
before scaling has any
indication that it's going to

04:08:09.670 --> 04:08:17.510
materialize. Again, singular figures.
Speaking of which, 100 years from now, this

04:08:17.590 --> 04:08:21.189
is presumably post-singularity,
whatever singularity is.

04:08:21.349 --> 04:08:24.769
When historians look back
at our time now, what

04:08:24.810 --> 04:08:28.180
technological breakthroughs
would they really

04:08:28.230 --> 04:08:32.070
emphasize as the breakthroughs
that led to the singularity?

04:08:32.109 --> 04:08:36.710
So far we have Turing to today, 80 years.

04:08:36.810 --> 04:08:40.410
- I think it would still be computing,
like the umbrella term "computing."

04:08:40.449 --> 04:08:44.269
I don't necessarily think that in 100

04:08:44.310 --> 04:08:47.930
or 200 years it would be AI.
It could still very well be

04:08:47.970 --> 04:08:51.920
computers. We are now taking
better advantage of them, but

04:08:51.949 --> 04:08:53.650
the fact of computing remains.

04:08:53.710 --> 04:08:57.390
- It's basically a Moore's
Law discussion. Even the

04:08:57.430 --> 04:09:01.310
details of CUDA and GPUs
won't even be remembered, nor

04:09:01.349 --> 04:09:07.189
will all this software turmoil.
It'll just be, obviously, compute.

04:09:07.250 --> 04:09:11.230
- I generally agree, but is
the connectivity of the

04:09:11.269 --> 04:09:17.730
internet and compute able to be
merged? Or is it both of them?

04:09:17.810 --> 04:09:21.760
- I think the internet will probably
be related to communication.

04:09:21.849 --> 04:09:25.430
It could be a phone, the
internet, or satellites.

04:09:25.510 --> 04:09:29.300
Compute is more like the
scaling aspect of it.

04:09:29.310 --> 04:09:32.109
- It's possible that the internet
is completely forgotten-

04:09:32.170 --> 04:09:37.609
-that the internet is wrapped into phone
networks, like communication networks.

04:09:38.529 --> 04:09:42.430
This is just another manifestation
of that, and the real breakthrough

04:09:42.490 --> 04:09:46.570
comes from increased compute, or
Moore's Law, broadly defined.

04:09:46.609 --> 04:09:50.470
- Well, I think the connection of
people is very fundamental to it.

04:09:50.529 --> 04:09:54.519
it's like, you can talk to
anyone. You want to find the

04:09:54.529 --> 04:09:58.490
best person in the world for something, they are
somewhere in the world. And being able to have

04:09:58.550 --> 04:10:02.420
that flow of information—the
AIs will also rely on this.

04:10:02.590 --> 04:10:06.490
I've been fixating on when I
said the dream was dead about

04:10:06.529 --> 04:10:10.400
the one central model. The thing that is
evolving is people having many agents

04:10:10.490 --> 04:10:14.250
for different tasks. People already
started doing this with different clouds.

04:10:14.310 --> 04:10:18.170
It's described as many
AGIs in the data center

04:10:18.210 --> 04:10:22.090
where each one manages and they
talk to each other. And that is

04:10:22.150 --> 04:10:25.949
reliant on networking and the
free flow of information.

04:10:26.029 --> 04:10:29.789
on top of compute. But
networking, especially with

04:10:29.810 --> 04:10:33.570
GPUs, is such a part of
scaling of compute. The

04:10:33.650 --> 04:10:36.500
GPUs and the data centers
need to talk to each other.

04:10:36.510 --> 04:10:40.380
- Anything about neural networks will
be remembered? Like, do you think

04:10:40.390 --> 04:10:44.108
there's something very specific and
singular to the fact that it's neural

04:10:44.130 --> 04:10:47.650
networks that's seen as a breakthrough,
like a genius, that you're

04:10:47.689 --> 04:10:51.590
basically replicating, in a very
crude way, the human mind? The

04:10:51.650 --> 04:10:54.109
structure of the human
brain, the human mind?

04:10:54.506 --> 04:10:58.436
- I think without the human mind,
we probably wouldn't have neural

04:10:58.485 --> 04:11:02.086
networks, because it just was an
inspiration for that. But on the

04:11:02.186 --> 04:11:06.086
other end, I think it's just so,
so different. I mean, it's digital

04:11:06.166 --> 04:11:10.006
versus biological, that I do
think it will probably be more

04:11:10.484 --> 04:11:11.706
grouped as an algorithm.

04:11:11.746 --> 04:11:15.426
- That's massively parallelizable...
...On this particular kind of compute?

04:11:15.606 --> 04:11:19.286
- It could have been like genetic
computing; genetic algorithms just

04:11:19.305 --> 04:11:23.225
parallelized. It just happens that this
is more efficient and works better.

04:11:23.315 --> 04:11:26.725
- And it very well could be that the
LLM, the neural networks, the way

04:11:26.766 --> 04:11:30.985
we architect them now is just
a small component of the

04:11:32.326 --> 04:11:33.786
system that leads to singularity.

04:11:33.796 --> 04:11:37.716
- If you think of it in 100
years, I think society can be

04:11:37.725 --> 04:11:41.195
changed more with more compute
and intelligence because of

04:11:41.225 --> 04:11:45.026
autonomy. But looking
at this, what are the

04:11:45.046 --> 04:11:48.645
things from the Industrial Revolution that we
remember? We remember the engine, which is

04:11:48.706 --> 04:11:51.836
probably the equivalent
of the computer in this.

04:11:51.846 --> 04:11:55.746
But there's a lot of other physical
transformations that people are aware

04:11:55.826 --> 04:12:00.416
of, like the cotton gin and
all these things, these

04:12:01.485 --> 04:12:04.836
machines that are still known:
air conditioning, refrigerators.

04:12:04.846 --> 04:12:07.895
Some of these things from
AI will still be known.

04:12:08.766 --> 04:12:12.725
The word "transformer" could still
be known. I would guess that deep

04:12:12.766 --> 04:12:16.645
learning is definitely still known, but
the transformer might be evolved away

04:12:16.766 --> 04:12:24.086
from in 100 years with AGI researchers
everywhere. But I think deep

04:12:24.126 --> 04:12:28.565
learning is likely to be a
term that is remembered.

04:12:28.586 --> 04:12:32.465
- And I wonder what the air conditioning and
refrigeration of the future is that AI brings.

04:12:32.526 --> 04:12:36.286
If we travel forward 100 years from
now, we transport there right now,

04:12:36.326 --> 04:12:40.225
what do you think is different? How do
you think the world looks different?

04:12:40.286 --> 04:12:44.186
First of all, do you think there are
humans? Do you think there are robots

04:12:44.206 --> 04:12:46.626
everywhere walking around?

04:12:46.666 --> 04:12:49.395
- I do think specialized robots,
for sure, for certain tasks.

04:12:49.446 --> 04:12:50.225
- Humanoid form?

04:12:50.326 --> 04:12:54.305
- Maybe half-humanoid. We'll see.

04:12:54.326 --> 04:12:57.826
I think for certain things, yes, there
will be humanoid robots because it's

04:12:57.905 --> 04:13:01.786
just amenable for the environment.
But for certain tasks,

04:13:01.846 --> 04:13:05.526
it might make sense. What's harder
to imagine is how we interact

04:13:05.626 --> 04:13:09.485
with the devices and what humans
do with devices. Well, I mean,

04:13:09.526 --> 04:13:13.466
I'm pretty sure it will probably
not be the cellphone or the laptop.

04:13:13.506 --> 04:13:16.186
Will it be implants?

04:13:16.225 --> 04:13:18.496
- I mean, it has to be
brain-computer interfaces, right?

04:13:18.546 --> 04:13:22.596
I mean, 100 years from now, given
the progress we're seeing now—

04:13:22.596 --> 04:13:28.246
there has to be... unless
there's legitimately a complete

04:13:29.346 --> 04:13:32.706
alteration of how we
interact with reality.

04:13:33.145 --> 04:13:36.996
- On the other hand, cars are
older than 100 years, right? And

04:13:37.026 --> 04:13:40.695
it's still the same interface.
We haven't replaced cars with

04:13:40.725 --> 04:13:44.466
something else. We just made them
better, but it's still a steering wheel,

04:13:44.546 --> 04:13:45.485
still wheels, you know?

04:13:45.606 --> 04:13:48.366
- I think we'll still carry around
a physical brick of compute

04:13:48.426 --> 04:13:52.405
because people want some ability
to have a private... Like, you

04:13:52.426 --> 04:13:56.186
might not engage with it as much as a
phone, but having private information

04:13:56.206 --> 04:13:59.086
that is yours as an interface
between the rest of the

04:13:59.126 --> 04:14:03.076
internet, I think that will
still exist. It might not

04:14:03.106 --> 04:14:06.916
look like an iPhone and it might be
used a lot less, but I still expect

04:14:06.926 --> 04:14:08.535
people to carry things around.

04:14:08.565 --> 04:14:11.516
- Why do you think the smartphone
is the embodiment of private?

04:14:11.645 --> 04:14:15.535
There's a camera on it. There's—

04:14:15.535 --> 04:14:19.456
- Private for you, like encrypted
messages, encrypted photos...

04:14:19.466 --> 04:14:20.866
know what your life is.

04:14:22.366 --> 04:14:25.966
I guess it's a question of how optimistic
on brain-machine interfaces you are.

04:14:26.046 --> 04:14:29.826
Is all that just going to be stored
in the cloud? Your whole calendar?

04:14:30.206 --> 04:14:33.905
It's hard to think about processing

04:14:33.985 --> 04:14:37.895
all the information that
we can process visually

04:14:37.946 --> 04:14:41.606
through brain-machine interfaces
presenting something like a

04:14:41.666 --> 04:14:44.246
calendar or something to you.

04:14:44.255 --> 04:14:49.145
It's hard to just think about knowing,
without looking, your email inbox.

04:14:49.166 --> 04:14:53.126
Like you signal to a computer and
then you just know your email inbox.

04:14:53.186 --> 04:14:56.866
Is that something that the human
brain can handle being piped

04:14:56.926 --> 04:15:03.006
into it non-visually? I don't know
exactly how those transformations happen.

04:15:03.016 --> 04:15:05.485
Humans aren't changing in 100 years.

04:15:05.565 --> 04:15:09.225
I think agency and community are
things that people actually want.

04:15:09.246 --> 04:15:10.346
- A local community, yeah.

04:15:10.366 --> 04:15:14.255
- People you are close to, being
able to do things with them

04:15:14.286 --> 04:15:22.186
and being able to ascribe meaning to
your life and being able to do things.

04:15:22.326 --> 04:15:26.166
In 100 years, I don't think
that human biology is

04:15:26.225 --> 04:15:30.206
changing away from those on a
time scale that we can discuss.

04:15:30.246 --> 04:15:34.086
And I think that UBI
does not solve agency.

04:15:34.546 --> 04:15:38.366
I do expect mass wealth, and
I hope that it has spread

04:15:38.426 --> 04:15:42.405
so that the average life looks
very different in 100 years.

04:15:42.426 --> 04:15:46.266
But that's still a lot to happen.
If you think about countries

04:15:46.326 --> 04:15:50.305
that are early in their
development process to getting

04:15:50.426 --> 04:15:55.635
access to computing and internet, to
build all the infrastructure and have

04:15:56.885 --> 04:16:00.416
policy that shares one
nation's wealth with

04:16:00.446 --> 04:16:04.346
another is... I think it's
an optimistic view to see

04:16:04.405 --> 04:16:05.946
all that happening in 100 years-

04:16:05.956 --> 04:16:09.946
...while they are still
independent entities and not just

04:16:10.006 --> 04:16:13.166
like absorbed into some
international order by force.

04:16:13.206 --> 04:16:17.676
- But there could be just better,
more elaborate, more effective

04:16:17.676 --> 04:16:21.606
... social support systems
that help alleviate

04:16:21.686 --> 04:16:25.206
some levels of basic suffering
from the world. You know, the

04:16:25.246 --> 04:16:29.086
transformation of society where a lot
of jobs are lost in the short term, I

04:16:29.106 --> 04:16:32.786
think we have to really remember
that each individual job that's lost

04:16:33.725 --> 04:16:36.766
is a human being who's
suffering. That's like a

04:16:37.846 --> 04:16:41.706
... When jobs are lost, the
scale is a real tragedy. You can

04:16:41.766 --> 04:16:45.746
make all kinds of arguments about
economics or how it's all going to

04:16:45.786 --> 04:16:49.536
be okay. It's good for the GDP,
there's going to be new jobs

04:16:49.626 --> 04:16:53.426
created. Fundamentally at the
individual level for that

04:16:53.485 --> 04:16:57.385
human being, that's real
suffering. That's a real

04:16:57.466 --> 04:17:01.385
personal sort of tragedy. And
we have to not forget that as

04:17:01.426 --> 04:17:05.274
the technologies are being
developed. And also my hope

04:17:05.334 --> 04:17:08.584
for all the AI slop we're seeing is

04:17:08.674 --> 04:17:13.334
that there will be a greater and
greater premium for the fundamental

04:17:14.394 --> 04:17:17.554
aspects of the human
experience that are in-person.

04:17:17.574 --> 04:17:22.894
The things that we all... Like seeing
each other, talking together in-person.

04:17:22.954 --> 04:17:26.894
- The next few years are definitely
going to be an increased value on

04:17:26.954 --> 04:17:32.194
physical goods and events— ...and
even more pressure on slop.

04:17:32.214 --> 04:17:35.154
So it'll be... the slop is only starting.

04:17:35.174 --> 04:17:38.734
The next few years will be more and
more diverse ...versions of slop.

04:17:38.774 --> 04:17:40.164
- They would be drowning
in slop. Is that what—

04:17:40.174 --> 04:17:44.114
- So I'm hoping that society
drowns in slop enough to snap

04:17:44.634 --> 04:17:48.474
out of it and be like, "We can't deal
with it. It just doesn't matter."

04:17:48.534 --> 04:17:53.614
And then, the physical has
such a higher premium on it.

04:17:53.654 --> 04:17:57.594
- Even like classic examples, I
honestly think this is true,

04:17:57.654 --> 04:18:01.494
and I think we will get tired of it.
We are already kind of tired of it.

04:18:01.594 --> 04:18:05.394
I mean, even art. I don't think art
will go away. You have paintings,

04:18:05.414 --> 04:18:09.214
physical paintings. There's
more value, not just

04:18:09.274 --> 04:18:13.054
monetary value, but just more
value appreciation for the actual

04:18:13.154 --> 04:18:16.254
painting than a photocopy of that
painting. It could be a perfect digital

04:18:16.794 --> 04:18:20.614
reprint, but there is something when you go to a
museum and you look at that art and you see the

04:18:20.654 --> 04:18:24.434
real thing and you just think,
"Okay. A human." It's like a craft.

04:18:24.574 --> 04:18:28.134
You have like an appreciation for that. And
I think the same is true for writing, for

04:18:28.214 --> 04:18:32.004
talking, for any type of experience...

04:18:32.194 --> 04:18:36.174
I do unfortunately think it
will be like a dichotomy,

04:18:36.214 --> 04:18:40.034
like a fork where some
things will be automated.

04:18:40.054 --> 04:18:43.954
Like, you know, there are not as many paintings
as there used to be, you know, 200 years ago.

04:18:43.974 --> 04:18:47.934
There are more photographs,
more photocopies. But at the

04:18:47.994 --> 04:18:51.914
same time, it won't go away.
There will be value in that.

04:18:51.954 --> 04:18:55.874
I think the difference will just be,
you know, what's the proportion of

04:18:55.934 --> 04:19:00.974
that. But personally, I have a hard time
reading things where I obviously see

04:19:00.994 --> 04:19:04.894
it's obviously AI generated.
I'm sorry. It might—it

04:19:04.934 --> 04:19:08.954
might be really good information there,
but I'm just like, "Nah, not for me."

04:19:08.964 --> 04:19:12.714
- I think eventually they'll fool
you, and it'll be on platforms that

04:19:12.874 --> 04:19:16.794
give ways of verifying or
building trust. So you will trust

04:19:16.854 --> 04:19:21.694
that Lex is not AI generated, having been
here. So then you have trust in this

04:19:21.794 --> 04:19:25.534
channel. But it's harder for new
people who don't have that trust.

04:19:25.574 --> 04:19:29.414
- Well, that will get interesting
because I think fundamentally it's a

04:19:29.494 --> 04:19:33.394
solvable problem by having trust

04:19:33.474 --> 04:19:37.184
in certain outlets that they won't do it,
but it's all going to be trust-based.

04:19:37.214 --> 04:19:41.174
There will be systems to authorize, "Okay, this
is real. This is not real." There will be some

04:19:41.234 --> 04:19:45.154
telltale signs where you can obviously
tell this is AI generated and

04:19:45.194 --> 04:19:49.143
this is not. But some will be so
good that it's hard to tell, and

04:19:49.154 --> 04:19:54.534
then you have to trust. And well, that will
get interesting and a bit problematic.

04:19:54.574 --> 04:19:57.934
- The extreme case of this is to
watermark all human content.

04:19:57.994 --> 04:20:02.684
So all photos that we take on our own
have some watermark until they are edited

04:20:02.714 --> 04:20:06.074
or something like this. And software
can manage communications with the

04:20:06.954 --> 04:20:11.124
device manufacturer- device
manufacturer to maintain human editing—

04:20:11.154 --> 04:20:15.714
which is the opposite of the discussion
to try to watermark AI images. And then

04:20:16.654 --> 04:20:20.923
you can make a Google image that has a watermark
and use a different Google tool to remove it.

04:20:20.934 --> 04:20:23.504
- Yep. It's going to be an
arms race, basically.

04:20:23.654 --> 04:20:26.914
- And we've been mostly focusing
on the positive aspects of

04:20:26.974 --> 04:20:30.794
AI. All the capabilities
that we've been talking

04:20:30.834 --> 04:20:34.774
about can be used to destabilize
human civilization with even just

04:20:35.614 --> 04:20:41.494
relatively dumb AI applied at scale,
and then further, superintelligent

04:20:41.534 --> 04:20:45.134
AI systems. Of course, there's
the sort of doomer take

04:20:45.894 --> 04:20:49.664
that's important to consider
as we develop these

04:20:49.694 --> 04:20:53.334
technologies. What gives you
hope about the future of human

04:20:53.414 --> 04:20:58.994
civilization, given everything we've been
talking about? Are we going to be okay?

04:20:59.094 --> 04:21:02.814
- I think we will. I'm
definitely a worrier, both

04:21:02.894 --> 04:21:10.014
about AI and non-AI things. But humans do
tend to find a way. I think that's what

04:21:10.054 --> 04:21:13.954
humans are built for: to have
community and find a way to figure out

04:21:13.974 --> 04:21:17.794
problems. That's what has gotten us
to this point. And to think that

04:21:19.054 --> 04:21:22.954
the AI opportunity and related
technologies is really

04:21:22.994 --> 04:21:27.414
big. And I think that there's big
social and political problems to

04:21:28.274 --> 04:21:32.214
help everybody understand that. And I
think that's what we're staring at a

04:21:32.274 --> 04:21:35.834
lot of right now, is like the world
is a scary place, and AI is a very

04:21:35.894 --> 04:21:38.914
uncertain thing. And it
takes a lot of work that is

04:21:40.074 --> 04:21:43.714
not necessarily building things.
It's like telling people and

04:21:43.774 --> 04:21:46.954
understanding people, that the
people building AI are historically

04:21:46.994 --> 04:21:50.094
not motivated or wanting to do.

04:21:50.114 --> 04:21:53.974
But it is something that is
probably doable. It just will

04:21:54.014 --> 04:21:57.554
take longer than people want.
And we have to go through that

04:21:57.754 --> 04:22:01.414
long period of like hard, distraught AI

04:22:01.474 --> 04:22:04.894
discussions if we want to
have the lasting benefits.

04:22:04.914 --> 04:22:07.854
- Yeah. Through that process, I'm
especially excited that we get a

04:22:07.894 --> 04:22:11.314
chance to better understand ourselves,

04:22:12.334 --> 04:22:15.294
us at the individual level as
humans and at the civilization

04:22:15.794 --> 04:22:19.624
level, and answer some of the
big mysteries, like what is

04:22:19.674 --> 04:22:22.804
this whole consciousness thing going on

04:22:22.854 --> 04:22:26.734
here? It seems to be truly special.
Like, there's a real miracle in

04:22:26.774 --> 04:22:30.234
our mind. And AI puts a mirror
to ourselves and we get

04:22:30.274 --> 04:22:34.194
to answer some of the big
questions about like, what is this

04:22:34.254 --> 04:22:35.714
whole thing going on here?

04:22:35.734 --> 04:22:39.694
- Well, one thing about that is also what
I do think makes us very different

04:22:39.714 --> 04:22:43.674
from AI and why I don't
worry about AI taking over

04:22:43.754 --> 04:22:47.634
is, like you said, consciousness. We
humans, we decide what we want to

04:22:47.654 --> 04:22:51.074
do. AI in its current
implementation, I can't see it

04:22:51.114 --> 04:22:55.034
changing. You have to tell
it what to do. And so you

04:22:55.114 --> 04:22:59.074
have still the agency. It doesn't
take the agency from you because

04:22:59.154 --> 04:23:02.914
it becomes a tool. You can think of
it as a tool. You tell it what to

04:23:02.954 --> 04:23:06.822
do. It will be more automatic
than other previous tools.

04:23:06.862 --> 04:23:10.822
It's certainly more powerful than a
hammer, it can figure things out, but

04:23:10.882 --> 04:23:14.862
it's still you in charge, right? So
the AI is not in charge, you're in

04:23:14.882 --> 04:23:17.732
charge. You tell the AI what to
do and it's doing it for you.

04:23:17.782 --> 04:23:21.622
- So in the post-singularity,
post-apocalyptic war between

04:23:21.681 --> 04:23:25.442
humans and machines, you're saying
humans are worth fighting for?

04:23:27.181 --> 04:23:31.931
- 100%. I mean, this is... The
movie Terminator, they made in

04:23:31.942 --> 04:23:34.152
the '80s, essentially,
and I do think, well,

04:23:35.502 --> 04:23:39.422
the only thing I can see
going wrong is, of course, if

04:23:39.502 --> 04:23:43.502
things are explicitly programmed to do
the thing that is harmful, basically.

04:23:43.562 --> 04:23:49.442
- I think actually in that, in a Terminator
type of setup, I think humans win.

04:23:49.502 --> 04:23:55.802
I think we're too clever. It's hard to
explain how we figure it out, but we do.

04:23:56.761 --> 04:24:02.822
And we'll probably be using local LLMs, open
source LLMs to help fight the machines.

04:24:04.002 --> 04:24:07.882
I apologize for the
ridiculousness. Like I said,

04:24:07.922 --> 04:24:11.601
Nathan already knows I've been a big
fan of his for a long time. Been

04:24:11.662 --> 04:24:15.562
a big fan of yours, Sebastian, for a long
time, so it's an honor to finally meet

04:24:15.622 --> 04:24:19.542
you. Thank you for everything you put out into the
world. Thank you for the excellent books you're

04:24:19.562 --> 04:24:26.062
writing. Thank you for teaching us. And
thank you for talking today. This was fun.

04:24:26.082 --> 04:24:30.622
- Thank you for inviting us here and having
this human connection, which is actually-

04:24:30.642 --> 04:24:32.832
- Extremely valuable- human connection.

04:24:33.922 --> 04:24:37.521
Thanks for listening to this conversation
with Sebastian Raschka and Nathan

04:24:37.601 --> 04:24:40.982
Lambert. To support this podcast,
please check out our sponsors in the

04:24:41.002 --> 04:24:44.521
description, where you can also
find links to contact me, ask

04:24:44.582 --> 04:24:47.862
questions, give feedback
and so on. And now

04:24:48.521 --> 04:24:52.482
let me leave you with some
words from Albert Einstein.

04:24:52.492 --> 04:24:56.312
"It is not that I'm so
smart, but I stay with the

04:24:56.382 --> 04:25:04.302
questions much longer." Thank you for
listening, and hope to see you next time.

